a little context for the Library

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:59.680
of Congress's commitment

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:03.170
to architectural
and design heritage.

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:06.180
The Library is both the oldest
federal cultural institution

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:09.740
in the United States and
the world's largest library.

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:14.020
Since its founding in 1800, its
collections, which are universal

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:19.620
in subject matter, have grown
to over 164 million items,

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:23.880
stored on more than
838 miles of shelving.

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:26.390
The collections include
more than 38 million books

00:06:26.390 --> 00:06:31.820
and other print materials, 36
-- or, 3.6 million recordings,

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:36.780
14 million manuscripts,
photographs, 5.5 million maps,

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:39.380
8.1 million pieces
of sheet music,

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:42.860
and 70 million manuscript
sheets.

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:45.800
What's germane to our
discussions today is the fact

00:06:45.800 --> 00:06:48.340
that the subjects of
architecture, design,

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:50.410
and engineering are
woven into all

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:52.800
of these different collections.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:54.610
However, the largest
concentration

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:57.810
of design sketches,
presentation renderings,

00:06:57.810 --> 00:07:00.370
and technical construction
drawings are in our prints

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:03.710
and photographs division, which
is also home to the Center

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:07.030
for Architecture
Design and Engineering.

00:07:07.030 --> 00:07:09.730
The division's extensive
holdings include original

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:13.180
designs by many of the most
distinguished designers

00:07:13.180 --> 00:07:15.010
who worked in the United States,

00:07:15.010 --> 00:07:18.810
including Benjamin Henry
Latrobe, Robert Fulton,

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:22.940
Richard Morris Hunt, Cass
Gilbert, Frank Lloyd Wright,

00:07:22.940 --> 00:07:26.980
Charles and Ray Eames, Raymond
Loewy, Paul Rudolph, and,

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:30.800
of course, I.M. Pei, just
to name a few of the giants

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:33.610
that live here at the
Library of Congress.

00:07:33.610 --> 00:07:35.730
We are also fortunate
in having the archives

00:07:35.730 --> 00:07:39.240
of two prominent
professional organizations,

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:41.430
The American Institute
of Architects,

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.910
and The Engineering
Society's Library.

