00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:27.760
Let me start with a brief story

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:30.940
about the first major
restoration

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:34.580
of the United States Capitol
Dome that we recently completed,

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:37.490
the first in a generation.

00:09:37.490 --> 00:09:40.280
You may have seen the
scaffolding going up

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:45.720
or coming down, and we completed
that terrific job in January

00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:48.760
of this year, just before --
or, December of this year --

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:51.770
last year, just before the
Presidential Inauguration.

00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:53.510
The Dome, as you may know,

00:09:53.510 --> 00:09:58.720
is made of nearly nine million
pounds of cast iron girders,

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:01.950
plates, columns, and
cast iron ornaments.

00:10:01.950 --> 00:10:05.130
Even the pedestal
upon which the Statue

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:08.610
of Freedom sits is
made of cast iron.

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:12.060
And as we were gearing up
for this restoration effort,

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:16.040
we used CAD drawings, of
course, of the Capitol Dome

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:20.240
that we had prepared
many years before

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:22.240
to help us develop
the scope of work,

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:26.310
to help us document the
more than 1300 cracks,

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:30.390
and deficiencies, and
repairs in the cast iron

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:32.970
that we were about to undertake.

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:36.120
And these digital assets,
or these CAD drawings,

00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:40.220
were incredibly helpful
to the work we were doing.

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:44.280
But they didn't contain
the important stuff,

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:47.340
the important details
of the fasteners,

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:51.830
the connection points, and
all of the cast iron parts.

00:10:51.830 --> 00:10:57.670
It wasn't exactly like working
with a virtual erector set

00:10:57.670 --> 00:11:02.690
that showed how all of these
hundreds of thousands of pieces

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:06.520
that fit together to
make up this dome.

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:10.320
You can't necessarily see them
all, either, the fasteners

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:12.920
and the connection points,
because they're hidden.

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:16.500
They're inside spaces
that haven't been --

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:20.570
haven't seen the light of
day in more than 160 years,

00:11:20.570 --> 00:11:22.930
in the gutter systems,
and balustrades,

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:27.030
and those connection points
are what are important to us,

00:11:27.030 --> 00:11:30.200
and what were important
to our contractor.

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:35.090
And so, despite the amazing
technology that was available

00:11:35.090 --> 00:11:37.650
to us, the most important tool

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:44.710
in this restoration project
was the roughly 200 original

00:11:44.710 --> 00:11:50.500
watercolor drawings from Thomas
Ustick Walter in the 1850s,

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:54.770
two of which you can see
right there on the screen.

00:11:54.770 --> 00:11:58.640
Thomas Ustick Walter was the
fourth Architect of the Capitol,

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:01.180
and his drawings were tremendous

00:12:01.180 --> 00:12:05.800
in documenting exactly how
everything would fit together

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:08.390
back in 1865.

00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:11.610
By sharing these drawings with
our contractors, they were able

00:12:11.610 --> 00:12:16.210
to develop their means and
methods by which they would go

00:12:16.210 --> 00:12:19.800
about disassembling all of
the pieces of this dome,

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:24.010
restoring them, and then
putting them all back together.

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:28.070
And that reduced our risk
immensely on the job.

00:12:28.070 --> 00:12:31.880
They were particularly
helpful on the balustrades,

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:34.900
some of which you can see
here, essentially serving

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:37.420
as a paint-by-numbers kit.

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:41.120
And it's amazing,
the level of detail

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:45.570
of these drawings
back 160 years ago.

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:49.100
I could spend the next 30
minutes talking about the state

00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:53.450
of our design drawings today
produced by our engineers

00:12:53.450 --> 00:12:58.230
and architects, and how
we can draw an outline

00:12:58.230 --> 00:13:02.900
of this particular dome, make
a bubble around it, and say,

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:05.830
"The contractor needs to prepare
shop drawings for all of this."

00:13:05.830 --> 00:13:10.760
Well, back in the 1860s, the
Architect of the Capitol did all

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:15.280
of that, and Walter made all
of those connection points.

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:17.970
And they -- in fact, we
don't have shop drawings,

00:13:17.970 --> 00:13:23.870
because his design documents
were essentially the shop

00:13:23.870 --> 00:13:25.170
drawings for that.

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:28.070
But that is for a
different gathering.

00:13:28.070 --> 00:13:30.950
Today, fortunately,
we are blessed

00:13:30.950 --> 00:13:34.200
to have some incredibly
archivists at the Architect

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:39.110
of the Capitol that were able
to pull these drawings together,

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:43.310
the ones from Thomas Ustick
Walter, more than 200 of them.

00:13:43.310 --> 00:13:46.630
They were stored on a
network drive, just a couple

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:50.320
of hundred gigabytes of
data that had been stored

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:54.110
on that drive for a
number of decades.

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:56.670
While we were working
on the dome restoration,

00:13:56.670 --> 00:14:00.620
we also took the time
to pay it forward

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:03.700
to our future colleagues,
as well.

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:09.050
We used BIM 360 to document
all of the work that we did,

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:12.780
whether it was including
the photographs

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:16.550
of existing conditions once
we took nearly 1/4 inch

00:14:16.550 --> 00:14:19.700
of paint off the dome --
lead-based paint, that is,

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:22.260
documenting the conditions
that we found,

00:14:22.260 --> 00:14:24.620
documenting the original
repairs,

00:14:24.620 --> 00:14:29.750
or repairs that were done in
the 1959 and 1960, that is.

00:14:29.750 --> 00:14:32.720
And paid it forward
for our colleagues

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:38.290
that might be undertaking
similar work some 50 or 75 years

00:14:38.290 --> 00:14:39.820
from now, as they go

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:44.380
about restoring the
Capitol Dome once again.

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:46.510
In the short term,
we're confident

00:14:46.510 --> 00:14:50.910
that we can mine this
data to diagnose problems

00:14:50.910 --> 00:14:55.180
that we may have with the dome
and our maintenance activities,

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:58.670
and in the longer term, of
course, it will be useful.

00:14:58.670 --> 00:15:03.860
This BIM 360 model will
certainly be useful only if it's

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:07.790
in a format that can be
assessed by future Architects

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:12.870
of the Capitol, again,
50 or 75 years from now.

00:15:12.870 --> 00:15:15.610
And as much as we want
to cling to paper,

00:15:15.610 --> 00:15:21.780
it's just not realistic, as you
know, as it won't last forever.

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:27.130
So we need to capture documents
in their born digital formats,

00:15:27.130 --> 00:15:29.940
and certainly, we're
all here today wrestling

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:31.600
with the same questions.

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:34.010
What's important to keep?

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:37.160
What are the challenges of
keeping it in perpetuity?

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.970
How do we protect the digital
record for the long-term.

00:15:40.970 --> 00:15:45.690
And perhaps most importantly for
me, anyway, how do we make sure

00:15:45.690 --> 00:15:48.240
that our colleagues
in the future,

00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:51.930
those that might undertake
the repair and restoration

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:55.810
of this great Capitol Dome
50 or 75 years from now --

00:15:55.810 --> 00:15:59.870
how do we make sure
they can use it?

00:15:59.870 --> 00:16:04.650
Well, I hope by the end of
the day, you can figure all

00:16:04.650 --> 00:16:06.030
of that out [laughter].

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:10.270
That's your challenge, and
I'm delighted to be here.

00:16:10.270 --> 00:16:11.820
I hope you have a great day.

00:16:11.820 --> 00:16:14.970
I look forward to hearing
the results of your work,

00:16:14.970 --> 00:16:19.180
and I'm quite certain you'll
be able to figure that out

00:16:19.180 --> 00:16:20.480
by the end of the day.

00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:24.510
So good luck, have a
great day, and thank you.

00:16:24.510 --> 00:16:33.000
[ Applause ]

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.300
&gt;&gt; Kate Murray: So
thank you, Mr. Ayers.

00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:35.600
That's a bit of a challenge.

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:37.820
I think we'll do our best
by the end of the day,

00:16:37.820 --> 00:16:39.490
and thanks to Mark
Sweeney, also,

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:41.880
for those wonderful
welcoming remarks.

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:44.170
So we're going to start with our
first session, which is going

00:16:44.170 --> 00:16:47.400
to be Aliza Leventhal, Katie
Pierce Meyer, and Tim Walsh,

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:49.930
and they're going to
give us an ADE primer.

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:52.230
Thank you.

00:16:55.730 --> 00:16:57.030
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer:
Good morning, everyone,

00:16:57.030 --> 00:16:58.690
and thank you all for coming.

00:16:58.690 --> 00:17:01.150
I am Katie Pierce Meyer.

00:17:01.150 --> 00:17:03.590
My colleagues, Tim Walsh
and Aliza Leventhal,

00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:06.190
and I are going -- are
very pleased to be asked

00:17:06.190 --> 00:17:08.950
to provide an ADE
formats primer.

00:17:08.950 --> 00:17:11.290
Essentially, what we're
going to do is give a --

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:13.070
you about a one-hour
introduction

00:17:13.070 --> 00:17:16.460
that covers the history and
preservation issues associated

00:17:16.460 --> 00:17:19.980
with architecture design and
engineering and digital content.

00:17:19.980 --> 00:17:23.640
We'll each take on a particular
period, identify key trends

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:25.710
and preservation concerns.

00:17:25.710 --> 00:17:28.200
I should note that the
three of us come with a bit

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:31.100
of an architecture bias,
but we're very interested

00:17:31.100 --> 00:17:35.640
in exploring the connections to
and overlaps with other fields.

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:39.520
So, I will introduce the early
years, provide a little bit

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:41.820
of a background on
early CAD development

00:17:41.820 --> 00:17:44.310
from the 1960s through
the 1980s.

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:47.630
My colleague Tim Walsh will
take on the 1990s and 2000s,

00:17:47.630 --> 00:17:50.380
a very active period in
technology development,

00:17:50.380 --> 00:17:53.190
and increasingly complex
preservation challenges.

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:56.080
And finally, Aliza Leventhal
will discuss software --

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:58.360
current software and
preservation landscape,

00:17:58.360 --> 00:18:01.140
setting us up for the
remaining sessions today.

00:18:01.140 --> 00:18:05.570
But first, let's start
with a look back.

00:18:05.570 --> 00:18:08.440
So the use of computer-aided
design applications

00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:11.050
in architecture trailed
similar implementations

00:18:11.050 --> 00:18:13.410
within engineering
and manufacturing.

00:18:13.410 --> 00:18:17.560
Stimulated by mandates from the
U.S. Air Force in the 19650s,

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:18.860
airplane engineers

00:18:18.860 --> 00:18:21.060
and manufacturers were
early adopters and testers

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:23.520
of computer technology
for design.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:27.280
Computer-aided design and
drafting, manufacturing tools,

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:29.910
and techniques were developed
to use machines as a means

00:18:29.910 --> 00:18:32.750
of increasing speed
and precision,

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:35.660
while decreasing
production costs.

00:18:35.660 --> 00:18:37.580
In the aerospace industry,

00:18:37.580 --> 00:18:40.590
automated drafting tools were
widely used in the 1950s,

00:18:40.590 --> 00:18:42.470
and the needs of
manufacturers resulted

00:18:42.470 --> 00:18:46.520
in innovative software
programs for project management,

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:49.220
data collection,
and engineering.

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:51.370
Research and development
intensified

00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:54.180
in the academic community,
however, in the 1960s.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:58.120
Ivan Sutherland, his 1963
electrical engineering doctoral

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:00.010
dissertation, and
his development

00:19:00.010 --> 00:19:02.950
of the sketchpad system
are widely credited

00:19:02.950 --> 00:19:04.850
with being a significant
contribution

00:19:04.850 --> 00:19:07.400
to computer graphics
programming.

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:10.770
Sutherland was working at
MIT, along with Steven Coons,

00:19:10.770 --> 00:19:14.050
to rethink the interaction
between humans and computers.

00:19:14.050 --> 00:19:17.170
He and Coons envisioned a
computer-aided design system

00:19:17.170 --> 00:19:19.820
that would allow multiple
designers to interact

00:19:19.820 --> 00:19:22.850
with the system simultaneously
to communicate effectively

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:25.380
with each other, and to,
quote, "use the creative

00:19:25.380 --> 00:19:29.080
and imaginative powers of
the man, and the analytical

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:32.510
and computational
powers of the machine."

00:19:32.510 --> 00:19:34.220
While these researchers
were approaching a problem

00:19:34.220 --> 00:19:36.740
from an engineering perspective,

00:19:36.740 --> 00:19:38.510
their work demonstrated
possibilities

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:40.130
for computer graphics
that held promise

00:19:40.130 --> 00:19:42.350
for applications
to architecture.

00:19:42.350 --> 00:19:43.650
The idea was to create, move,

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:47.790
copy geographical
entities using a light pen.

00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:51.710
By the 1960s, several
conferences were organized

00:19:51.710 --> 00:19:54.930
to bring professionals, kind
of like we are here today,

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:57.780
to discuss the possibility and
implications of using computers

00:19:57.780 --> 00:19:59.490
in architectural practice.

00:19:59.490 --> 00:20:02.670
The goals of the conferences
and associated publications were

00:20:02.670 --> 00:20:05.320
to present information
about current efforts

00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:08.390
in using computers in
architecture and related fields,

00:20:08.390 --> 00:20:09.980
and to open up a discussion

00:20:09.980 --> 00:20:12.650
about the potential use
for creative design.

00:20:12.650 --> 00:20:15.630
There were also conversations
about the role of the architect,

00:20:15.630 --> 00:20:18.390
and what that looks like if
you start adopting computers

00:20:18.390 --> 00:20:19.690
in your practice.

00:20:19.690 --> 00:20:21.730
So there's a little bit of
an apprehension on the part

00:20:21.730 --> 00:20:24.480
of some architects about
embracing computer technology,

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:27.870
because of the uncertainty of
the value of the technology,

00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:31.360
and concerns about potentially
changing their role and status.

00:20:31.360 --> 00:20:33.160
A common theme in
the conferences

00:20:33.160 --> 00:20:37.680
and publications focused
on educating practitioners

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:40.960
about computers and addressing
their role as architects.

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:45.850
Now, in the 1970s,
we saw the beginning

00:20:45.850 --> 00:20:49.430
of the first commercial programs
available to the market.

00:20:49.430 --> 00:20:52.420
These are just a few examples
of those that were available.

00:20:52.420 --> 00:20:54.620
They were, however,
very expensive.

00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:59.040
In his 1977 book,
"Computer-Aided Design,"

00:20:59.040 --> 00:21:01.670
William Mitchell predicted that
developments in architecture

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:04.500
and computer technology
had finally reached a point

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:08.560
where the tools would, quote,

00:21:08.560 --> 00:21:10.880
"radically transform the
practice of architecture."

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:12.180
So what was coming
down the line --

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:16.050
a lot of things regarding
personal computing,

00:21:16.050 --> 00:21:20.740
and just a lot of changes
within computer technology

00:21:20.740 --> 00:21:22.740
that were going to make
these programs a little more

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:25.490
accessible, and, as
we'll see in a moment,

00:21:25.490 --> 00:21:27.340
change just the nature
of the field.

00:21:27.340 --> 00:21:30.760
So the book was written
as an introductory guide

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:33.740
for architects, students,
and computer technologists,

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:36.780
to try to bring them together
to think about the developments

00:21:36.780 --> 00:21:40.300
in computer technology, and what
was possible in architecture.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:42.230
So he encouraged
thinking about design

00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:47.040
as an information processing
task, in which one conceives

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:48.950
of the mechanics
of managing data.

00:21:48.950 --> 00:21:51.160
So it was about data
even in the early days.

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:55.020
He was concerned about
the seeming hostility

00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:58.730
from architects, their
ignorance of the potentials

00:21:58.730 --> 00:22:03.740
of the computer technology, but
mostly the financial constraints

00:22:03.740 --> 00:22:05.040
of relatively small firms.

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:08.400
It was -- he noted that the
challenges were particularly

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:09.800
great as compared
to other fields,

00:22:09.800 --> 00:22:12.520
where computer-aided design
was implemented more readily --

00:22:12.520 --> 00:22:15.700
specifically, automotive
and aerospace engineering.

00:22:15.700 --> 00:22:19.210
One point he made was that the
relatively small size of firms

00:22:19.210 --> 00:22:21.190
and the economic
investment necessary

00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:24.290
to bring computer-aided
design to such firms meant

00:22:24.290 --> 00:22:26.680
that the adoption of
the technology needed

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:29.410
to be perceived as necessary
or valuable to the industry,

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:31.800
not just to individual firms
or individual practitioners.

00:22:31.800 --> 00:22:35.300
It needed to be sort
of a broadly-applied --

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:39.390
to have real value, and to be
perceived as having real value.

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:41.340
So what are some

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:43.540
of the preservation
challenges from this period?

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:46.410
You know, I've introduced
kind of a lot of big ideas

00:22:46.410 --> 00:22:49.690
around what was going
on in those early days.

00:22:49.690 --> 00:22:53.840
There's not as much in the
way of -- as far as I know,

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:57.410
large quantities of
records available,

00:22:57.410 --> 00:22:58.710
in terms of the technology.

00:22:58.710 --> 00:23:01.670
But there are some, and I think
identifying where those are,

00:23:01.670 --> 00:23:05.760
where different repositories
might have different things

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:08.120
that might help us preserve what
was tried, what was debated,

00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:11.380
and what was presented
to various audiences,

00:23:11.380 --> 00:23:14.340
what has value, both for the
history of design records,

00:23:14.340 --> 00:23:16.900
but also for the history
of computer technology.

00:23:16.900 --> 00:23:18.660
Because some really interesting
things were happening during

00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:21.180
this period, and they're just
sort of blending, and merging,

00:23:21.180 --> 00:23:25.650
and borrowing ideas and
technologies from other fields.

00:23:25.650 --> 00:23:26.980
So looking at that, I think,

00:23:26.980 --> 00:23:29.200
is one of the things
that's really valuable.

00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:33.220
There's also the experimentation
and adaptation to new markets.

00:23:33.220 --> 00:23:36.320
Some of the technologies
were created for one market

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:38.180
and then used within another,
and I think that's the kind

00:23:38.180 --> 00:23:40.490
of thing that we might
want to be preserving

00:23:40.490 --> 00:23:41.790
and providing access to.

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:43.740
So, moving on to the 1980s --

00:23:43.740 --> 00:23:47.240
the 1980s can really
be characterized

00:23:47.240 --> 00:23:49.480
by a proliferation of programs.

00:23:49.480 --> 00:23:51.590
As I mentioned earlier,
there's sort of a change

00:23:51.590 --> 00:23:54.430
in computer technology --
several changes that allowed

00:23:54.430 --> 00:24:00.610
for a wider array of people to
have access to the technologies.

00:24:00.610 --> 00:24:04.470
They were becoming
less expensive.

00:24:04.470 --> 00:24:06.450
Numerous vendors
entered the market.

00:24:06.450 --> 00:24:08.400
So this is a very long list,

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:10.380
that is by no means
comprehensive,

00:24:10.380 --> 00:24:14.070
of all the vendors that were
entering this particular space.

00:24:14.070 --> 00:24:16.920
Some were specifically focused
on architectural software,

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:19.060
while others expanded
their offerings

00:24:19.060 --> 00:24:20.920
to the architecture
and design market.

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:25.180
So numerous companies competed
to create and sell CAD software

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:29.040
to firms, including
AutoDesk, Intergraph, Bentley,

00:24:29.040 --> 00:24:30.890
Dassault, just to name a few.

00:24:30.890 --> 00:24:32.560
So in the early 1980s,

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:34.970
firms began adopting
computer-aided design

00:24:34.970 --> 00:24:36.390
technologies -- some firms --

00:24:36.390 --> 00:24:38.720
in large part because the
development and affordability

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:41.590
of computers occurred in
concert with years of research

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:43.320
and discussion within
the industry.

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:44.950
So another thing I like
to point out is that all

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:48.660
of this happened, you know,
over a long period of time.

00:24:48.660 --> 00:24:51.960
There was a long period of
discussion that was occurring,

00:24:51.960 --> 00:24:53.260
that, you know, architects
were sort

00:24:53.260 --> 00:24:55.810
of debating what
their role would be,

00:24:55.810 --> 00:24:58.250
how they might implement
this, whether it was worth it.

00:24:58.250 --> 00:25:00.600
There's a kind of -- there's
a lot of sort of social,

00:25:00.600 --> 00:25:03.750
and political, and economic
considerations that go along

00:25:03.750 --> 00:25:06.870
with all these changes
in technology.

00:25:06.870 --> 00:25:14.300
So, just to give you a
little bit of a view of some

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:16.100
of the advertising that was
going on during this period,

00:25:16.100 --> 00:25:18.480
in the 1980s -- this is taken

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:22.050
from several different
journals in the mid-'80s.

00:25:22.050 --> 00:25:25.030
And one of the things I thought
I'd mention was that the editors

00:25:25.030 --> 00:25:26.840
of "Architectural
Technology," a publication

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:29.220
of The American Institute
of Architects,

00:25:29.220 --> 00:25:31.320
organized two rounds
of CAD evaluations.

00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:32.620
They called them shoot-outs,

00:25:32.620 --> 00:25:36.070
and published the
results in 1984 and 1986.

00:25:36.070 --> 00:25:40.570
They evaluated numerous programs
-- architects evaluated them,

00:25:40.570 --> 00:25:44.350
and by the '84 review, AutoCAD
was already pretty acknowledged

00:25:44.350 --> 00:25:48.150
as the de facto standard
for affordable CAD.

00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:55.530
And by 1986, it's noted that
most of them were expanding

00:25:55.530 --> 00:26:00.980
into giving 3D possibilities,
or 3D models of buildings,

00:26:00.980 --> 00:26:03.870
as well as 2D plans, elevation,
and construction drawings.

00:26:03.870 --> 00:26:06.320
So one of the things
that was revealed is

00:26:06.320 --> 00:26:08.090
that there were many
affordable options

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:10.400
for CAD software
in the mid-1980s.

00:26:10.400 --> 00:26:13.250
So it wasn't as easy as CAD just
-- you know, AutoCAD came in

00:26:13.250 --> 00:26:14.550
and took over the market.

00:26:14.550 --> 00:26:17.490
There was a lot of
competition during this period,

00:26:17.490 --> 00:26:20.500
and a lot of different
software out there,

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:22.570
and a lot of different
companies making this software.

00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:24.560
So -- let's see.

00:26:24.560 --> 00:26:28.690
From the 1980s through the '90s,

00:26:28.690 --> 00:26:32.960
the substantial competition
existed,

00:26:32.960 --> 00:26:35.330
with AutoCAD really
becoming a predominant tool

00:26:35.330 --> 00:26:37.330
within the architectural
community by the 1990s,

00:26:37.330 --> 00:26:39.360
but by no means the only tool.

00:26:39.360 --> 00:26:45.660
Others have persisted, and
digital assets that produce --

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:47.750
produced by these programs
have a lot of value.

00:26:47.750 --> 00:26:52.110
One thing I would like to note
is that, during this period,

00:26:52.110 --> 00:26:54.400
there's several preservation
things to contend with.

00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:56.150
So a lot of this
software was sold

00:26:56.150 --> 00:26:58.550
in hardware and software
bundles.

00:26:58.550 --> 00:27:00.880
So one thing we might need
to think about is not just,

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:03.170
you know, providing access
to software, but thinking

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:05.510
about the hardware used
to access these materials,

00:27:05.510 --> 00:27:07.080
which we would in
most cases anyway.

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:08.750
But there's some
really interesting

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:11.690
and different hardware that
might've come with some

00:27:11.690 --> 00:27:14.450
of these programs that we
would need to contend with.

00:27:14.450 --> 00:27:17.470
There's, as I mentioned before,
development or adaptation

00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:19.750
across multiple different
fields.

00:27:19.750 --> 00:27:22.400
There's a lot of proprietary
systems that we're just starting

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:25.240
to see, and you'll hear
more about from Tim.

00:27:25.240 --> 00:27:29.000
I'd also argue that preserving
the context of these assets,

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.360
the history of these
vendors, is very --

00:27:31.360 --> 00:27:33.380
I think interesting,
and significant.

00:27:33.380 --> 00:27:39.340
There was a lot of mergers,
a lot of bankruptcy,

00:27:39.340 --> 00:27:44.720
or people choosing to get out
of CAD, but also people choosing

00:27:44.720 --> 00:27:46.940
to merge together
with another company,

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:48.400
because they were
stronger as one.

00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:51.530
So I think that kind of
history might also help us,

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:53.550
when thinking about the
challenges we're dealing with,

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:56.680
and just thinking about
telling a broader story

00:27:56.680 --> 00:27:59.490
about computer-aided design
technology for architecture.

00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:01.260
So collaborating with
colleagues to identify

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:04.900
and address the preservation
of legacy assets is part

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:07.320
of the challenge we're
here to address today.

00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:10.580
And I'm very happy to
introduce my colleague, Tim,

00:28:10.580 --> 00:28:13.630
to tell you about the 1990s.

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:24.540
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: Good
morning, everyone.

00:28:24.540 --> 00:28:26.330
I thought I'd take a second,

00:28:26.330 --> 00:28:29.860
if we can just together
congratulate Katy,

00:28:29.860 --> 00:28:33.510
who just successfully
defended her Ph.D. Whoo!

00:28:33.510 --> 00:28:37.040
[ Applause ]

00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:38.490
And on very similar topics,

00:28:38.490 --> 00:28:41.110
so you have the right person
introducing the early days

00:28:41.110 --> 00:28:42.410
of this to you.

00:28:42.410 --> 00:28:48.390
So picking up with the 1990s, I
think one thing that's important

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:49.810
to acknowledge is
that, you know,

00:28:49.810 --> 00:28:51.440
there's some arbitrary
distinctions here.

00:28:51.440 --> 00:28:53.330
Some of the things that'll
characterize as, like,

00:28:53.330 --> 00:28:57.230
from the '90s, or from the 2000s
-- it's not quite so linear.

00:28:57.230 --> 00:28:59.530
People weren't always working
on the same timeframes.

00:28:59.530 --> 00:29:03.350
There's a lot of trends
that stretch over time,

00:29:03.350 --> 00:29:05.660
but that said, we'll
kind of stick

00:29:05.660 --> 00:29:09.540
with the narrative for now.

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:12.960
The '90s really saw sort
of two divergent trends.

00:29:12.960 --> 00:29:16.600
In aerospace, automotive,
engineering,

00:29:16.600 --> 00:29:19.680
we started to see a lot
more market consolidation

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:21.920
around a handful of systems.

00:29:21.920 --> 00:29:26.760
This is probably largely because
in these fields, the longevity

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:30.280
of assets is just as, if not
more, important than, you know,

00:29:30.280 --> 00:29:33.440
the creativity of the
design, which is, I think,

00:29:33.440 --> 00:29:35.280
something that we'll hear
a lot more about later

00:29:35.280 --> 00:29:37.800
on with projects like
the LOTAR project.

00:29:37.800 --> 00:29:41.990
But really, we saw quite a lot
of consolidation around tools

00:29:41.990 --> 00:29:50.520
like NX, and CATIA, and Pro
ENGINEER, largely by these sort

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:54.030
of gigantic firms like GM,
who not only standardized

00:29:54.030 --> 00:29:56.240
around the software, but
actually, in some cases,

00:29:56.240 --> 00:30:00.730
you know, purchased it,
and guided its development.

00:30:00.730 --> 00:30:02.650
At the same time,
in architecture,

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:06.010
we sort of saw an explosion
of the amount of software

00:30:06.010 --> 00:30:09.450
that was being used,
and experimentation --

00:30:09.450 --> 00:30:11.710
you know, even people
taking software,

00:30:11.710 --> 00:30:14.220
realizing it didn't
quite meet their needs,

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:17.840
and sort of scripting around it,
and hacking on it a little bit.

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:21.640
And a lot of this is
related to the development

00:30:21.640 --> 00:30:24.890
of 32-bit operating systems
and personal computers

00:30:24.890 --> 00:30:27.710
that actually had the
processing power to compete

00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:31.290
against these larger, UNIX-based
mainframe applications

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:33.680
that had previously kind
of dominated the market.

00:30:33.680 --> 00:30:38.060
So when we get 32-bit operating
systems, like Windows NT

00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:40.400
with more advanced
graphics capacities,

00:30:40.400 --> 00:30:42.900
more advanced processors,

00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:47.800
suddenly a desktop application
could actually be just as viable

00:30:47.800 --> 00:30:51.870
as a mainframe application at
a significantly lower cost.

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:56.000
Which opens the door to
smaller firms, to students,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:59.370
to people working at home, which
really kind of changes the game,

00:30:59.370 --> 00:31:01.540
when it goes from being
basically a technician doing the

00:31:01.540 --> 00:31:02.840
CAD, or, you know,

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:05.540
a very trained professional
doing the CAD to anybody.

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:08.450
You know, where now, you
know, a student, like,

00:31:08.450 --> 00:31:10.400
one of the first things they're
going to do is open up Rhino

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:12.640
and start doing 3D modeling,
and it's very, very different

00:31:12.640 --> 00:31:14.850
than what it used to be.

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:18.360
We also have the development
-- sort of the brief rise --

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:21.600
like, fast rise and brief heyday
of Silicon Graphics, which is,

00:31:21.600 --> 00:31:26.580
I think, a history that has been
kind of written, but in relation

00:31:26.580 --> 00:31:29.560
to this field, is really
important to think about.

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:32.200
Because essentially, that meant

00:31:32.200 --> 00:31:36.620
that there were these
commercially-available systems

00:31:36.620 --> 00:31:40.620
that were miles and miles
beyond, in terms of 3D modeling

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:42.980
and animation, anything
else that was out there,

00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:46.200
that were largely used in
other but related spheres.

00:31:46.200 --> 00:31:48.000
And I think this is
something that I'll talk

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:51.080
about a little bit -- I'll
keep talking about a bit.

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:54.780
Like animation, the film
industry, special effects --

00:31:54.780 --> 00:31:57.050
so basically, you have
software that's being written

00:31:57.050 --> 00:32:01.450
for these machines that's being
used to do advanced CGI work,

00:32:01.450 --> 00:32:04.790
that's then getting taken by
firms like Asymptote and applied

00:32:04.790 --> 00:32:08.160
to do visualization of the
New York Stock Exchange,

00:32:08.160 --> 00:32:12.230
for instance, which becomes
part of a built environment.

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:14.940
And these sort of crosses
between these disciplines,

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:16.480
I think, complicate the history,

00:32:16.480 --> 00:32:17.780
make it a little
more interesting.

00:32:17.780 --> 00:32:23.070
So some of the software that
we see in this time period --

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:25.070
a lot of it's not new.

00:32:25.070 --> 00:32:29.250
Form-Z would be an exception
here, which it came out in 1991.

00:32:29.250 --> 00:32:32.100
But existing systems, like
MicroStation, Solid Edge,

00:32:32.100 --> 00:32:35.290
SolidWorks, AutoCAD really sort

00:32:35.290 --> 00:32:38.470
of developed the 3D capacities
either for the first time,

00:32:38.470 --> 00:32:41.560
like AutoCAD comes
out with release 13.

00:32:41.560 --> 00:32:45.480
Or they sort of continue to
develop the 3D capacities

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:47.290
that were already there to the
point that they're actually,

00:32:47.290 --> 00:32:52.380
you know, viable, commercially.

00:32:52.380 --> 00:32:55.980
And I'll talk about this more
in a minute, but, I mean,

00:32:55.980 --> 00:32:58.990
these are some of the
systems that basically won

00:32:58.990 --> 00:33:00.900
in this market that
Katie was talking about,

00:33:00.900 --> 00:33:02.270
with a lot of competitors.

00:33:02.270 --> 00:33:05.760
There were a lot of
other systems out there,

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:08.860
but these are the ones -- you
know, they're still around.

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:11.230
They're still in wide use.

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:15.920
We also have, like I said,
this sort of parallel trend

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:19.100
of 3D modeling, and this
largely coming out of film,

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:23.050
games, special effects.

00:33:23.050 --> 00:33:25.090
So PowerAnimator becomes Alias.

00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:26.520
Alias becomes Maya.

00:33:26.520 --> 00:33:29.120
These things are basically
used to create the dinosaurs

00:33:29.120 --> 00:33:31.290
from Jurassic Park, and
the liquid spider --

00:33:31.290 --> 00:33:34.110
or, the liquid Terminator
from Terminator 2,

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:36.610
but then get applied to
architecture, and design,

00:33:36.610 --> 00:33:39.130
and engineering, and
sort of change the way

00:33:39.130 --> 00:33:41.290
that not only models
are being created,

00:33:41.290 --> 00:33:43.570
but also how they're presented.

00:33:43.570 --> 00:33:45.090
Things like, you know, having --

00:33:45.090 --> 00:33:47.090
being able to do
animated renderings,

00:33:47.090 --> 00:33:50.340
and photorealistic
video walk-throughs

00:33:50.340 --> 00:33:52.980
of what a building would be like
kind of changes the interactions

00:33:52.980 --> 00:33:54.280
that people have with clients,

00:33:54.280 --> 00:33:56.610
on top of how they're
actually doing the work.

00:33:56.610 --> 00:33:58.500
And a lot of this
software's still around.

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:01.420
I mean, even big budget movies
are mostly still using things

00:34:01.420 --> 00:34:06.240
like 3ds Max, Maya, which
were largely developed

00:34:06.240 --> 00:34:10.460
for and/or bought by
AutoDesk, for the most part.

00:34:10.460 --> 00:34:16.550
This is a couple of the
other software programs

00:34:16.550 --> 00:34:17.850
that were around.

00:34:17.850 --> 00:34:21.310
This is the desk next to mine at
work, some of the old software

00:34:21.310 --> 00:34:22.640
that we're disk imaging.

00:34:22.640 --> 00:34:26.640
But just to show that, you
know, there are lots of names

00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:29.430
out there, too, that you
don't necessarily remember.

00:34:29.430 --> 00:34:30.730
I think I agree with Katie.

00:34:30.730 --> 00:34:32.030
I think it's a fascinating
history

00:34:32.030 --> 00:34:35.560
that deserves a little
more attention.

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:37.760
There was a lot of
experimentation,

00:34:37.760 --> 00:34:40.920
and what this means is that, if
you are a place like the CCA,

00:34:40.920 --> 00:34:44.750
where I work, or, you know,
a library archive museum,

00:34:44.750 --> 00:34:46.850
and you're getting the
archives of these projects --

00:34:46.850 --> 00:34:49.130
like, these are just a
few of the file extensions

00:34:49.130 --> 00:34:52.730
and softwares [sic] that you're
potentially contending with.

00:34:52.730 --> 00:34:55.630
You know, I think
we have a tendency,

00:34:55.630 --> 00:34:58.410
from our historical perspective
now, to think, like, oh,

00:34:58.410 --> 00:35:02.010
it's like AutoCAD, and Revit,
and maybe MicroStation,

00:35:02.010 --> 00:35:05.380
but there's, you know, dozens
and dozens of software programs

00:35:05.380 --> 00:35:06.800
and file formats that
we potentially have

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:08.100
to contend with.

00:35:08.100 --> 00:35:09.460
Which is, I think, a thing
that we should keep in mind

00:35:09.460 --> 00:35:13.260
when we're talking about things
like best practices for working

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:16.830
with these legacy collections,
you know, that file formats

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:19.060
like STEP are fantastic, but
it doesn't necessarily mean

00:35:19.060 --> 00:35:20.360
that we're going
to have a converter

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:22.520
into these open file
formats from all

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:24.750
of these previous softwares
[sic] that came before.

00:35:24.750 --> 00:35:29.730
Some of the preservation
challenges come, again,

00:35:29.730 --> 00:35:33.470
from this sort of just variety
of applications out there,

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:35.660
most of whom were proprietary,

00:35:35.660 --> 00:35:40.150
most of whom didn't
sell that many copies.

00:35:40.150 --> 00:35:42.250
These applications are
also extremely expensive,

00:35:42.250 --> 00:35:44.550
so it's not like
Word or something,

00:35:44.550 --> 00:35:46.030
where you can buy
a copy off of eBay,

00:35:46.030 --> 00:35:47.600
because it was in
almost every home.

00:35:47.600 --> 00:35:50.630
At this point, even tracking
down the software to begin

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:53.290
with can be a real challenge.

00:35:53.290 --> 00:35:55.580
Experimentation and
practice as well --

00:35:55.580 --> 00:35:57.570
I think this is something --
I might be a little biased,

00:35:57.570 --> 00:36:00.390
coming from CCA, which is
usually interested, sort of,

00:36:00.390 --> 00:36:04.040
in developments in theory
and practice more than sort

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:06.570
of the end products
of architecture.

00:36:06.570 --> 00:36:08.530
But, you know, in
our collections,

00:36:08.530 --> 00:36:11.260
we see from this period
a lot of scripting,

00:36:11.260 --> 00:36:14.200
a lot of creative
experimentation with software,

00:36:14.200 --> 00:36:15.930
which means you have to
get creative in response

00:36:15.930 --> 00:36:18.310
when you're thinking about
how you preserve access

00:36:18.310 --> 00:36:21.480
to this material
over the long term.

00:36:21.480 --> 00:36:23.970
One of the things which
continues before as --

00:36:23.970 --> 00:36:27.040
or, begins before, and
continues even now,

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:30.250
is that it's an extremely
protective market, which means,

00:36:30.250 --> 00:36:32.150
like I said, the
licenses are expensive,

00:36:32.150 --> 00:36:34.710
but also that we're dealing
with things like dongles

00:36:34.710 --> 00:36:37.710
and hardware keys, where
the application won't work

00:36:37.710 --> 00:36:40.120
if you just have a copy of
the application and a license.

00:36:40.120 --> 00:36:42.250
You also have to have
something physically plugged

00:36:42.250 --> 00:36:45.400
in to a parallel
port or a USB port.

00:36:45.400 --> 00:36:48.020
So if we're thinking
about, like, oh,

00:36:48.020 --> 00:36:49.900
maybe one potential
solution to this is,

00:36:49.900 --> 00:36:52.340
we preserve the old software,
and we run it in emulators,

00:36:52.340 --> 00:36:54.550
which is something we're going
to hear more about today.

00:36:54.550 --> 00:36:56.520
And there's a sort of
added layer of complexity,

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:57.820
because how do you -- you know,

00:36:57.820 --> 00:37:02.260
how do you convince this
software that's not actually

00:37:02.260 --> 00:37:04.570
running on a physical machine
that there's this dongle plugged

00:37:04.570 --> 00:37:06.610
into a physical machine,
without actually going in

00:37:06.610 --> 00:37:07.910
and cracking the software?

00:37:07.910 --> 00:37:13.710
Which is not exactly allowed
by U.S. or Canadian law

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:15.790
without explicit permission.

00:37:15.790 --> 00:37:17.480
So these things start
to complicate some

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:20.100
of our potential
solutions a little bit.

00:37:20.100 --> 00:37:22.750
Proprietary hardware platforms,
like Katie was saying, too,

00:37:22.750 --> 00:37:24.220
you know, SGI was fantastic.

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:28.130
It was also extremely expensive,
so people like Neil Denari

00:37:28.130 --> 00:37:30.530
in architecture only got copies
because they were hanging

00:37:30.530 --> 00:37:33.400
out with people in
the film industry.

00:37:33.400 --> 00:37:37.100
So it's not like there's
a hobbyist gamer community

00:37:37.100 --> 00:37:41.810
emulating these things, that
we can then use to emulate it.

00:37:41.810 --> 00:37:44.950
You know, so there's
whole challenges there.

00:37:44.950 --> 00:37:47.470
And I would say, you know,
finally, that sort of lack of,

00:37:47.470 --> 00:37:50.410
like, fully interoperable
vendor-neutral file formats --

00:37:50.410 --> 00:37:52.490
you have things like Ijus
[phonetic] that's long

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:53.790
established by this point.

00:37:53.790 --> 00:37:59.140
STEP is in development by
the '90s, but it doesn't mean

00:37:59.140 --> 00:38:01.540
that all these software
programs can actually write data

00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:03.360
into these interoperable
file formats.

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:07.480
It doesn't mean that data
isn't lost in that migration.

00:38:07.480 --> 00:38:10.770
So just a thing to keep in mind.

00:38:10.770 --> 00:38:13.930
As we go into the
2000s, essentially,

00:38:13.930 --> 00:38:16.880
we see sort of further
development of these tools,

00:38:16.880 --> 00:38:19.710
especially around 3D
modeling and scripting.

00:38:19.710 --> 00:38:21.740
Probably the biggest
thing, though,

00:38:21.740 --> 00:38:23.180
is just a wider adoption,

00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:25.290
that these software
programs get more advanced

00:38:25.290 --> 00:38:27.190
because there's more
time, but also more money,

00:38:27.190 --> 00:38:29.350
because the market's bigger.

00:38:29.350 --> 00:38:31.840
We see the development of things
like SketchUp and Rhinoceros

00:38:31.840 --> 00:38:36.900
that really lower the barrier to
entry for things like modeling.

00:38:36.900 --> 00:38:40.390
Also, a lot of really
interesting automated

00:38:40.390 --> 00:38:42.850
fabrication, 3D printing --

00:38:42.850 --> 00:38:45.050
so people start to play with
materials a little more,

00:38:45.050 --> 00:38:48.420
think about what can change
on the construction site,

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:50.840
what can change in the process
of creating the materials

00:38:50.840 --> 00:38:53.330
that ultimately go to the site.

00:38:53.330 --> 00:38:57.950
One of the biggest things, which
actually starts in the '90s,

00:38:57.950 --> 00:39:00.950
really -- technically maybe
before with AutoLISP --

00:39:00.950 --> 00:39:04.660
but is a -- this, like, sort of
experimentation with scripting.

00:39:04.660 --> 00:39:07.550
So in the '90s, you know, if you
look at a software like Maya,

00:39:07.550 --> 00:39:10.010
which is largely used
for, like, animation

00:39:10.010 --> 00:39:12.950
and special effects
work, but tends to get --

00:39:12.950 --> 00:39:17.040
like, gets used in
architecture and design as well,

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:20.170
you no longer have to program
outside of it and figure out how

00:39:20.170 --> 00:39:22.350
to interact with the program.

00:39:22.350 --> 00:39:25.070
They start to build in
capacity for scripting.

00:39:25.070 --> 00:39:29.500
So Maya has the Maya
embedded language, or, like,

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:31.110
MEL language, so you
can actually script

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:34.110
within the program to do
things like generative design.

00:39:34.110 --> 00:39:35.410
That eventually gives way

00:39:35.410 --> 00:39:38.710
to more standard programming
languages, like Python,

00:39:38.710 --> 00:39:40.090
and then, you know,
in the 2010s,

00:39:40.090 --> 00:39:42.210
like Aliza will talk about,
that gives way to even sort

00:39:42.210 --> 00:39:44.160
of easier methods of scripting.

00:39:44.160 --> 00:39:46.200
So they start -- these
things that people were doing

00:39:46.200 --> 00:39:49.320
as experimental practice in the
'90s start to become normalized

00:39:49.320 --> 00:39:53.040
as part of, like,
typical practice.

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:57.730
And finally, but certainly
not least for the 2000s,

00:39:57.730 --> 00:40:00.780
we see the real development
of BIM.

00:40:00.780 --> 00:40:04.780
If you look at the sort
of AIA membership surveys

00:40:04.780 --> 00:40:06.610
at this point, you realize

00:40:06.610 --> 00:40:10.350
that basically Revit gets
developed in the 2000s.

00:40:10.350 --> 00:40:15.910
ArchiCAD becomes, you know,
fully unarguably BIM software

00:40:15.910 --> 00:40:21.240
at this point, but not that
many people are using it yet,

00:40:21.240 --> 00:40:23.000
except for the really
large firms.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:24.300
So something like, you know,

00:40:24.300 --> 00:40:26.940
16% of architectural firms
are using BIM software

00:40:26.940 --> 00:40:31.190
by the mid-2000s, but
IFC is in development.

00:40:31.190 --> 00:40:32.490
The software's there.

00:40:32.490 --> 00:40:34.210
There's a lot of
evangelizing going on,

00:40:34.210 --> 00:40:37.120
a lot of discussion going
on, which sort of leads us

00:40:37.120 --> 00:40:38.860
up to the current moment.

00:40:38.860 --> 00:40:45.540
So unique preservation
challenges for the 2000s --

00:40:45.540 --> 00:40:49.040
you know, all this use of
scripting, of parametricism,

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:51.090
of experimentation around
the software means a lot

00:40:51.090 --> 00:40:53.630
of dependencies, and a lot of
data that's potentially lost

00:40:53.630 --> 00:40:55.790
if we migrate between formats.

00:40:55.790 --> 00:40:57.690
Always complicates things.

00:40:57.690 --> 00:40:59.870
We have much more
complex workflows, which,

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:04.820
for someone like me, means
I might get what appears

00:41:04.820 --> 00:41:07.470
to be the same model in
four different file formats

00:41:07.470 --> 00:41:09.390
from four different
software packages,

00:41:09.390 --> 00:41:11.280
and unless you have
documentation from the project,

00:41:11.280 --> 00:41:14.110
you don't necessarily
know what the order

00:41:14.110 --> 00:41:15.640
that things happened in was.

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:18.030
Because they might be doing
initial modeling in one thing,

00:41:18.030 --> 00:41:20.350
and then porting it to
something else for rendering,

00:41:20.350 --> 00:41:21.840
and porting it to
something else for creation

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:23.420
of construction drawings,

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:25.900
and sometimes it's a lot
more complex than that.

00:41:25.900 --> 00:41:27.200
So it starts to -- we start

00:41:27.200 --> 00:41:29.050
to need quite a lot
more documentation

00:41:29.050 --> 00:41:31.350
to understand the
work processes.

00:41:31.350 --> 00:41:35.010
A vast increase in the number
of files and file size --

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:36.770
so at this point,

00:41:36.770 --> 00:41:38.780
as the software gets
a lot more complex,

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:40.560
the assets get a lot bigger,

00:41:40.560 --> 00:41:43.680
which has real sort
of economic concerns.

00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:45.210
Which, I think, when --
especially when we're talking

00:41:45.210 --> 00:41:47.420
about the cultural sector, has
a big impact when we're talking

00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:49.550
about collecting, because we
have to actually be able to pay

00:41:49.550 --> 00:41:51.310
for all this redundant storage

00:41:51.310 --> 00:41:54.580
to meet our digital
preservation best practices.

00:41:54.580 --> 00:41:58.320
And finally, a challenge
that I think is not related

00:41:58.320 --> 00:42:00.440
to just architecture, and
engineering, and design,

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:03.680
but certainly universal,
is partially

00:42:03.680 --> 00:42:05.200
because these files
were so much bigger,

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:07.570
there was so much more
data, people didn't want

00:42:07.570 --> 00:42:09.780
to keep the stuff on their
computers and servers anymore.

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:12.850
And people were told that it
was best practice in the 2000s

00:42:12.850 --> 00:42:16.400
to use things like Archival
Gold CDs that were guaranteed

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:22.440
for 300 years, that I can't read
10 years later, and LTO tape,

00:42:22.440 --> 00:42:23.740
which degrades over time.

00:42:23.740 --> 00:42:25.920
You know, there was a
really common practice --

00:42:25.920 --> 00:42:28.250
a lot of architects were
like, we'll burn our archive

00:42:28.250 --> 00:42:30.870
to CDs now, and these are things

00:42:30.870 --> 00:42:32.490
that we have to contend
with now.

00:42:32.490 --> 00:42:35.310
It basically means that
there's a ticking clock,

00:42:35.310 --> 00:42:36.890
where a lot of data's sitting

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:39.040
on removable media that's
in people's closets.

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:41.270
It's under the stairs.

00:42:41.270 --> 00:42:44.430
It's rapidly degrading, and
things have to get migrated off

00:42:44.430 --> 00:42:47.560
if we want to even have the
assets around to begin with,

00:42:47.560 --> 00:42:50.580
in order to preserve and
provide access to them.

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:53.780
And with that, I will
leave it to Aliza

00:42:53.780 --> 00:42:57.040
to very competently
continue the talk.

00:42:57.040 --> 00:42:58.840
Thank you.

