00:43:54.960 --> 00:43:58.780
And so it's important to
understand that this is not --

00:43:58.780 --> 00:44:03.280
we're not looking at a
microcosm of our system.

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:06.850
It's a larger ecosystem, and
these software are working

00:44:06.850 --> 00:44:09.870
in between different
disciplines.

00:44:09.870 --> 00:44:11.750
But the important thing
also to think about is

00:44:11.750 --> 00:44:17.610
that as some software, like
Revit, is becoming more robust

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:21.030
and heavier, clunkier,
bigger, can handle more data.

00:44:21.030 --> 00:44:23.360
We're also getting really light
things like Tim mentioned,

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:26.850
of Rhino and SketchUp, that
are really easy plug-and-play,

00:44:26.850 --> 00:44:29.010
which I'll talk about
in just a second.

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:32.460
That facilitate much
easier access,

00:44:32.460 --> 00:44:34.290
and for you to do different
things at different times.

00:44:34.290 --> 00:44:36.350
And so the workflow issues
that Tim's talking about --

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:39.510
talked about just a minute
ago get more complex,

00:44:39.510 --> 00:44:41.000
because you're like, oh,
I see a SketchUp file.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.030
That was only during
schematic design.

00:44:43.030 --> 00:44:44.330
Great. Nope.

00:44:44.330 --> 00:44:46.410
Nope. That's not the case,
because sometimes you'll want

00:44:46.410 --> 00:44:47.960
to do a piece of that
massing in SketchUp,

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:49.260
and then import it into Revit.

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:52.110
And then it's there, and now
you're building on top of that.

00:44:52.110 --> 00:44:53.450
So it's a very confusing --

00:44:53.450 --> 00:44:55.800
and I'm sorry for everyone
who is not familiar

00:44:55.800 --> 00:44:57.100
with all of these software.

00:44:57.100 --> 00:44:58.400
I'm going to explain
them in just a second.

00:44:58.400 --> 00:44:59.700
My apologies.

00:44:59.700 --> 00:45:01.810
But the workflow is
really confusing,

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:03.190
because you might
think that you know

00:45:03.190 --> 00:45:05.860
when something was used based on
what the software is capable of,

00:45:05.860 --> 00:45:09.490
but it's kind of a -- you
know, the Wild West continues.

00:45:09.490 --> 00:45:10.870
We thought it was only
really in the '90s,

00:45:10.870 --> 00:45:14.080
when everyone could sort of
hack and break their software,

00:45:14.080 --> 00:45:15.880
but it's continued to evolve.

00:45:15.880 --> 00:45:17.810
It wasn't an anomaly
of the '90s.

00:45:17.810 --> 00:45:19.850
It's actually the
trend, which is great,

00:45:19.850 --> 00:45:21.240
but two of the main
things that come

00:45:21.240 --> 00:45:24.140
out of the 2010s is
really parametric design,

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:26.600
and computational design,
and visual scripting.

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:28.670
Visual scripting is
particularly interesting,

00:45:28.670 --> 00:45:30.390
and comes a little bit
later, so we'll focus

00:45:30.390 --> 00:45:31.890
on parametric design for now.

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:35.290
The software that's
included on this list --

00:45:35.290 --> 00:45:37.660
the large blue R is Revit.

00:45:37.660 --> 00:45:39.540
It is a building
information modeling system,

00:45:39.540 --> 00:45:43.260
and it definitely has the
lion's share of the market.

00:45:43.260 --> 00:45:47.800
It is incredibly robust, because
it can handle engineering.

00:45:47.800 --> 00:45:50.180
Mechanical and structural
engineering can be added on,

00:45:50.180 --> 00:45:51.850
or you can take those
layers off.

00:45:51.850 --> 00:45:53.180
It's really helpful for that.

00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:56.890
The bumblebee, and
ladybug, and all of that --

00:45:56.890 --> 00:46:02.520
there's actually a whole zoo
that exists for energy modeling

00:46:02.520 --> 00:46:06.460
and more environmentally
oriented data elements,

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:07.760
and -- for programming.

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:10.880
And then Rhino and SketchUp,
as I'll explain right here,

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:13.450
are the much lighter-weight
softwares [sic].

00:46:13.450 --> 00:46:15.340
So this should just
give you a basic primer

00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:20.110
of what we're looking at, in
terms of gradation of intensity.

00:46:20.110 --> 00:46:22.440
So starting at the
top, it's much easier.

00:46:22.440 --> 00:46:25.290
You can really -- like, first
day of class in design --

00:46:25.290 --> 00:46:27.710
any design program, you should
be able to just, you know,

00:46:27.710 --> 00:46:29.210
hop on and start playing around.

00:46:29.210 --> 00:46:30.650
It'll be super confusing
at first.

00:46:30.650 --> 00:46:33.400
I have worked with it,
and it's very confusing.

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:35.910
But once you understand
the lay of the ground,

00:46:35.910 --> 00:46:38.650
it makes it much easier to
come into these other software,

00:46:38.650 --> 00:46:40.470
and so you start
understanding what massing is,

00:46:40.470 --> 00:46:45.810
what different layers can look
like, and different levels

00:46:45.810 --> 00:46:49.880
of texture and materiality
that you can apply to it.

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:52.640
Alternatively, we've got
Grasshopper and Dynamo.

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:55.220
So Grasshopper came out
much earlier, and was meant

00:46:55.220 --> 00:46:57.010
to be paired with Rhino.

00:46:57.010 --> 00:46:58.630
I'll just go there
and show you that.

00:46:58.630 --> 00:46:59.930
So that's helpful.

00:46:59.930 --> 00:47:02.450
So these -- Grasshopper was
designed to work with Rhino,

00:47:02.450 --> 00:47:05.380
and Dynamo, which is this
fun four-cornered thing

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:07.910
that has an arrow going to
Revit, comes from AutoDesk.

00:47:07.910 --> 00:47:11.510
And they basically
-- sorry, yeah.

00:47:11.510 --> 00:47:13.120
Revit, great.

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:17.740
They basically are intentionally
designed software to pair

00:47:17.740 --> 00:47:20.870
with another software, which is
an entire market that evolves.

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:23.620
But, a lot of the time,
the software like Revit --

00:47:23.620 --> 00:47:25.840
Revit has just kind of made
itself this wonderful amoeba

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:27.910
that can just continue
to accept things in.

00:47:27.910 --> 00:47:29.730
So more things can
be imported into it,

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:31.650
and it can handle
exporting into a different --

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:35.560
a huge range of different
file types.

00:47:35.560 --> 00:47:38.150
So it's sort of just
becoming this sponge

00:47:38.150 --> 00:47:39.530
that can handle taking
everything in.

00:47:39.530 --> 00:47:41.280
It becomes a really
heavy software, though,

00:47:41.280 --> 00:47:43.070
and that's really
dangerous when you're working

00:47:43.070 --> 00:47:44.710
on a very large project.

00:47:44.710 --> 00:47:47.520
There's this chance for not
something to get saved back

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:50.410
to the file correctly, as many
people are playing with it --

00:47:50.410 --> 00:47:52.010
not playing, working in it.

00:47:52.010 --> 00:47:54.250
And -- you know, and
so it can become --

00:47:54.250 --> 00:47:58.020
it can become much more complex
and difficult to parse apart,

00:47:58.020 --> 00:48:00.070
and find where the errors
happened, because you're working

00:48:00.070 --> 00:48:01.370
on a much larger scale.

00:48:01.370 --> 00:48:03.400
The wonderful thing that
comes with visual scripting is

00:48:03.400 --> 00:48:07.380
that it allows designers to
very quickly get into that --

00:48:07.380 --> 00:48:10.500
the landscape of
programming, and providing some

00:48:10.500 --> 00:48:13.510
of the automation that the
1970s had hoped computers would

00:48:13.510 --> 00:48:14.810
offer them.

00:48:14.810 --> 00:48:17.190
Because if you've ever worked
in any of these software,

00:48:17.190 --> 00:48:19.090
you know you don't want to
really be the one that has

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:21.610
to number every single
room in a dorm

00:48:21.610 --> 00:48:23.470
as you're working
on the floor plan.

00:48:23.470 --> 00:48:25.560
And so that's one of the things
that Dynamo can do for you,

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:27.030
is like, we'll automatically
create that --

00:48:27.030 --> 00:48:30.140
if you run that script, it
can create numbering systems.

00:48:30.140 --> 00:48:32.620
And so it lightens the load
for the designer to not have

00:48:32.620 --> 00:48:34.580
to focus on these
granular details

00:48:34.580 --> 00:48:36.430
that you really don't want
to mess up, and instead,

00:48:36.430 --> 00:48:39.300
you can rely on the strength
of the computer to fix

00:48:39.300 --> 00:48:41.480
that for you, if you've
applied that element.

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:43.860
So that's a really hopeful
thing that's come about,

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:46.260
but it does create a lot of
layers of issues that I'll talk

00:48:46.260 --> 00:48:47.660
about in just a second.

00:48:47.660 --> 00:48:49.120
This is the layer of issue.

00:48:49.120 --> 00:48:52.110
So this looks really
simple and clean, right?

00:48:52.110 --> 00:48:53.700
Oh, obviously, one-to-one.

00:48:53.700 --> 00:48:55.890
Yeah, that's super, except
that's not really what happens.

00:48:55.890 --> 00:48:59.980
This is an actual diagram
from our sustainability lead

00:48:59.980 --> 00:49:04.550
in my firm, and she created it
to explain how certain data goes

00:49:04.550 --> 00:49:06.260
from one area to
another in order for you

00:49:06.260 --> 00:49:08.410
to create certain energy
modeling assessments.

00:49:08.410 --> 00:49:14.360
And so, I'm not going to get
into all of the various critters

00:49:14.360 --> 00:49:17.990
on the screen, but the important
thing to understand is that,

00:49:17.990 --> 00:49:21.520
it is a really complex problem
that we're dealing with.

00:49:21.520 --> 00:49:24.820
Because this is just for
her part of a project.

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:29.470
Like, that is a very small
portion of a much larger animal,

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:31.510
and we're not even at
construction administration yet.

00:49:31.510 --> 00:49:34.020
Like, this is during
design phase.

00:49:34.020 --> 00:49:36.870
You know, so -- and for everyone
who might not know every --

00:49:36.870 --> 00:49:38.380
might not understand
the full phases,

00:49:38.380 --> 00:49:40.910
there's schematic design, which
is where you'd want to just play

00:49:40.910 --> 00:49:43.580
around with massing and come
up with a general concept.

00:49:43.580 --> 00:49:46.050
There's design documents.

00:49:46.050 --> 00:49:48.540
That's when you're working
more in honing the design,

00:49:48.540 --> 00:49:50.940
and really cleaning --
clearing it up, and then you get

00:49:50.940 --> 00:49:52.240
into construction documents.

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:54.830
And that's when things get
really firm and more concrete,

00:49:54.830 --> 00:49:57.280
to actually then make
it into concrete.

00:49:57.280 --> 00:50:02.250
And so this comes much earlier
than the actual concrete moment,

00:50:02.250 --> 00:50:04.220
but -- like, this
is the landscape

00:50:04.220 --> 00:50:05.520
that we're dealing with.

00:50:05.520 --> 00:50:09.140
And I can tell you,
it's terrifying to me.

00:50:09.140 --> 00:50:10.440
I'm sorry.

00:50:10.440 --> 00:50:11.830
That probably doesn't make
anyone here feel very good,

00:50:11.830 --> 00:50:15.890
but -- [laughter] but it's
a scary space to be in,

00:50:15.890 --> 00:50:18.490
to recognize that when
you accept these files in,

00:50:18.490 --> 00:50:20.850
even at my firm, there's
a good chance that some

00:50:20.850 --> 00:50:24.100
of these won't have these
saved to our billable drive.

00:50:24.100 --> 00:50:26.040
It'll be something that she
was working on on the side

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:30.030
in this case of the
sustainability coordinator,

00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:32.060
just testing something
out, and then maybe

00:50:32.060 --> 00:50:33.360
that doesn't get back.

00:50:33.360 --> 00:50:34.970
And so, I mean, that's, like,

00:50:34.970 --> 00:50:37.740
one orphan record
kind of situation.

00:50:37.740 --> 00:50:39.990
But for someone at a
collecting institution,

00:50:39.990 --> 00:50:41.880
that becomes a much bigger
issue, and it's something

00:50:41.880 --> 00:50:44.020
that needs to be talked
about in terms of appraisal.

00:50:44.020 --> 00:50:45.450
Which is not what I'm
here to talk to you about,

00:50:45.450 --> 00:50:47.540
so I promise I'll stop there.

00:50:47.540 --> 00:50:49.540
We'll continue with the primer.

00:50:49.540 --> 00:50:51.860
That's just a nice
little doom and gloom

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:53.160
for everyone to keep in mind.

00:50:53.160 --> 00:50:56.070
So then, more doom and
gloom, but also excitement,

00:50:56.070 --> 00:50:58.130
is that now we're
moving towards the cloud,

00:50:58.130 --> 00:51:01.430
and it's a more collaborative
environment, higher impact

00:51:01.430 --> 00:51:02.980
in terms of -- firms can work

00:51:02.980 --> 00:51:04.300
across the country
with each other.

00:51:04.300 --> 00:51:07.920
They can work across the world
with one another using platforms

00:51:07.920 --> 00:51:10.080
like GreenBIM and A360.

00:51:10.080 --> 00:51:11.490
I include Adobe Creative Cloud,

00:51:11.490 --> 00:51:15.030
because it's also an incredibly
robust cloud-based suite.

00:51:15.030 --> 00:51:17.960
And basically, what we need
to be worried about here is

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:21.460
who owns these records,
because they're being hosted

00:51:21.460 --> 00:51:22.760
on their server.

00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:24.490
And it's not that
I think that any --

00:51:24.490 --> 00:51:27.130
the servers aren't trustworthy,
or have poor security,

00:51:27.130 --> 00:51:29.320
or anything like that,
but it's about figuring

00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:30.620
out the right regulations.

00:51:30.620 --> 00:51:33.340
If we're the prime on a project,
and we have subconsultants

00:51:33.340 --> 00:51:34.850
that need to have
access to certain parts,

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:40.920
how do we protect our
model from any, you know,

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:42.440
mischievous goings-on?

00:51:42.440 --> 00:51:46.010
And so, you have to keep that
in mind as we think about --

00:51:46.010 --> 00:51:47.970
well, the model -- the business
model then also changes.

00:51:47.970 --> 00:51:50.560
So the expense is going back
up, because not only do you have

00:51:50.560 --> 00:51:54.500
to have your copy of Revit
2018, but then you also have

00:51:54.500 --> 00:51:56.900
to pay separately for A360.

00:51:56.900 --> 00:51:59.540
So now a firm that would
normally pay a set price

00:51:59.540 --> 00:52:00.960
for one year for that person

00:52:00.960 --> 00:52:02.790
to have one thing is now
paying basically double

00:52:02.790 --> 00:52:05.180
that for every single person
who needs access to it,

00:52:05.180 --> 00:52:07.160
because of the way that the
subscription model has been

00:52:07.160 --> 00:52:08.460
set up.

00:52:08.460 --> 00:52:10.800
And as software becomes
software as a service,

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:13.690
and subscription models rather
than, you buy that software

00:52:13.690 --> 00:52:16.050
and you have it on your
computer, and it's something

00:52:16.050 --> 00:52:18.350
that -- oh, well, Katie's
gone onto another place,

00:52:18.350 --> 00:52:20.220
so we can take her copy
and give it to Charlotte.

00:52:20.220 --> 00:52:23.000
You know, that doesn't
work anymore,

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:26.220
and it's something that,
as people who are going

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:28.120
to be collecting this
stuff in 20 years,

00:52:28.120 --> 00:52:29.420
need to think about now.

00:52:29.420 --> 00:52:33.120
Because there has to be
a proactive solution,

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:36.650
because otherwise, we're
all kind of in trouble.

00:52:36.650 --> 00:52:38.220
And so that's something
to keep in mind,

00:52:38.220 --> 00:52:40.060
because we're getting
more exciting as well.

00:52:40.060 --> 00:52:43.030
So A360 and BIM -- GreenBIM,

00:52:43.030 --> 00:52:45.160
BIM360 that was mentioned
earlier --

00:52:45.160 --> 00:52:46.480
they're all really
exciting platforms,

00:52:46.480 --> 00:52:50.520
and they allow the designers to
do incredibly innovative things

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:52.260
as a result of being
able to work in real time

00:52:52.260 --> 00:52:56.060
across the world and with each
other in different spaces.

00:52:56.060 --> 00:52:58.110
However, we need
to keep in mind --

00:52:58.110 --> 00:52:59.440
what does it mean when
the project is done,

00:52:59.440 --> 00:53:02.530
and how do you get
those records back?

00:53:02.530 --> 00:53:04.770
So then, we'll talk about
something fun again,

00:53:04.770 --> 00:53:07.280
which is about augmented
reality and virtual reality.

00:53:07.280 --> 00:53:10.320
These are the new ways
that firms are beginning

00:53:10.320 --> 00:53:11.900
to communicate with clients.

00:53:11.900 --> 00:53:15.700
So building models is still
huge, and is really important

00:53:15.700 --> 00:53:17.660
to materiality, and
expressing the idea,

00:53:17.660 --> 00:53:20.150
because visual literacy isn't
something that everyone has

00:53:20.150 --> 00:53:22.190
at the same level as a
designer who went through five

00:53:22.190 --> 00:53:24.470
or seven years of design school.

00:53:24.470 --> 00:53:29.130
And so it's great to be able
to provide a relatable way

00:53:29.130 --> 00:53:31.790
to experience building,
and one of those is --

00:53:31.790 --> 00:53:35.240
virtual reality has become
a new way of communicating.

00:53:35.240 --> 00:53:36.630
And so sometimes, we've
been able to use it

00:53:36.630 --> 00:53:38.510
and actually share it with our
clients, and sometimes it's just

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:41.380
for the designers to get in the
space and see what it's like.

00:53:41.380 --> 00:53:44.370
And virtual reality is really
interesting, because as you see

00:53:44.370 --> 00:53:46.020
on the screen, Revit
and Enscape,

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:47.410
you can just pull
something right in.

00:53:47.410 --> 00:53:49.170
You can make a change
in a Revit model,

00:53:49.170 --> 00:53:50.470
and it'll be immediately
reflected

00:53:50.470 --> 00:53:53.370
in Enscape, which
is really cool.

00:53:53.370 --> 00:53:56.310
But then you can also do that
for a SketchUp model, which --

00:53:56.310 --> 00:53:58.860
SketchUp just has a little
button, and you can go

00:53:58.860 --> 00:54:00.160
into virtual reality mode.

00:54:00.160 --> 00:54:01.640
And so, again, what
happens to that record?

00:54:01.640 --> 00:54:02.940
Because there's no
way of knowing

00:54:02.940 --> 00:54:04.580
that someone did the
virtual reality mode

00:54:04.580 --> 00:54:05.920
of their SketchUp model.

00:54:05.920 --> 00:54:07.320
Maybe they wrote
down in context.

00:54:07.320 --> 00:54:09.330
Maybe they have it in the
meeting minutes with the client,

00:54:09.330 --> 00:54:10.970
that they showed them
that, but it's --

00:54:10.970 --> 00:54:12.390
the context is really important.

00:54:12.390 --> 00:54:15.560
And it's one thing to know
what the software's capable of.

00:54:15.560 --> 00:54:16.860
It's another thing to know --

00:54:16.860 --> 00:54:18.930
what did someone actually
do with the software?

00:54:18.930 --> 00:54:20.780
That is the question,
when it comes

00:54:20.780 --> 00:54:22.370
to understanding
what is available.

00:54:22.370 --> 00:54:24.120
And then augmented reality --

00:54:24.120 --> 00:54:26.320
I was also told by somebody that
there's, like, mixed reality,

00:54:26.320 --> 00:54:27.930
and I don't know what
that is, so I'm sorry.

00:54:27.930 --> 00:54:31.590
But augmented reality is
where you apply, like --

00:54:31.590 --> 00:54:34.060
if anyone's familiar with
the game PokÃ©mon Go,

00:54:34.060 --> 00:54:35.780
where you basically
put a layer on top

00:54:35.780 --> 00:54:37.080
of what you're experiencing.

00:54:37.080 --> 00:54:39.170
So this could be really
incredible for planners who want

00:54:39.170 --> 00:54:42.610
to show, like, this is what
this square could look like now,

00:54:42.610 --> 00:54:45.360
or this is what the
streetscape could be going --

00:54:45.360 --> 00:54:47.270
like, walking down, you
know, Pennsylvania Avenue.

00:54:47.270 --> 00:54:48.570
They could just change things,

00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:50.610
and so you could see what
layers get put on top of,

00:54:50.610 --> 00:54:53.360
rather than sitting in
an office and looking

00:54:53.360 --> 00:54:55.070
at a model on your table.

00:54:55.070 --> 00:54:57.180
You could walk and
experience that yourself.

00:54:57.180 --> 00:54:59.170
And the potential
for that is immense.

00:54:59.170 --> 00:55:03.110
Like, I'm so encouraged by
what is possible, but then,

00:55:03.110 --> 00:55:04.410
like, how do you save this?

00:55:04.410 --> 00:55:06.040
Especially if it's
made as an application.

00:55:06.040 --> 00:55:07.570
Well, then, now we have
to worry about holding

00:55:07.570 --> 00:55:10.730
onto a cell phone type
that this was made for.

00:55:10.730 --> 00:55:13.380
And as we all have experienced,
even if you're really nice

00:55:13.380 --> 00:55:14.800
to your cell phone, maybe
it's not always going

00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:16.100
to be so nice to you.

00:55:16.100 --> 00:55:17.400
So that's something to think

00:55:17.400 --> 00:55:20.220
about when we work
through these things.

00:55:20.220 --> 00:55:23.440
And so, to end on
the wonderful part

00:55:23.440 --> 00:55:24.890
of new preservation challenges,

00:55:24.890 --> 00:55:26.320
you'll note these are
basically the same ones

00:55:26.320 --> 00:55:27.670
that Tim mentioned earlier.

00:55:27.670 --> 00:55:29.080
They just get more intense.

00:55:29.080 --> 00:55:31.970
So there's more scripting,
and that's great.

00:55:31.970 --> 00:55:33.650
It's increased the number
of dependencies, though,

00:55:33.650 --> 00:55:35.560
because now we have
more data involved,

00:55:35.560 --> 00:55:38.760
and there's more experimentation
as it has become democratized.

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:44.370
So it's not only, you know,
the incredible experimental

00:55:44.370 --> 00:55:46.050
and early adopters that
Tim has at the CCA --

00:55:46.050 --> 00:55:48.970
has the records of,
but now it's --

00:55:48.970 --> 00:55:51.180
literally every student
can try experimenting

00:55:51.180 --> 00:55:55.900
and creating these new
concept at a very low barrier.

00:55:55.900 --> 00:55:58.780
And so that just means we have a
whole lot more experimentation.

00:55:58.780 --> 00:56:02.400
Instead of only 10 people
messing around, got thousands.

00:56:02.400 --> 00:56:04.170
The workflows are,
like I mentioned,

00:56:04.170 --> 00:56:06.270
as you can see, super fun.

00:56:06.270 --> 00:56:08.510
Workflow number one -- and so,

00:56:08.510 --> 00:56:09.990
workflows are getting
much more complex,

00:56:09.990 --> 00:56:12.570
and that adds a whole
new spectrum

00:56:12.570 --> 00:56:15.390
of understanding the
provenance of the records,

00:56:15.390 --> 00:56:18.760
understanding the intention of
the records, and then worrying

00:56:18.760 --> 00:56:22.060
about how to actually get those
records when they are done.

00:56:22.060 --> 00:56:25.160
As an Archos Ware firm, it's
a very complicated process

00:56:25.160 --> 00:56:27.130
of getting the records
when a project completes,

00:56:27.130 --> 00:56:29.620
because there are so many
different ways of defining

00:56:29.620 --> 00:56:31.120
when a project is completed.

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:33.760
Especially if you continue
to work with a client for,

00:56:33.760 --> 00:56:35.060
you know, 30 years -- maybe

00:56:35.060 --> 00:56:36.430
that project's never
actually completed,

00:56:36.430 --> 00:56:38.280
but then it's 30
years of records

00:56:38.280 --> 00:56:40.740
that have not been cared for.

00:56:40.740 --> 00:56:43.410
And that becomes much more
dangerous as we move more

00:56:43.410 --> 00:56:46.200
into digital, and if
people think that it's safe

00:56:46.200 --> 00:56:50.880
to leave things on CDs,
we might be in a bind.

00:56:50.880 --> 00:56:52.280
We are in a bind.

00:56:52.280 --> 00:56:57.220
So -- [laughter] and so then
the last two are a vast increase

00:56:57.220 --> 00:56:59.000
in the number of project
files and file size,

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:03.640
and that means more in terms
of, like, affordability --

00:57:03.640 --> 00:57:05.530
like, the sustainability
of an archive being able

00:57:05.530 --> 00:57:08.420
to handle collecting
more material.

00:57:08.420 --> 00:57:10.620
If your first three
collections, you didn't realize

00:57:10.620 --> 00:57:12.950
that you needed to change
your appraisal guidelines,

00:57:12.950 --> 00:57:16.860
so now you have six terabytes
from, you know, Aliza Leventhal,

00:57:16.860 --> 00:57:20.110
congratulations,
but that's not great

00:57:20.110 --> 00:57:22.770
if you are now 45 people
in, and they also want

00:57:22.770 --> 00:57:24.430
to give you all three
terabytes that they have.

00:57:24.430 --> 00:57:28.500
If you don't have the
bandwidth to literally house it,

00:57:28.500 --> 00:57:30.820
and you don't have the
funding to support that,

00:57:30.820 --> 00:57:33.330
that becomes a problem that
we need to become better

00:57:33.330 --> 00:57:35.490
at articulating, so
that we're more careful

00:57:35.490 --> 00:57:37.400
in how we're curating
our collection.

00:57:37.400 --> 00:57:40.240
Which is a dangerous thing
to say, because we don't want

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:42.170
to be pre-selecting too far --

00:57:42.170 --> 00:57:43.560
too much, but we also need

00:57:43.560 --> 00:57:45.600
to be protecting
ourselves for the long term.

00:57:45.600 --> 00:57:47.710
And then, the last thing is
actually digital deliverables,

00:57:47.710 --> 00:57:49.780
and that's something that
I'm really hopeful for,

00:57:49.780 --> 00:57:51.520
and hope that we get to
talk a lot more about today,

00:57:51.520 --> 00:57:54.250
which is that there is
now a need for this.

00:57:54.250 --> 00:57:56.980
So before, it was,
wouldn't that be nice?

00:57:56.980 --> 00:57:58.280
Ah, this is really frustrating.

00:57:58.280 --> 00:57:59.580
I don't know what to do.

00:57:59.580 --> 00:58:02.710
But if these files are
becoming contract deliverables,

00:58:02.710 --> 00:58:05.270
that means that, in perpetuity,
they need to be available.

00:58:05.270 --> 00:58:07.370
It's not just being kind
to our future colleagues

00:58:07.370 --> 00:58:09.620
and future designers that
need to reference these.

00:58:09.620 --> 00:58:11.720
It's a legal obligation

00:58:11.720 --> 00:58:13.990
to provide these records
for long-term access.

00:58:13.990 --> 00:58:15.340
And so it's a call to arms,

00:58:15.340 --> 00:58:17.980
not only for the preservation
community, but for designers

00:58:17.980 --> 00:58:20.560
who are agreeing -- who are
signing these contracts, saying,

00:58:20.560 --> 00:58:22.280
"Yep, I will definitely
give this to you

00:58:22.280 --> 00:58:25.980
in various level of
detail BIM mode."

00:58:25.980 --> 00:58:27.280
Yowza. All right.

00:58:27.280 --> 00:58:29.390
You need to, like, have a
way to do that, and you need

00:58:29.390 --> 00:58:31.310
to help educate the
person who's claiming

00:58:31.310 --> 00:58:36.090
that they want this file to
then be able to receive it

00:58:36.090 --> 00:58:37.730
and protect it for
the long term.

00:58:37.730 --> 00:58:39.810
Because that's the whole point,
is that they want to move

00:58:39.810 --> 00:58:42.970
that one file to, you know,
rule them all, sort of thing.

00:58:42.970 --> 00:58:44.270
That's what Revit's promise --

00:58:44.270 --> 00:58:46.120
or, not Revit, but
BIM's promise,

00:58:46.120 --> 00:58:49.100
was that if I have this
building information model,

00:58:49.100 --> 00:58:50.950
I can have the designer
design it.

00:58:50.950 --> 00:58:52.470
They can give it
to the contractor.

00:58:52.470 --> 00:58:54.670
The contractor can build it,
add whatever notes they need

00:58:54.670 --> 00:58:56.310
to in the process, and
then they can hand it

00:58:56.310 --> 00:58:57.610
to the facilities manager.

00:58:57.610 --> 00:58:59.790
And that's a really
beautiful idea.

00:58:59.790 --> 00:59:02.270
We're just not there yet,
but the deliverable --

00:59:02.270 --> 00:59:03.850
that contract deliverable
is the thing that's going

00:59:03.850 --> 00:59:05.150
to get us there.

00:59:05.150 --> 00:59:07.630
Because there's no
other way to ensure

00:59:07.630 --> 00:59:10.600
that something will get done
unless there is a very huge

00:59:10.600 --> 00:59:14.400
amount of liability to
not do it the right way.

00:59:14.400 --> 00:59:18.000
So I know that's not a very
exciting way to end that,

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:19.900
but it is -- I think
it is really hopeful,

00:59:19.900 --> 00:59:22.680
and I hope you also think so.

