01:01:32.540 --> 01:01:34.290
And then the next thing
is figuring out how --

01:01:34.290 --> 01:01:37.470
how do we make this so that
it can be long-term access,

01:01:37.470 --> 01:01:41.340
and it's not dependent on if
it was a 2016 or a 2017 file?

01:01:41.340 --> 01:01:45.260
Because corruption does
happen at that point.

01:01:45.260 --> 01:01:46.770
Yeah. Yeah.

01:01:46.770 --> 01:01:48.070
&gt;&gt; Kate Murray: Thank you.

01:01:48.070 --> 01:01:49.370
Mike --

01:01:49.370 --> 01:01:51.200
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: Well, I might
add something real quick,

01:01:51.200 --> 01:01:54.580
which is that if there are any
software vendors in the room,

01:01:54.580 --> 01:01:56.140
that means there's
a business case

01:01:56.140 --> 01:01:58.820
for licensing us
your old software,

01:01:58.820 --> 01:02:01.860
and not just librarians
and archivists.

01:02:01.860 --> 01:02:04.770
It does come in handy,
and we would pay,

01:02:04.770 --> 01:02:08.630
if there was an option to.

01:02:08.630 --> 01:02:09.930
&gt;&gt; Aliza Leventhal: Hint.

01:02:09.930 --> 01:02:13.030
&gt;&gt; Really, good luck.

01:02:13.030 --> 01:02:17.400
&gt;&gt; Kate Murray: The
mic is on the way.

01:02:17.400 --> 01:02:22.440
&gt;&gt; Aliza, you talked a little
about problems of assessing

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:26.000
or determining ownership
in the cloud environment,

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:27.300
and I thought that
was fascinating.

01:02:27.300 --> 01:02:33.070
And I wondered if Katie or
Tim had any comments on issues

01:02:33.070 --> 01:02:37.490
about the same problem
with respect

01:02:37.490 --> 01:02:43.900
to the earlier periods
that you described.

01:02:43.900 --> 01:02:46.310
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: Probably not
much cloud in the '70s, yeah?

01:02:46.310 --> 01:02:47.610
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer: Yeah.

01:02:47.610 --> 01:02:49.690
Yeah. Well, but not the
cloud, but file ownership --

01:02:49.690 --> 01:02:50.990
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: Right,
ownership, okay.

01:02:50.990 --> 01:02:53.720
&gt;&gt; Question doesn't go so
much to the cloud as it does

01:02:53.720 --> 01:02:56.630
to issues about who owns what,

01:02:56.630 --> 01:02:59.480
and to what extent
they appear even

01:02:59.480 --> 01:03:02.940
in the pre-cloud environment.

01:03:02.940 --> 01:03:04.240
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer: I
think there's always going

01:03:04.240 --> 01:03:07.610
to be issues of who owns what,
but I think in most cases,

01:03:07.610 --> 01:03:11.930
it'll come down to -- you
know, those were the products

01:03:11.930 --> 01:03:13.710
of the firm, and so
that they own them.

01:03:13.710 --> 01:03:20.200
And they have then an ability to
hand over rights to those files.

01:03:20.200 --> 01:03:24.210
I don't know -- in the case of
where I work, I'm dealing mostly

01:03:24.210 --> 01:03:27.570
with printed documents, as
opposed to softwares [sic].

01:03:27.570 --> 01:03:30.830
Tim has more experience with
software from this period.

01:03:30.830 --> 01:03:33.100
I don't know if you've run
into this particular issue.

01:03:33.100 --> 01:03:36.390
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: I don't think we
run into an issue of ownership

01:03:36.390 --> 01:03:39.790
with the -- well,
there's an issue --

01:03:39.790 --> 01:03:41.550
there's a question about
ownership of software

01:03:41.550 --> 01:03:44.940
and transferability of licenses,
if we get old files as well

01:03:44.940 --> 01:03:47.300
as installation media
for old software.

01:03:47.300 --> 01:03:49.740
And that's a thing that quite a
lot of people are talking about,

01:03:49.740 --> 01:03:52.140
who are quite a lot more
legally qualified than me.

01:03:52.140 --> 01:03:55.030
So I'll just leave that there.

01:03:55.030 --> 01:03:58.750
But otherwise, I don't
think much ownership issue

01:03:58.750 --> 01:04:00.050
on that level.

01:04:00.050 --> 01:04:01.880
One thing is that, you know,
there's always a question,

01:04:01.880 --> 01:04:04.700
but I think this was true
before, of whether, you know,

01:04:04.700 --> 01:04:07.090
the architects can also give
us the engineering records

01:04:07.090 --> 01:04:08.390
and all that.

01:04:08.390 --> 01:04:09.690
And that depends
on their contracts,

01:04:09.690 --> 01:04:11.330
and how they've handled that.

01:04:11.330 --> 01:04:16.610
So that's sort of a
case-by-case issue.

01:04:16.610 --> 01:04:20.460
Yeah. I think, in terms of
accessibility to content,

01:04:20.460 --> 01:04:24.220
though, it's very similar in
that right now, I'm spending --

01:04:24.220 --> 01:04:27.630
my team is spending quite a
lot of time basically, like,

01:04:27.630 --> 01:04:29.870
disk imaging old media,
everything from, like,

01:04:29.870 --> 01:04:33.660
zip disks, and CDs, and floppy
disks, and SyQuest cartridges,

01:04:33.660 --> 01:04:36.690
and whatever as, like, overhead

01:04:36.690 --> 01:04:39.560
to actually getting
access to the content.

01:04:39.560 --> 01:04:41.930
And I think that
overhead is remaining.

01:04:41.930 --> 01:04:43.660
It's just changing, where
now it's going to be,

01:04:43.660 --> 01:04:44.960
you have to figure
out how to get

01:04:44.960 --> 01:04:46.860
into these third-party
servers managed

01:04:46.860 --> 01:04:50.860
by other people, and
get the data out.

01:04:50.860 --> 01:04:53.050
And, you know, it's not just
us that's dealing with this.

01:04:53.050 --> 01:04:56.850
The digital forensics community
is really seeing a change

01:04:56.850 --> 01:04:58.740
in how they work,
from going to, like,

01:04:58.740 --> 01:05:01.580
evidence that's physically
inscribed on a disk

01:05:01.580 --> 01:05:04.010
to transactions being
on third-party,

01:05:04.010 --> 01:05:06.070
corporate-owned cloud servers.

01:05:06.070 --> 01:05:08.270
And figuring out, like, how --

01:05:08.270 --> 01:05:11.590
you know, it requires a whole
change in the way that you work,

01:05:11.590 --> 01:05:14.880
but that's just always true.

01:05:14.880 --> 01:05:18.250
You know, formats evolve,
and we evolve with them.

01:05:18.250 --> 01:05:19.550
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer: And
I've had other concerns,

01:05:19.550 --> 01:05:20.850
I guess, lately.

01:05:20.850 --> 01:05:22.420
I've been thinking a lot
about privacy and security,

01:05:22.420 --> 01:05:25.990
and providing access
to just any sort

01:05:25.990 --> 01:05:27.890
of building documentation
in general.

01:05:27.890 --> 01:05:29.240
So this is something
I'd probably

01:05:29.240 --> 01:05:30.980
like to work a little
further on,

01:05:30.980 --> 01:05:32.280
to think about this
kind of issue.

01:05:32.280 --> 01:05:34.040
But I think that's one
thing to keep in mind, too,

01:05:34.040 --> 01:05:36.590
is we're always talking
about data about buildings,

01:05:36.590 --> 01:05:39.930
or about the built environment,
and ways that we might want

01:05:39.930 --> 01:05:44.190
to be sensitive to, or need
to be legally responsible

01:05:44.190 --> 01:05:46.740
for what we provide
access to in terms

01:05:46.740 --> 01:05:49.390
of privately owned structures.

01:05:49.390 --> 01:05:53.760
And that may have security
issues for, you know,

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:56.920
individuals, or society
in general.

01:05:56.920 --> 01:06:02.330
So that's, I guess, where
I'll leave off on that.

01:06:02.330 --> 01:06:05.790
&gt;&gt; I've got one here.

01:06:05.790 --> 01:06:07.520
&gt;&gt; Hi, Kate, Tim, and Aliza.

01:06:07.520 --> 01:06:08.820
It's Kurt Helfric
[assumed spelling] --

01:06:08.820 --> 01:06:10.120
&gt;&gt; Aliza Leventhal: Hi, Kurt.

01:06:10.120 --> 01:06:11.420
&gt;&gt; -- and I just
want to thank you all

01:06:11.420 --> 01:06:12.720
for a fantastic presentation.

01:06:12.720 --> 01:06:15.260
I mean, I think you've really
shown us so many things

01:06:15.260 --> 01:06:17.980
that some people remember
maybe way back in the day,

01:06:17.980 --> 01:06:20.490
but you've given us a
really great overview

01:06:20.490 --> 01:06:22.040
and assessment from today.

01:06:22.040 --> 01:06:24.000
So congratulations on that.

