01:06:27.780 --> 01:06:32.650
about the contractual
obligations as a driving force

01:06:32.650 --> 01:06:35.000
for trying to get
some of these things

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:37.460
in standards that we can accept.

01:06:37.460 --> 01:06:38.870
I do want to share
with you something --

01:06:38.870 --> 01:06:41.180
in my current position,
this isn't true, but in --

01:06:41.180 --> 01:06:44.760
previously, at Santa
Barbara, we were very careful

01:06:44.760 --> 01:06:46.640
as collecting repositories
never to claim

01:06:46.640 --> 01:06:48.020
to be the legal repository

01:06:48.020 --> 01:06:50.490
for the materials
we were collecting.

01:06:50.490 --> 01:06:52.130
And I think -- I
want to remind people

01:06:52.130 --> 01:06:57.350
that that's still definitely the
way for research collections.

01:06:57.350 --> 01:07:00.630
The question I had,
really, is --

01:07:00.630 --> 01:07:03.250
I'm just going to
throw this out to you.

01:07:03.250 --> 01:07:06.390
Do you think it's going to take
some serious legal lawsuits

01:07:06.390 --> 01:07:11.970
to actually be able to then
get these things developed,

01:07:11.970 --> 01:07:16.330
or is it something we can
really reach out and work on?

01:07:16.330 --> 01:07:18.710
&gt;&gt; Aliza Leventhal: So I really
hope it doesn't take that,

01:07:18.710 --> 01:07:20.010
because it's terrifying.

01:07:20.010 --> 01:07:24.270
But, for instance, the
$6.1 billion revenue loss

01:07:24.270 --> 01:07:27.860
that happened for
Airbus in 2006,

01:07:27.860 --> 01:07:29.360
they had a problem with CATIA.

01:07:29.360 --> 01:07:30.930
They had two different
versions being used.

01:07:30.930 --> 01:07:32.760
One was in Germany, one was in
France, and then when they tried

01:07:32.760 --> 01:07:36.270
to build the plane, the
wires weren't long enough.

01:07:36.270 --> 01:07:38.650
Whoops. And so, all of
these flights got delayed,

01:07:38.650 --> 01:07:40.830
and they had to, you know,
change a bunch of things over.

01:07:40.830 --> 01:07:42.130
And these planes were
supposed to be able

01:07:42.130 --> 01:07:44.180
to handle double the capacity,
and would be able to fly

01:07:44.180 --> 01:07:45.820
around the world
in one tank of gas.

01:07:45.820 --> 01:07:47.730
It was, like, you know,
this crazy awesome new plane

01:07:47.730 --> 01:07:50.470
that they were making, and $6.1
billion is definitely a reason

01:07:50.470 --> 01:07:52.170
why LOTAR now exists.

01:07:52.170 --> 01:07:53.590
Super. Thank you, LOTAR.

01:07:53.590 --> 01:07:55.330
But -- which also
sets a precedent.

01:07:55.330 --> 01:07:58.530
It's an ISO standard for
the aerospace industry.

01:07:58.530 --> 01:08:01.230
Sorry for everyone who isn't
as much of a nerd as I am,

01:08:01.230 --> 01:08:03.140
as excited about LOTAR.

01:08:03.140 --> 01:08:06.160
But that, like -- so that
set a precedent for us.

01:08:06.160 --> 01:08:09.620
And so, luckily, we have someone
to talk to us today, here --

01:08:09.620 --> 01:08:11.850
yay -- a little bit about
what that experience is.

01:08:11.850 --> 01:08:14.720
But I think that my
Chicken Little schtick

01:08:14.720 --> 01:08:16.760
for quite a while has been,
well, it already happened

01:08:16.760 --> 01:08:19.030
to somebody else, with
something that's very similar

01:08:19.030 --> 01:08:20.330
to what we're dealing with.

01:08:20.330 --> 01:08:23.020
Shouldn't we just be able to now
proactively address this issue?

01:08:23.020 --> 01:08:26.570
And I'm not quite sure
we're there quite yet,

01:08:26.570 --> 01:08:28.160
but we certainly have
the momentum now.

01:08:28.160 --> 01:08:31.930
And I think we're articulating
it in a much more effective way

01:08:31.930 --> 01:08:34.530
to capture attention for this,

01:08:34.530 --> 01:08:37.230
and having the contract
deliverable also be pushing

01:08:37.230 --> 01:08:40.210
at the same time -- we're
hitting a critical moment

01:08:40.210 --> 01:08:42.480
where it's now about
identifying what does

01:08:42.480 --> 01:08:44.700
that actually look like.

01:08:44.700 --> 01:08:47.750
Because, as Tim said,
STEP is a great idea,

01:08:47.750 --> 01:08:49.860
but it's not really realistic.

01:08:49.860 --> 01:08:52.030
Especially -- I work within
a firm that is, you know --

01:08:52.030 --> 01:08:54.440
at any one time, they could
be working on five projects

01:08:54.440 --> 01:08:57.150
as a person -- not as the firm.

01:08:57.150 --> 01:08:59.250
But -- and so, like, that --

01:08:59.250 --> 01:09:03.130
that level of chaos and
hecticness, them to be able

01:09:03.130 --> 01:09:05.430
to then apply COBI metadata

01:09:05.430 --> 01:09:08.110
on a daily basis seems
very unrealistic.

01:09:08.110 --> 01:09:09.630
And so we have to come
up with some way --

01:09:09.630 --> 01:09:12.620
again, hint, vendors
-- that we should --

01:09:12.620 --> 01:09:16.010
the software should be able
to account for this for them.

01:09:16.010 --> 01:09:18.510
Because just like
Microsoft finally came

01:09:18.510 --> 01:09:19.930
and said, "You know what?

01:09:19.930 --> 01:09:22.110
We're going to stop messing
with it every two years,

01:09:22.110 --> 01:09:24.350
so that you can't have
access to it in a forward

01:09:24.350 --> 01:09:25.860
and backward compatibility

01:09:25.860 --> 01:09:28.410
with massive data
loss or corruption."

01:09:28.410 --> 01:09:30.720
And I hope that that's where
we move, in that direction,

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:32.250
so that there's just a
little bit more safety

01:09:32.250 --> 01:09:33.550
and security in the files.

01:09:33.550 --> 01:09:37.080
The concern really is about all
this stuff that came before,

01:09:37.080 --> 01:09:40.300
because we're at a moment where
we can help, as a groundswell,

01:09:40.300 --> 01:09:42.700
shift it moving forward
so that software's better,

01:09:42.700 --> 01:09:44.000
but we still have to deal

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:46.010
with all the crazy
that happened before.

01:09:46.010 --> 01:09:48.950
And that's why we
have Tim and Katie.

01:09:48.950 --> 01:09:50.960
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: I do think that's
an important distinction,

01:09:50.960 --> 01:09:52.390
though, and it's one we
should keep in mind today,

01:09:52.390 --> 01:09:53.940
that there's sort of, like --

01:09:53.940 --> 01:09:56.630
what are the best practices we
can lay down moving forward,

01:09:56.630 --> 01:09:59.050
and how can we try to
make it more likely

01:09:59.050 --> 01:10:02.220
that people will use
IFC and, you know,

01:10:02.220 --> 01:10:03.640
document their workflows?

01:10:03.640 --> 01:10:07.760
And thinking about contract
deliverables is a really --

01:10:07.760 --> 01:10:10.140
you know, it's a really
important factor in there.

01:10:10.140 --> 01:10:12.550
I think looking at Scandinavia,
it's also very interesting that,

01:10:12.550 --> 01:10:14.430
you know, there are
countries out there

01:10:14.430 --> 01:10:17.410
that are requiring BIM files,
not just for the deliverables,

01:10:17.410 --> 01:10:18.980
but also for, like,
competition entries.

01:10:18.980 --> 01:10:22.630
And it sort of changes
how things work.

01:10:22.630 --> 01:10:26.520
But, you know, in a certain way,

01:10:26.520 --> 01:10:28.660
we have all this older
stuff to deal with, too.

01:10:28.660 --> 01:10:32.320
I think it's extremely
interesting.

01:10:32.320 --> 01:10:36.680
Maybe it's because it's what I
deal with the most, but yeah,

01:10:36.680 --> 01:10:41.420
we do kind of need two
strategies, at least.

01:10:41.420 --> 01:10:43.210
And so we're almost talking

01:10:43.210 --> 01:10:45.070
about two separate
things at that point.

01:10:45.070 --> 01:10:46.800
There are a lot of
issues that continue,

01:10:46.800 --> 01:10:48.330
especially around file formats,

01:10:48.330 --> 01:10:51.450
and their interoperability,
and their longevity.

01:10:51.450 --> 01:10:55.850
But, you know, the solution
that we do for creative,

01:10:55.850 --> 01:10:57.880
small design projects that
never got built in, like,

01:10:57.880 --> 01:11:00.310
1992 is going to be a little
different than the solutions

01:11:00.310 --> 01:11:03.270
that we have for, like,
massive infrastructural projects

01:11:03.270 --> 01:11:04.870
in 2018.

01:11:04.870 --> 01:11:07.040
And that's okay, but it
means we're kind of talking

01:11:07.040 --> 01:11:09.290
about separate things sometimes.

01:11:09.290 --> 01:11:10.720
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer: That have
some continuity between them,

01:11:10.720 --> 01:11:14.800
hopefully, in the long term,
from a historian's perspective.

