&gt;&gt; Aliza Leventhal: Yeah.

01:13:05.740 --> 01:13:07.040
Because the appraisal
grid needs to be updated.

01:13:07.040 --> 01:13:08.340
Waverly [assumed spelling]

01:13:08.340 --> 01:13:09.640
and Tonnie [assumed spelling]
have a wonderful book.

01:13:09.640 --> 01:13:10.940
If you haven't read
it, you really should.

01:13:10.940 --> 01:13:13.560
It's basically the
architecture of records --

01:13:13.560 --> 01:13:16.930
architecture and construction
records management book.

01:13:16.930 --> 01:13:18.940
It's great, and they have
an appraisal grid in there

01:13:18.940 --> 01:13:21.620
that is wonderful, but is
very focused on analog.

01:13:21.620 --> 01:13:24.410
And so the important
thing I've been discussing

01:13:24.410 --> 01:13:28.370
with Waverly lately is how to
update that, because it's not

01:13:28.370 --> 01:13:29.670
that they're create --

01:13:29.670 --> 01:13:31.520
that designers are
creating new records --

01:13:31.520 --> 01:13:35.100
as in, like, the construction
process hasn't changed

01:13:35.100 --> 01:13:36.400
that dramatically.

01:13:36.400 --> 01:13:38.490
It's not now you
offer, like, a, like,

01:13:38.490 --> 01:13:40.180
hologram of what
you're producing.

01:13:40.180 --> 01:13:42.160
But even then, like,
we still have plans.

01:13:42.160 --> 01:13:44.320
You still have illustrative
plans.

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:47.580
You still have renderings,
and perspectives,

01:13:47.580 --> 01:13:49.050
and elevations, and details.

01:13:49.050 --> 01:13:50.810
All those things
are still existing.

01:13:50.810 --> 01:13:52.940
It's just understanding
what are the file types

01:13:52.940 --> 01:13:55.800
that are most likely going to be
the case, and what does it mean

01:13:55.800 --> 01:13:58.670
to say, "Keep forever,"
versus, "You know,

01:13:58.670 --> 01:14:00.310
I don't need your
punch list for --

01:14:00.310 --> 01:14:02.070
like, after statute
of limitations."

01:14:02.070 --> 01:14:05.010
Like, punch list is not that
necessary for me to hold onto.

01:14:05.010 --> 01:14:07.860
Could be terribly interesting
for research, but, you know,

01:14:07.860 --> 01:14:12.930
making the decision of the --

01:14:12.930 --> 01:14:15.500
what records we still
need are consistent,

01:14:15.500 --> 01:14:16.800
but it's now changed.

01:14:16.800 --> 01:14:18.980
Because instead of saying, "You
need the full set," you now say,

01:14:18.980 --> 01:14:22.940
"I want the central file for
Revit and all of its extras."

01:14:22.940 --> 01:14:25.340
And I can't forget that
there's a bunch of things

01:14:25.340 --> 01:14:26.640
that are connected to this file,

01:14:26.640 --> 01:14:28.120
because if it's not
packaged correctly,

01:14:28.120 --> 01:14:31.810
having the Revit central file
and none of the families,

01:14:31.810 --> 01:14:34.660
like -- so that would be like
not having windows or walls

01:14:34.660 --> 01:14:37.520
or furniture, which are
what families are in Revit.

01:14:37.520 --> 01:14:39.830
So then you just kind
of have, like, a box.

01:14:39.830 --> 01:14:42.080
That's the kind of
stuff that I think needs

01:14:42.080 --> 01:14:43.640
to be sussed out more.

01:14:43.640 --> 01:14:45.610
And so the appraisal
conversations I've had

01:14:45.610 --> 01:14:48.700
with people in my firm haven't
gotten quite to that level yet,

01:14:48.700 --> 01:14:51.580
because we're still waiting
for our files to be old enough

01:14:51.580 --> 01:14:53.310
to need to be assessed that way.

01:14:53.310 --> 01:14:56.820
But when talking to project
teams, like, it's really --

01:14:56.820 --> 01:14:58.800
there's a difference
between your working files

01:14:58.800 --> 01:15:01.190
and your deliverable, and
the deliverable's the thing

01:15:01.190 --> 01:15:03.930
that we're legally required to
provide if something happens.

01:15:03.930 --> 01:15:08.080
And so making sure everyone
in the room understands that,

01:15:08.080 --> 01:15:11.470
going back to Kurt's point of,
like, the legal requirements

01:15:11.470 --> 01:15:15.120
for the files, is
really important here.

01:15:15.120 --> 01:15:16.420
&gt;&gt; Tim Walsh: Yeah.

01:15:16.420 --> 01:15:17.720
I think there's a couple
things to consider.

01:15:17.720 --> 01:15:20.140
One that may not be so
obvious for the people

01:15:20.140 --> 01:15:23.420
who don't do sort of,
like, digital preservation

01:15:23.420 --> 01:15:27.230
in the cultural sphere is the
significant overhead that goes

01:15:27.230 --> 01:15:29.380
into preserving files
for the long-term.

01:15:29.380 --> 01:15:30.680
Like, basically all

01:15:30.680 --> 01:15:32.810
of our digital preservation
best practices require lots,

01:15:32.810 --> 01:15:35.320
and lots, and lots of
replication of files.

01:15:35.320 --> 01:15:37.560
So if we're talking to a
donor, and they're like, "Yeah,

01:15:37.560 --> 01:15:39.630
I want to give you everything
that's on my servers,

01:15:39.630 --> 01:15:42.580
and it's 10 terabytes," that
-- in our underlying storage,

01:15:42.580 --> 01:15:45.110
when we account for the
fact that formats are kept

01:15:45.110 --> 01:15:47.760
in the original format, and
also migrated to file formats

01:15:47.760 --> 01:15:50.550
that are more likely to be
usable over the long term.

01:15:50.550 --> 01:15:52.550
And then all of those
things are replicated

01:15:52.550 --> 01:15:55.780
across different media types,
and geographically replicated,

01:15:55.780 --> 01:15:57.820
so that we don't have a
single point of failure.

01:15:57.820 --> 01:16:00.280
We can do things like audit the
files over time, restore them

01:16:00.280 --> 01:16:01.800
from backups if they change.

01:16:01.800 --> 01:16:03.180
All of that has a
significant overhead,

01:16:03.180 --> 01:16:04.480
and it' significantly expensive.

01:16:04.480 --> 01:16:07.110
So it means that we have to
be more careful, versus, like,

01:16:07.110 --> 01:16:10.830
a paper drawing that goes into
a climate-controlled vault.

01:16:10.830 --> 01:16:16.170
I think it, again, sort of just
depends on the material, though.

01:16:16.170 --> 01:16:19.010
Part of it is also -- like, I
agree with Aliza that, you know,

01:16:19.010 --> 01:16:21.970
thinking about sending --
updating the appraisal grid,

01:16:21.970 --> 01:16:25.330
so that we can think about
what's actually worth keeping,

01:16:25.330 --> 01:16:28.470
is really important, that
there are a lot of things

01:16:28.470 --> 01:16:30.730
like externally-referenced
files and dependencies

01:16:30.730 --> 01:16:32.030
that you don't want to break.

01:16:32.030 --> 01:16:33.330
So that means that you have
to know what you're doing

01:16:33.330 --> 01:16:35.800
when you're interacting with the
material, but at the same time,

01:16:35.800 --> 01:16:37.790
with paper records, we
never kept anything, either.

01:16:37.790 --> 01:16:39.470
It's sort of the difference
between an archivist

01:16:39.470 --> 01:16:42.180
and being a hoarder, is,
like, you identify the things

01:16:42.180 --> 01:16:44.710
that have permanent
value, and you keep those.

01:16:44.710 --> 01:16:46.590
But we don't need to keep
every draft of everything.

01:16:46.590 --> 01:16:48.580
We don't need to
-- so this diagram

01:16:48.580 --> 01:16:50.480
that Aliza showed, it's big.

01:16:50.480 --> 01:16:51.780
It's complex.

01:16:51.780 --> 01:16:53.080
It doesn't mean that we have

01:16:53.080 --> 01:16:54.750
to keep everything that's ever
been created in perpetuity,

01:16:54.750 --> 01:16:56.560
especially in this world

01:16:56.560 --> 01:16:58.250
where things are,
like, more networked.

01:16:58.250 --> 01:16:59.600
The files are bigger.

01:16:59.600 --> 01:17:01.500
So I think we have a lot of
critical reflection to do

01:17:01.500 --> 01:17:04.030
about that, and it's really
good to have a standard

01:17:04.030 --> 01:17:05.330
like the appraisal grid.

01:17:05.330 --> 01:17:08.390
I also think it just
depends on your institution.

01:17:08.390 --> 01:17:09.910
Like, who are your researchers,

01:17:09.910 --> 01:17:12.690
and what are they
going to be doing?

01:17:12.690 --> 01:17:14.790
If you want to make sure

01:17:14.790 --> 01:17:17.520
that you have plans
around, PDFs might be fine.

01:17:17.520 --> 01:17:19.340
If you want to make sure
that people can go in

01:17:19.340 --> 01:17:21.330
and reuse the data, then
you're going to have

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:24.320
to keep something a lot heavier.

01:17:24.320 --> 01:17:27.960
So it all really
sort of depends.

01:17:27.960 --> 01:17:30.040
I'll say for the old
stuff, our strategy,

01:17:30.040 --> 01:17:33.440
largely through a project called
Archaeology of the Digital

01:17:33.440 --> 01:17:37.230
that the CCA did with Greg Lynn
over a period of about five,

01:17:37.230 --> 01:17:39.100
was basically to
identify the key projects

01:17:39.100 --> 01:17:40.870
that we thought were
interesting and innovative

01:17:40.870 --> 01:17:43.970
from the early days
and go grab everything.

01:17:43.970 --> 01:17:45.360
But that's a lot more feasible

01:17:45.360 --> 01:17:47.580
when everything is a
computer that's been sitting

01:17:47.580 --> 01:17:50.570
in someone's closet for
a while, or, like --

01:17:50.570 --> 01:17:54.920
you know, I think the largest
one is probably about 500 gigs.

01:17:54.920 --> 01:17:56.940
A lot of them are,
like, 10 gigs.

01:17:56.940 --> 01:17:59.960
So there, we can just kind of
go in and vacuum everything up,

01:17:59.960 --> 01:18:02.360
and I think for the old
stuff, we kind of need to do

01:18:02.360 --> 01:18:04.080
that when we have the chance.

01:18:04.080 --> 01:18:05.670
Because, collectively,

01:18:05.670 --> 01:18:07.480
collecting institutions
should've been doing this for,

01:18:07.480 --> 01:18:11.720
like, 10 or 15 years by
now, and it's kind of close

01:18:11.720 --> 01:18:13.020
to too late for some of it.

01:18:13.020 --> 01:18:14.370
Like, the media's
already degrading.

01:18:14.370 --> 01:18:16.590
People already retired,
moved on, whatever.

01:18:16.590 --> 01:18:22.110
For the newer stuff, we have
to be a lot more careful.

01:18:22.110 --> 01:18:25.030
Like -- because when we
talk to donors now, yeah,

01:18:25.030 --> 01:18:28.140
usually the assumption at the
beginning on their part is

01:18:28.140 --> 01:18:29.440
that we'll want everything,

01:18:29.440 --> 01:18:31.540
because we're collecting
the total archive.

01:18:31.540 --> 01:18:32.920
But we can't afford that.

01:18:32.920 --> 01:18:34.220
It's not feasible.

01:18:34.220 --> 01:18:35.520
I don't think it's good
for our researchers

01:18:35.520 --> 01:18:40.280
to just present them with,
like, you know, 700,000 files.

01:18:40.280 --> 01:18:43.910
No matter how you index
it, that's not going

01:18:43.910 --> 01:18:46.000
to be helpful to anybody.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:48.850
So, yeah. But it's
a work in progress.

01:18:48.850 --> 01:18:50.630
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer: Yeah,
just to add a little bit more,

01:18:50.630 --> 01:18:53.590
