01:24:39.880 --> 01:24:41.180
memorialized anywhere.

01:24:41.180 --> 01:24:44.470
And frankly, the technologies
don't exist to enable

01:24:44.470 --> 01:24:48.380
that in the first place,
and I think the key thing

01:24:48.380 --> 01:24:50.430
that was definitely
made clear on the --

01:24:50.430 --> 01:24:56.030
in the 2010s is this
unique production process.

01:24:56.030 --> 01:24:59.340
We often use the same
tools project to project,

01:24:59.340 --> 01:25:02.010
but there is certainly no
such thing as a standard

01:25:02.010 --> 01:25:05.230
when it comes to what
information is captured,

01:25:05.230 --> 01:25:07.500
how information is developed.

01:25:07.500 --> 01:25:13.220
We're very much a right tool
for the project sort of a firm.

01:25:13.220 --> 01:25:15.980
That certainly doesn't
make it easy for us

01:25:15.980 --> 01:25:18.400
on the technology side to
make it easier for the teams

01:25:18.400 --> 01:25:20.010
to interoperate between
platforms.

01:25:20.010 --> 01:25:21.680
And that actually is --

01:25:21.680 --> 01:25:24.980
the linked discussion
we're having here is,

01:25:24.980 --> 01:25:28.300
the business drivers are
starting to make sense for us

01:25:28.300 --> 01:25:32.170
to think about making
data more interoperable,

01:25:32.170 --> 01:25:35.870
and what are the things that we
need to start to do to do that?

01:25:35.870 --> 01:25:38.440
And that, to me, at least,
is a part of the discussion

01:25:38.440 --> 01:25:41.770
about how an archival
process could become easier,

01:25:41.770 --> 01:25:46.980
because I'm -- generally sort
of look to the, you know,

01:25:46.980 --> 01:25:49.220
sort of aerospace
industries and others.

01:25:49.220 --> 01:25:52.950
And I think the business drivers
have made it easier to start

01:25:52.950 --> 01:25:58.220
to have these discussions
right now, where we're unable

01:25:58.220 --> 01:26:01.300
to find those -- find the
benefits without starting

01:26:01.300 --> 01:26:03.150
to think about those long-term.

01:26:03.150 --> 01:26:07.690
So from a -- just a
generally way of working --

01:26:07.690 --> 01:26:10.320
and I think we can go in
many directions with these,

01:26:10.320 --> 01:26:14.030
but 95% of our projects
are model-based.

01:26:14.030 --> 01:26:16.220
We're moving to a
global file system.

01:26:16.220 --> 01:26:23.160
So the reason I'm bringing
that up is, from an archiving

01:26:23.160 --> 01:26:26.300
as a result of work strategy,
we're moving to a system

01:26:26.300 --> 01:26:29.000
that will give us
backups every 15 minutes.

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:31.810
In everybody else's
minds, that's perfect.

01:26:31.810 --> 01:26:33.420
I don't have to think
about anything anymore.

01:26:33.420 --> 01:26:34.970
I just work, and it's backed up.

01:26:34.970 --> 01:26:39.320
And I have a million copies of
stuff every time it's changed.

01:26:39.320 --> 01:26:42.260
And it certainly
will only get worse.

01:26:42.260 --> 01:26:46.420
We're not -- from the big
design and engineering firms,

01:26:46.420 --> 01:26:48.580
they're certainly not the first
entity to start to do this,

01:26:48.580 --> 01:26:51.190
but the notion of, you
know, every 15 minutes,

01:26:51.190 --> 01:26:52.840
you have a snapshot
of everything you did

01:26:52.840 --> 01:26:57.720
for perpetuity -- and that's
sort of our view of --

01:26:57.720 --> 01:26:59.020
it's a short-term view.

01:26:59.020 --> 01:27:00.630
But that's definitely
the way we're going.

01:27:00.630 --> 01:27:05.330
The idea of archiving things
just doesn't make sense

01:27:05.330 --> 01:27:06.630
to people.

01:27:06.630 --> 01:27:08.050
So it's -- well,
we did the work.

01:27:08.050 --> 01:27:09.350
It's saved.

01:27:09.350 --> 01:27:11.840
I can go back in a slider,
and see where it was in time.

01:27:11.840 --> 01:27:13.480
Whether you have the
information around it

01:27:13.480 --> 01:27:16.750
that describes its state, and
which -- you know, because it's,

01:27:16.750 --> 01:27:19.690
you know, 9:45 or 10:00
a.m. three years ago,

01:27:19.690 --> 01:27:21.260
who could possibly know?

01:27:21.260 --> 01:27:24.160
We are starting to do --

01:27:24.160 --> 01:27:27.380
the popular term in the
industry is data lake processes,

01:27:27.380 --> 01:27:31.040
but some approaches
are to use data lakes

01:27:31.040 --> 01:27:32.660
and just take everything
and put them somewhere,

01:27:32.660 --> 01:27:35.500
which is very much an archive --

01:27:35.500 --> 01:27:38.270
don't do anything before
processing the data

01:27:38.270 --> 01:27:39.720
archive strategy.

01:27:39.720 --> 01:27:43.920
Because we're starting to
see a business driver --

01:27:43.920 --> 01:27:46.140
and this is the piece
that I'm most focused on,

01:27:46.140 --> 01:27:48.830
is a business driver to
making the data interoperable

01:27:48.830 --> 01:27:50.160
or accessible.

01:27:50.160 --> 01:27:52.080
So, simple example.

01:27:52.080 --> 01:27:55.270
We get asked by clients
-- we do hospitals.

01:27:55.270 --> 01:27:57.690
What does the OR look --
what do these ORs look

01:27:57.690 --> 01:28:00.520
like in the last 20
projects you've worked on?

01:28:00.520 --> 01:28:03.370
This is a three-day
intern question, typically.

01:28:03.370 --> 01:28:07.380
That should be a, you know,
half-hour, sit down in front

01:28:07.380 --> 01:28:10.730
of a computer, and
write a query question.

01:28:10.730 --> 01:28:16.570
But that question -- certainly
we can have the non-geometric

01:28:16.570 --> 01:28:19.450
information, but then
you've dissociated

01:28:19.450 --> 01:28:20.750
with it the actual design.

01:28:20.750 --> 01:28:23.250
So from a technology
perspective, we're starting

01:28:23.250 --> 01:28:26.150
to look at tools that will
actually allow us to ask

01:28:26.150 --> 01:28:28.760
that question, and both
get the geometric result

01:28:28.760 --> 01:28:30.060
and the information.

01:28:30.060 --> 01:28:34.580
And that's, to us, a very
beneficial way of, you know,

01:28:34.580 --> 01:28:37.120
sort of as a firm our size,

01:28:37.120 --> 01:28:38.970
thinking about that
sort of problem.

01:28:38.970 --> 01:28:44.920
So we can certainly go into
that further in the discussion.

01:28:44.920 --> 01:28:49.030
And that -- there's a
question that always comes up,

01:28:49.030 --> 01:28:55.150
because buildings -- or, HOK was
one of the original founders,

01:28:55.150 --> 01:28:59.710
along with others, AutoDesk --
I'm blanking on a few others.

01:28:59.710 --> 01:29:04.370
Honeywell -- of AIIAI,
which became Building Smart,

01:29:04.370 --> 01:29:07.480
about whether or not our
processes are IFC-driven,

01:29:07.480 --> 01:29:09.370
you know, using these
open tools.

01:29:09.370 --> 01:29:11.170
One of the things that
we're finding is a lot

01:29:11.170 --> 01:29:13.760
of the processes don't
result in the use of them,

01:29:13.760 --> 01:29:16.820
so we're starting to have
that discussion as well,

01:29:16.820 --> 01:29:20.250
about whether we need to be
more proactive with the industry

01:29:20.250 --> 01:29:22.450
to make IFC part of that.

01:29:22.450 --> 01:29:26.260
So that's a -- would come up
in a question, so I just want

01:29:26.260 --> 01:29:27.970
to make sure I mentioned that.

01:29:27.970 --> 01:29:29.530
So, last one.

01:29:29.530 --> 01:29:34.300
I like cats.

01:29:34.300 --> 01:29:37.080
And this is complete
post-rationalization.

01:29:37.080 --> 01:29:38.700
I just like this one,
but particularly,

01:29:38.700 --> 01:29:41.470
I have a technique I
use in presentations,

01:29:41.470 --> 01:29:45.400
which is actually just
combine the topic of a slide

01:29:45.400 --> 01:29:47.460
with the word cat, and
you search the internet,

01:29:47.460 --> 01:29:49.980
and you can always
find a result.

01:29:49.980 --> 01:29:52.210
There's actually -- in
the image-based result.

01:29:52.210 --> 01:29:56.230
And this one in particular was
obviously laser-scanning cats,

01:29:56.230 --> 01:30:02.190
but it's a very meaningful
-- it's actually, you know,

01:30:02.190 --> 01:30:05.570
in the where we are
thinking about going, and --

01:30:05.570 --> 01:30:08.600
within Building Smart, and
starting to get back into it

01:30:08.600 --> 01:30:10.490
at HOK, the concepts
around linked data

01:30:10.490 --> 01:30:12.690
and semantic web
technologies as a means

01:30:12.690 --> 01:30:15.690
to help describe this context.

01:30:15.690 --> 01:30:18.940
One of the most often used
linked data concepts is cat is

01:30:18.940 --> 01:30:21.080
an animal -- you know,
sort of the diagram.

01:30:21.080 --> 01:30:24.920
So that's a -- like I said, a
very good post-rationalization.

01:30:24.920 --> 01:30:28.200
So I'm going to stop
there, and we'll go

01:30:28.200 --> 01:30:29.500
on to the next presenter.

01:30:29.500 --> 01:30:31.710
And we'll have a
nice conversation.

01:30:31.710 --> 01:30:33.510
Thank you.

