01:32:05.450 --> 01:32:09.050
And that -- 20 tons, you know?

01:32:09.050 --> 01:32:10.350
How many cars is that?

01:32:10.350 --> 01:32:11.710
That's a lot of cars.

01:32:11.710 --> 01:32:16.890
But anyway, despite that
we're in the digital age,

01:32:16.890 --> 01:32:23.530
and the example of the wiring
harness snafu at Airbus,

01:32:23.530 --> 01:32:28.180
using the same CAD system
at two different locations,

01:32:28.180 --> 01:32:31.440
and having problems, is
still pretty typical.

01:32:31.440 --> 01:32:37.780
I think my message today has
to do with interoperability

01:32:37.780 --> 01:32:39.840
through the use of standards.

01:32:39.840 --> 01:32:43.750
The primary standard we use
-- not the only standard,

01:32:43.750 --> 01:32:46.750
but one of the primary
standards we use in aerospace

01:32:46.750 --> 01:32:49.760
and defense is the
ISO STEP standard.

01:32:49.760 --> 01:32:54.120
And I'm going to talk
about two use cases today.

01:32:54.120 --> 01:32:58.470
One has to do with
collaboration between partners,

01:32:58.470 --> 01:33:00.580
and Pratt &amp; Whitney and
Airbus are partners.

01:33:00.580 --> 01:33:05.620
And then also between
OEMs and their suppliers.

01:33:05.620 --> 01:33:08.190
So I guess -- we're --

01:33:08.190 --> 01:33:17.360
y'all have probably seen
the model-based enterprise

01:33:17.360 --> 01:33:18.950
pyramid before.

01:33:18.950 --> 01:33:21.110
You know, we've changed it

01:33:21.110 --> 01:33:26.470
to fit our particular
mode of operation.

01:33:26.470 --> 01:33:28.760
From an archival standpoint,

01:33:28.760 --> 01:33:32.130
the main three things there are
the information requirements

01:33:32.130 --> 01:33:36.650
and business rules, the
process and systems,

01:33:36.650 --> 01:33:40.690
and the repository -- the
retention period and the format.

01:33:40.690 --> 01:33:49.230
One thing that's very important
in the A&amp;D industry to archive,

01:33:49.230 --> 01:33:51.850
and is -- well, I'll
just go ahead and say it,

01:33:51.850 --> 01:33:53.750
and then I'll talk
about it a little bit,

01:33:53.750 --> 01:33:56.340
but it is design intent.

01:33:56.340 --> 01:34:00.770
And design intent takes
many different forms.

01:34:00.770 --> 01:34:06.340
You know, some of them are
relatively easy to digitize,

01:34:06.340 --> 01:34:08.820
like geometric dimensions
and tolerances,

01:34:08.820 --> 01:34:11.940
what we call product
manufacturing information today.

01:34:11.940 --> 01:34:19.370
You know, maybe some of the
systems engineering data,

01:34:19.370 --> 01:34:23.560
maybe some parametrics in the
model, things of that nature.

01:34:23.560 --> 01:34:29.280
And others aren't quite so easy
to digitize and then archive,

01:34:29.280 --> 01:34:33.200
or pass on to one
of your partners.

01:34:36.530 --> 01:34:40.520
The aerospace industry, just
like the building industry,

01:34:40.520 --> 01:34:44.490
has very complex products.

01:34:44.490 --> 01:34:46.500
You know, they have -- you know,

01:34:46.500 --> 01:34:49.270
a simple product only
has thousands of parts.

01:34:49.270 --> 01:34:51.540
A complex products
has tens of thousands

01:34:51.540 --> 01:34:54.240
of parts, maybe a million.

01:34:54.240 --> 01:35:00.000
But as the products get
more complex, it's --

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:04.100
also becomes more complex on
how do you retain that data

01:35:04.100 --> 01:35:06.660
for many years down the road.

01:35:11.570 --> 01:35:14.560
I don't know if I like the
title of this slide or not.

01:35:14.560 --> 01:35:18.090
I would've called it "Just
an Interesting Slide,"

01:35:18.090 --> 01:35:22.380
but you have the various
Boeing aircraft programs

01:35:22.380 --> 01:35:27.270
across the top there, the
767, the 747, the 77 --

01:35:27.270 --> 01:35:30.490
the triple 7, and the 787.

01:35:30.490 --> 01:35:33.210
And the top half
of that chart kind

01:35:33.210 --> 01:35:36.360
of represents the
as-designed view,

01:35:36.360 --> 01:35:40.140
and the bottom represents
the as-manufactured view.

01:35:40.140 --> 01:35:42.270
And if you look at
the numbers --

01:35:42.270 --> 01:35:44.790
I mean, look at the data
volume in the as designed

01:35:44.790 --> 01:35:46.350
and the as manufactured.

01:35:46.350 --> 01:35:49.170
Those are significantly
different numbers.

01:35:49.170 --> 01:35:52.750
One other thing I'll point
out is that, you know,

01:35:52.750 --> 01:35:56.080
you're looking at the parts
per airplane there, and you go,

01:35:56.080 --> 01:35:59.970
"Well, why did it go
down from the triple 7

01:35:59.970 --> 01:36:01.720
to the 787, anyway?"

01:36:01.720 --> 01:36:05.970
And that's because the
more use of composite parts

01:36:05.970 --> 01:36:07.270
in the later aircraft.

01:36:07.270 --> 01:36:11.970
So that causes it to
be down -- to go down.

01:36:19.390 --> 01:36:21.270
One last thing on this,
and this has to do

01:36:21.270 --> 01:36:23.200
with the complexity
of managing data.

01:36:23.200 --> 01:36:29.610
And this is a general
comment, but up until 2005,

01:36:29.610 --> 01:36:33.490
the amount of data
that had been created

01:36:33.490 --> 01:36:36.080
in the world was
something on the order

01:36:36.080 --> 01:36:40.710
of 500 billion gigabytes.

01:36:40.710 --> 01:36:46.090
And very soon, probably
-- maybe we are now --

01:36:46.090 --> 01:36:49.260
we'll be creating that much data
every 10 minutes in the world.

01:36:49.260 --> 01:36:51.560
So --

01:36:55.050 --> 01:37:00.870
-- early example of data
exchange, the Rosetta Stone,

01:37:00.870 --> 01:37:05.680
the same information in
three different languages.

01:37:07.590 --> 01:37:10.030
Evolving technologies --

01:37:10.030 --> 01:37:14.250
and this is kind of
aerospace-centric,

01:37:14.250 --> 01:37:23.900
but something I'm going to
throw in here is the requirement

01:37:23.900 --> 01:37:28.070
by the FAA to provide the
type design data to them,

01:37:28.070 --> 01:37:31.970
or to retain it for
long periods of time.

01:37:31.970 --> 01:37:35.580
And the first generation
was the engineering drawing

01:37:35.580 --> 01:37:39.100
and the authority,
or the -- to the --

01:37:39.100 --> 01:37:42.490
for the FAA was the 2D drawing.

01:37:42.490 --> 01:37:46.760
We're kind of in the end of the
second generation right now.

01:37:46.760 --> 01:37:49.950
You know, we are in a 3D world.

01:37:49.950 --> 01:37:55.340
We were talking last night
that the production folks tend

01:37:55.340 --> 01:37:57.620
to still be in the 2D world.

01:37:57.620 --> 01:38:01.570
And I see a lot of
my customers --

01:38:01.570 --> 01:38:04.560
company like a Rockwell
Collins, or a Honeywell,

01:38:04.560 --> 01:38:08.160
when they provide data
to one of their suppliers

01:38:08.160 --> 01:38:10.980
to manufacture it, they'll
provide them both a --

01:38:10.980 --> 01:38:15.740
maybe a STEP file, or a CAD
model, and a 2D drawing.

01:38:15.740 --> 01:38:20.340
But anyway, we're certainly
moving toward that 3D world,

01:38:20.340 --> 01:38:22.960
and we are in discussion
with the FAA

01:38:22.960 --> 01:38:28.050
about a 3D authority
for this data.

01:38:28.050 --> 01:38:31.310
Something else that's
very important to us

01:38:31.310 --> 01:38:36.200
in the A&amp;D industry is
controlling that product data.

01:38:36.200 --> 01:38:40.750
And, you know, we used to be
configuration management-based,

01:38:40.750 --> 01:38:43.020
which was, you know,
somewhat paper-based.

01:38:43.020 --> 01:38:48.300
You know, it was kind
of haphazard, really.

01:38:48.300 --> 01:38:51.980
The engineering intent
or the design intent was

01:38:51.980 --> 01:38:53.280
in multiple locations.

01:38:53.280 --> 01:38:56.670
We moved on to product
data management,

01:38:56.670 --> 01:39:00.580
which was really a
file-based notion.

01:39:00.580 --> 01:39:05.880
You know, the engineering intent
or the design intent was still

01:39:05.880 --> 01:39:07.860
in multiple locations.

01:39:07.860 --> 01:39:10.150
And now, we're moving into more

01:39:10.150 --> 01:39:13.400
of a product life cycle
management scenario,

01:39:13.400 --> 01:39:16.240
which is more of a
relation-based system,

01:39:16.240 --> 01:39:18.610
and one nice thing about this is

01:39:18.610 --> 01:39:23.120
that we can gather all the
design intent into one location.

01:39:29.720 --> 01:39:32.220
Having to do with
product life cycles --

01:39:32.220 --> 01:39:39.570
and, you know, different
industries have different

01:39:39.570 --> 01:39:41.870
timelines regarding this.

01:39:41.870 --> 01:39:44.650
Typically, point releases

01:39:44.650 --> 01:39:47.070
of software upgrades
are probably every three

01:39:47.070 --> 01:39:48.980
to six months.

01:39:48.980 --> 01:39:53.650
You know, major releases
are one to two years,

01:39:53.650 --> 01:39:55.220
maybe a little longer.

01:39:55.220 --> 01:39:58.300
Computer processes are
changing all the time.

01:39:58.300 --> 01:40:01.430
People are coming and
going at the company.

01:40:01.430 --> 01:40:03.680
