for us to see our own data.

01:54:50.540 --> 01:54:53.500
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: Yeah, a couple
thoughts from the GSA side.

01:54:53.500 --> 01:54:56.050
We have two primary
challenges kind

01:54:56.050 --> 01:54:59.330
of implementing design software
and related software at GSA.

01:54:59.330 --> 01:55:02.900
One is that, since we
are a federal agency,

01:55:02.900 --> 01:55:05.920
all of our software that we
purchase, and that we put

01:55:05.920 --> 01:55:09.590
into our agreements with our
contractors and architects,

01:55:09.590 --> 01:55:11.810
has to comply with federal
IT security requirements,

01:55:11.810 --> 01:55:13.110
which can be quite onerous.

01:55:13.110 --> 01:55:15.320
And so we're always
balancing kind

01:55:15.320 --> 01:55:18.440
of giving our teams
all the tools they need

01:55:18.440 --> 01:55:20.290
to get the job done,
working with our contractors

01:55:20.290 --> 01:55:23.540
and architects to kind of be
open to software that they use,

01:55:23.540 --> 01:55:27.610
but also trying to comply
with FedRAMP and FISMA.

01:55:27.610 --> 01:55:30.760
As more and more applications
go to the cloud, you know,

01:55:30.760 --> 01:55:32.470
we're trying to work with
industry to make sure

01:55:32.470 --> 01:55:35.350
that those applications
are working in alignment

01:55:35.350 --> 01:55:37.430
with our security requirements.

01:55:37.430 --> 01:55:40.290
The other thing that we run
into a lot, also, is that --

01:55:40.290 --> 01:55:43.100
since we're an agency
that has regional offices

01:55:43.100 --> 01:55:47.630
across the country, and we run
about 10,000 projects a year,

01:55:47.630 --> 01:55:51.740
kind of every region is
basically responsible

01:55:51.740 --> 01:55:54.380
for thinking how to
run their own project.

01:55:54.380 --> 01:55:58.400
And so, getting the level of
consistency in terms of inputs

01:55:58.400 --> 01:56:00.380
across all those project
teams, across our contracts,

01:56:00.380 --> 01:56:02.040
is something that, you know,

01:56:02.040 --> 01:56:05.420
we're always striving
to do better at.

01:56:05.420 --> 01:56:06.830
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: Given
what you've all just said,

01:56:06.830 --> 01:56:09.580
are there some compelling --

01:56:09.580 --> 01:56:13.280
some compelling needs
of future software

01:56:13.280 --> 01:56:17.970
that would help your design
processes and workflows?

01:56:19.810 --> 01:56:21.400
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: You know, one
of the frustrations I've had,

01:56:21.400 --> 01:56:23.370
just in terms of presenting --

01:56:23.370 --> 01:56:28.080
and I'm frustrated by
the feedback here --

01:56:28.080 --> 01:56:35.730
is the ability to present in
a fluid way to clients on top

01:56:35.730 --> 01:56:37.410
of the drawings that we have.

01:56:37.410 --> 01:56:42.020
There's an increasing dependence
on telecommunication, and --

01:56:42.020 --> 01:56:43.780
you want me to be closer to it?

01:56:43.780 --> 01:56:48.610
Okay. And -- you know,
so it's not uncommon,

01:56:48.610 --> 01:56:52.130
even for a sole practitioner,
to have a video conference.

01:56:52.130 --> 01:56:55.620
And I think, given the
dependence on drawing,

01:56:55.620 --> 01:56:59.280
having an integrated
touch-screen application --

01:56:59.280 --> 01:57:03.180
I sort of see the
future of the iPad Pro.

01:57:03.180 --> 01:57:05.460
Like the Toshiba tablet I used
to have where you can draw

01:57:05.460 --> 01:57:08.220
on top of your own drawings
to present to a client,

01:57:08.220 --> 01:57:11.200
but do it in a really fluid
way that's touch-sensitive.

01:57:11.200 --> 01:57:14.220
And that kind of technology
would be really valuable,

01:57:14.220 --> 01:57:15.520
I think.

01:57:15.520 --> 01:57:18.970
I've seen -- as it
relates to SketchUp,

01:57:18.970 --> 01:57:24.000
to sort of incorporate the --
some of the technology I've seen

01:57:24.000 --> 01:57:26.090
in Maya that General
Motors uses,

01:57:26.090 --> 01:57:29.330
where you can actually use your
freehand drawing to carve away

01:57:29.330 --> 01:57:30.810
at the model would
be really helpful.

01:57:30.810 --> 01:57:33.350
And so I've always imagined
somehow being to do --

01:57:33.350 --> 01:57:36.470
being able to do something
like that on my own desktop.

01:57:36.470 --> 01:57:40.130
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: I think, as
an owner, we want, you know,

01:57:40.130 --> 01:57:43.190
more integration between design
software and kind of the rest

01:57:43.190 --> 01:57:45.710
of the ownership life cycle.

01:57:45.710 --> 01:57:49.280
I work mainly in the
project space, but obviously,

01:57:49.280 --> 01:57:50.580
we have building maintenance.

01:57:50.580 --> 01:57:52.640
We have portfolio decisions
that are being made.

01:57:52.640 --> 01:57:55.930
We do a lot with lease
facilities, too, and right now,

01:57:55.930 --> 01:57:58.080
kind of all of those
things are segmented

01:57:58.080 --> 01:57:59.800
in our model of things.

01:57:59.800 --> 01:58:02.120
So bringing that all together,
either through integration,

01:58:02.120 --> 01:58:04.630
or additional functionalities
in software, is something

01:58:04.630 --> 01:58:07.730
that we're eager to work on.

01:58:07.730 --> 01:58:09.310
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:
And something

01:58:09.310 --> 01:58:12.980
that was discussed earlier this
morning, too, was processes,

01:58:12.980 --> 01:58:18.230
and in our effort to prepare
our archive to be sent

01:58:18.230 --> 01:58:22.600
to Yale University Library, it's
something that is very important

01:58:22.600 --> 01:58:24.660
to us, is how do we
document the process?

01:58:24.660 --> 01:58:29.020
How did we get to that
final phase in the design?

01:58:29.020 --> 01:58:35.020
And in Microsoft Word, you
can track your changes.

01:58:35.020 --> 01:58:39.240
We don't have HOK 15
minutes backup system

01:58:39.240 --> 01:58:42.800
in our small practice,
but adding something,

01:58:42.800 --> 01:58:49.890
or doing online GoTo Meeting,
or some sort of conference call

01:58:49.890 --> 01:58:51.820
where you can mark things up.

01:58:51.820 --> 01:58:56.730
There is no record of any of
this, and maybe a software

01:58:56.730 --> 01:58:59.760
that would somehow
help us document,

01:58:59.760 --> 01:59:04.140
not only those final project
and deliverable, but processes,

01:59:04.140 --> 01:59:07.290
would be interesting to us.

01:59:07.290 --> 01:59:11.600
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: Do you have
somebody in your firm that --

01:59:11.600 --> 01:59:13.890
or somebodies who are
responsible for that --

01:59:13.890 --> 01:59:18.490
for any documentation like that
currently, without the software

01:59:18.490 --> 01:59:20.350
that you're looking for?

01:59:20.350 --> 01:59:23.130
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:
So it's a very --

01:59:23.130 --> 01:59:28.630
we are preparing the archive
and the legacy of Diana Balmori,

01:59:28.630 --> 01:59:30.220
the founding principal
in our firm

01:59:30.220 --> 01:59:32.570
that passed away a year ago.

01:59:32.570 --> 01:59:37.700
And we have started this
process probably five --

01:59:37.700 --> 01:59:40.690
five years ago, or so.

01:59:40.690 --> 01:59:44.160
And the archiving process

01:59:44.160 --> 01:59:48.810
of older project is
informing the new projects

01:59:48.810 --> 01:59:53.230
that we are doing now, and how
we should keep record of them.

01:59:53.230 --> 01:59:55.530
But at the same time,
we are a small firm,

01:59:55.530 --> 02:00:00.510
and we don't have a
designated person to arrange

02:00:00.510 --> 02:00:01.850
and organize all this data.

02:00:01.850 --> 02:00:04.040
So it's kind of left
for all of us to do.

02:00:04.040 --> 02:00:05.650
We have a set of standards

02:00:05.650 --> 02:00:09.830
that are never really
followed, or a naming system.

02:00:09.830 --> 02:00:16.570
It is just too hard
to keep and maintain.

02:00:16.570 --> 02:00:18.010
So we all do a little part.

02:00:18.010 --> 02:00:21.590
We all wear different hats, and
spend a couple of hours here

02:00:21.590 --> 02:00:26.970
and there preparing those
files to be sent to Yale.

02:00:26.970 --> 02:00:30.590
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: How's that
work in your firm, Mark?

02:00:30.590 --> 02:00:33.240
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: On slightly
larger projects, or more --

02:00:33.240 --> 02:00:35.130
for more sophisticated
clients, you know,

02:00:35.130 --> 02:00:42.270
our archiving process
tends to be a PowerPoint.

02:00:42.270 --> 02:00:46.530
Having a sequential story
that begins as a storyboard

02:00:46.530 --> 02:00:48.880
in the office, and ends up
being, you know, the best way

02:00:48.880 --> 02:00:52.040
to explain how you got
to where you did kind

02:00:52.040 --> 02:00:56.730
of simultaneously presents
the work you've put together,

02:00:56.730 --> 02:00:59.970
and records the thoughts
that went into it.

02:00:59.970 --> 02:01:03.750
You can throw sketches into
the inside, and it also kind

02:01:03.750 --> 02:01:05.950
of documents that a
phase is complete.

02:01:05.950 --> 02:01:11.100
So, you know, often, a really
well thought out PowerPoint,

02:01:11.100 --> 02:01:14.380
you know, provides
a kind of closer

02:01:14.380 --> 02:01:17.170
that a big rolled-up
set of drawings doesn't.

02:01:17.170 --> 02:01:21.400
Because it forms this record
of design intent as a story,

02:01:21.400 --> 02:01:23.320
and about the only
thing that would improve

02:01:23.320 --> 02:01:26.810
on that would be -- you
know, I think we all come

02:01:26.810 --> 02:01:29.430
up against some of
the fundamentals

02:01:29.430 --> 02:01:34.360
of operating systems, like
just opening images in Windows,

02:01:34.360 --> 02:01:37.830
and the ability to kind of
quickly scroll through images.

02:01:37.830 --> 02:01:40.720
So, you know, I would love
to be able to have software

02:01:40.720 --> 02:01:45.310
like Portfolio that -- Alias
Portfolio Wall that Alias,

02:01:45.310 --> 02:01:48.340
now AutoDesk has, where
you can pull out the images

02:01:48.340 --> 02:01:51.980
and arrange them on a
desktop, and not open a folder.

02:01:51.980 --> 02:01:54.300
Because the more organized
you are in archiving,

02:01:54.300 --> 02:01:56.760
and putting things in folders,
the harder it is to figure

02:01:56.760 --> 02:01:58.280
out -- where was
that great image?

02:01:58.280 --> 02:02:01.250
Which meeting was that that we
-- remember that sketch we did?

02:02:01.250 --> 02:02:03.050
And which presentation
was it in?

02:02:03.050 --> 02:02:08.480
Oh, it was in 17-11-15
under bar, you know,

02:02:08.480 --> 02:02:11.350
client presentation three, and
I think it was in the middle.

02:02:11.350 --> 02:02:14.870
And by that time, you know, you
get a phone call, and you've --

02:02:14.870 --> 02:02:18.550
you're unable to sort of connect
back to the original idea.

02:02:18.550 --> 02:02:22.590
So getting access to images
really quickly and sorting

02:02:22.590 --> 02:02:28.360
through them remains, you know
-- as was a dream in the origin

02:02:28.360 --> 02:02:30.520
of Windows, it still remains
something that's a little

02:02:30.520 --> 02:02:33.530
out of reach for all of us.

02:02:33.530 --> 02:02:34.830
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: Interesting.

02:02:34.830 --> 02:02:36.350
Nick, do you want to talk
about that a little bit?

02:02:36.350 --> 02:02:37.650
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: Sure.

02:02:37.650 --> 02:02:38.950
At a product level, we try

02:02:38.950 --> 02:02:41.510
to collect everything that's
produced by our product teams,

02:02:41.510 --> 02:02:43.880
and they -- we've taken the
strategy to kind of worry

02:02:43.880 --> 02:02:47.320
about how to get to the
access of that data later.

02:02:47.320 --> 02:02:49.680
But for the design
phase, I mean,

02:02:49.680 --> 02:02:52.800
we kind of collect
every iteration

02:02:52.800 --> 02:02:54.770
of the formal design submissions

02:02:54.770 --> 02:02:56.890
that are specified
in our contracts.

02:02:56.890 --> 02:02:59.610
Once we get to construction,

02:02:59.610 --> 02:03:02.350
our existing enterprise
product management tool is built

02:03:02.350 --> 02:03:05.650
to collect all RFIs and
submittals that are generated

02:03:05.650 --> 02:03:09.400
on the project, as well as any
reports and other correspondence

02:03:09.400 --> 02:03:11.640
that happens during the
course of a project.

02:03:11.640 --> 02:03:14.230
So right now, at a product
level, we're trying to track all

02:03:14.230 --> 02:03:16.700
that throughout every
phase of the project.

02:03:16.700 --> 02:03:19.870
I think our bigger issue is,
after that product is over,

02:03:19.870 --> 02:03:21.710
you know, how does that
stuff get maintained?

02:03:21.710 --> 02:03:23.380
Does it get maintained well?

02:03:23.380 --> 02:03:25.470
Somebody mentioned
earlier about having to --

02:03:25.470 --> 02:03:27.800
you know, what's the
right level of detail

02:03:27.800 --> 02:03:31.960
to have people enter
data, drawings

02:03:31.960 --> 02:03:34.550
or other, you know, artifacts.

02:03:34.550 --> 02:03:36.820
And we struggle with that
a lot, because, you know,

02:03:36.820 --> 02:03:39.540
resource-wise, our building
managers are probably managing

02:03:39.540 --> 02:03:40.930
40-plus projects at a time,

02:03:40.930 --> 02:03:42.350
while also taking care
of their buildings.

02:03:42.350 --> 02:03:44.250
So they don't have
time to kind of --

02:03:44.250 --> 02:03:47.080
when a paint color
changes, or something else,

02:03:47.080 --> 02:03:48.380
to update that in the BIM file.

02:03:48.380 --> 02:03:50.470
So, you know, what do
you do with all that data

02:03:50.470 --> 02:03:54.180
that you need, but don't
have the resources to manage?

02:03:55.380 --> 02:03:56.680
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: You've
each talked a little bit

02:03:56.680 --> 02:03:58.560
about standards,
and I'm wondering

02:03:58.560 --> 02:04:02.130
if we can draw some more out
about standards, and how --

02:04:02.130 --> 02:04:05.800
what the role is of external
guidelines, or standards,

02:04:05.800 --> 02:04:10.790
or vendor-neutral file
formats have in your workflow,

02:04:10.790 --> 02:04:13.960
and why they're -- and
if they're challenging,

02:04:13.960 --> 02:04:15.260
how they're challenging.

02:04:15.260 --> 02:04:16.850
If we could draw out
a little bit more

02:04:16.850 --> 02:04:20.480
about that -- do
you want to start?

02:04:20.480 --> 02:04:22.640
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany: Sure.

02:04:22.640 --> 02:04:24.540
So maybe I could start

02:04:24.540 --> 02:04:28.300
by introducing the
process in the office.

02:04:28.300 --> 02:04:31.730
So Aliza spoke a
little bit about it,

02:04:31.730 --> 02:04:36.340
but in the schematic -- again,
not every project is the same,

02:04:36.340 --> 02:04:40.430
but in most cases, the
schematic design phase,

02:04:40.430 --> 02:04:44.260
concept design phase --
in the landscape field,

02:04:44.260 --> 02:04:47.520
we're going to want
to work in 3D.

02:04:47.520 --> 02:04:53.670
And we are most likely going to
be using Rhino to think of it.

02:04:53.670 --> 02:04:58.230
So different slope, and
berms, and recessed areas --

02:04:58.230 --> 02:05:00.310
after we've started to
think about volume --

02:05:00.310 --> 02:05:03.960
and that's the sort of file that
will exchange with Architect.

02:05:03.960 --> 02:05:05.260
That file is very easy.

02:05:05.260 --> 02:05:06.700
It doesn't need to be packaged.

02:05:06.700 --> 02:05:08.730
All the information is
contained with that file,

02:05:08.730 --> 02:05:10.740
so it's very easy to share.

02:05:10.740 --> 02:05:14.260
After that, when we move
into the design development

02:05:14.260 --> 02:05:18.110
and construction document, at
that moment that we're going

02:05:18.110 --> 02:05:22.940
to go into the 2D and start
documenting our design

02:05:22.940 --> 02:05:25.410
in AutoCAD.

02:05:25.410 --> 02:05:30.710
At that moment, we are
going to start using --

02:05:31.780 --> 02:05:36.100
we're going to set
the files with --

02:05:36.100 --> 02:05:39.780
following the format
of the deliverable.

02:05:39.780 --> 02:05:43.910
Each of those file is like --

02:05:43.910 --> 02:05:47.730
in the paper form is just one
sheet, and within that sheet,

02:05:47.730 --> 02:05:54.350
we are going to link in,
or to add some ex-ref,

02:05:54.350 --> 02:05:57.750
which are reference
to other files

02:05:57.750 --> 02:06:00.230
of that same AutoCAD format.

02:06:00.230 --> 02:06:06.210
And we are going to be able
to work on that sheet file

02:06:06.210 --> 02:06:11.270
and on those ex-ref file, with
multiple people being able

02:06:11.270 --> 02:06:13.550
to touch at different files.

02:06:13.550 --> 02:06:18.000
As landscape, for example, if we
do a project with an architect,

02:06:18.000 --> 02:06:21.760
we are going to add
their building

02:06:21.760 --> 02:06:25.550
as an ex-ref to our file.

02:06:25.550 --> 02:06:33.580
If, at the end of this process,
we do not package this file,

02:06:33.580 --> 02:06:37.310
we are going to lose all the
different linked file to it.

02:06:37.310 --> 02:06:41.440
Or, in our office, all the
files are saved on the servers,

02:06:41.440 --> 02:06:45.480
and the server is backed up
in two different location,

02:06:45.480 --> 02:06:49.340
on the east coast and the west
coast, and we can get copies --

02:06:49.340 --> 02:06:55.080
I think we are saving three
copies a day of those files.

02:06:55.080 --> 02:06:57.720
When the project
is sort of done,

02:06:57.720 --> 02:07:02.110
we move it into what we call the
archive partition of our server,

02:07:02.110 --> 02:07:08.110
and in moving files -- and that
archive partition is not backed

02:07:08.110 --> 02:07:09.410
up as often.

02:07:09.410 --> 02:07:12.290
When we move those files,
if we did not package them,

02:07:12.290 --> 02:07:18.230
then we are going to have
to spend 10, 15 minutes,

02:07:18.230 --> 02:07:22.380
maybe even more, trying to
search those linked files

02:07:22.380 --> 02:07:25.410
to be able to have
-- I'm so sorry.

02:07:25.410 --> 02:07:27.810
It's very complicated.

02:07:27.810 --> 02:07:32.700
But it's just -- it's what we
need to do, and we often --

02:07:32.700 --> 02:07:35.290
because we have -- working
on 10 different projects,

02:07:35.290 --> 02:07:37.370
something's always -- one
deadline after another deadline,

02:07:37.370 --> 02:07:41.100
we often forget that one step.

02:07:41.100 --> 02:07:44.640
And then we regret it when, 10
years later, the project is back

02:07:44.640 --> 02:07:49.730
on track, and we have to
find those original file.

02:07:51.840 --> 02:07:53.650
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: That all
sounds very familiar to me,

02:07:53.650 --> 02:07:57.700
since one of the most recent
projects I've been working on is

02:07:57.700 --> 02:08:02.380
with a landscape
firm collaborating

02:08:02.380 --> 02:08:04.080
with other freelancers.

02:08:04.080 --> 02:08:07.160
And it's interesting to see
just -- it's kind of a miracle,

02:08:07.160 --> 02:08:10.210
in a way, how a group of people

02:08:10.210 --> 02:08:12.490
who haven't really
met each other manage

02:08:12.490 --> 02:08:18.000
to coordinate a site plan and
a landscape architecture firm

02:08:18.000 --> 02:08:20.530
without having a manual.

02:08:20.530 --> 02:08:24.780
And it's very complex, because
the survey will come in with all

02:08:24.780 --> 02:08:27.770
of its layers, and you'll
create these external references

02:08:27.770 --> 02:08:34.060
from maybe a Google Earth image
that you put in on one layer,

02:08:34.060 --> 02:08:39.010
and the GIS information
that shows county boundaries

02:08:39.010 --> 02:08:42.150
for sensitive areas
and steep slopes.

02:08:42.150 --> 02:08:46.450
And by the time you're
ready to draw a rectangle

02:08:46.450 --> 02:08:49.390
for where the building
goes, you've got a really,

02:08:49.390 --> 02:08:52.160
really complex file, and the
way you even edit any part

02:08:52.160 --> 02:08:57.410
of it involves a lot of care.

02:08:57.410 --> 02:09:00.540
And if someone comes in that
is in a little bit of a hurry,

02:09:00.540 --> 02:09:03.840
and puts one of those references
in a folder, or worse yet,

02:09:03.840 --> 02:09:06.630
somebody who's really into
filing systems and thinks

02:09:06.630 --> 02:09:08.710
that the names of things
should be different,

02:09:08.710 --> 02:09:11.070
and you change the name
of an image that --

02:09:11.070 --> 02:09:12.580
it's true with the
Adobe products, too.

02:09:12.580 --> 02:09:15.100
You're in the image folder, and
you change the name of an image

02:09:15.100 --> 02:09:18.240
to give it a little more
clarity -- instead of scan 32,

02:09:18.240 --> 02:09:20.250
it becomes, you know, barn.

02:09:20.250 --> 02:09:23.730
And suddenly, it's unlinked,
and no one can find it,

02:09:23.730 --> 02:09:26.310
and it doesn't come out
on your presentation.

02:09:26.310 --> 02:09:30.590
So it's a very -- it's a
very, very methodical process

02:09:30.590 --> 02:09:33.780
that many of us, you
know, became designers

02:09:33.780 --> 02:09:37.480
because we weren't really that
methodical to start out with.

02:09:37.480 --> 02:09:41.670
And so we've had to learn
how to be really methodical,

02:09:41.670 --> 02:09:43.240
and I almost -- I picture it.

02:09:43.240 --> 02:09:45.960
It's like the -- Daniel
Kahneman's book, "Thinking Fast

02:09:45.960 --> 02:09:47.260
and Slow," that you
might've read.

02:09:47.260 --> 02:09:49.900
I feel like as designers, we're
in this sort of system one,

02:09:49.900 --> 02:09:51.820
and everything's intuitive, and
we're shooting from the hip.

02:09:51.820 --> 02:09:53.940
And then, when it comes time

02:09:53.940 --> 02:09:57.270
to make sure our external
references are all filed

02:09:57.270 --> 02:10:00.500
correctly, we have to
be really methodical.

02:10:02.210 --> 02:10:03.510
System two.

02:10:03.510 --> 02:10:04.810
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: Yeah, at
GSA, we try to stay away

02:10:04.810 --> 02:10:09.090
from dictating how designers
manage the CAD files,

02:10:09.090 --> 02:10:11.060
and how they construct
the drawings

02:10:11.060 --> 02:10:12.360
that they're working on.

02:10:12.360 --> 02:10:14.790
We do have -- obviously, we're
a large federal bureaucracy,

02:10:14.790 --> 02:10:18.040
so we have lots of standards
and guides that are out there.

02:10:18.040 --> 02:10:23.770
P100 kind of dictates all of our
requirements around construction

02:10:23.770 --> 02:10:25.090
and design requirements,

02:10:25.090 --> 02:10:27.130
and also some deliverable
requirements.

02:10:27.130 --> 02:10:28.560
We do have a BIM guide
that's out there,

02:10:28.560 --> 02:10:31.980
that helps to define kind of, if
we are using BIM on a project,

02:10:31.980 --> 02:10:33.280
what the final deliverables have

02:10:33.280 --> 02:10:34.990
to comply with, and
stuff like that.

02:10:34.990 --> 02:10:37.860
But a lot of the time, you
know, again, we're dealing

02:10:37.860 --> 02:10:41.800
with thousands of contractors,
thousands of architects.

02:10:41.800 --> 02:10:45.980
So we try to stay out of the
how you do the job part of it,

02:10:45.980 --> 02:10:48.750
and just try to kind of
manage the end product

02:10:48.750 --> 02:10:51.110
by our contracts, and
satisfying, you know,

02:10:51.110 --> 02:10:53.410
what those deliverables
need to look like.

02:10:54.780 --> 02:10:57.380
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: Are there
other aspects of your workflow

02:10:57.380 --> 02:11:00.810
that you think are helpful
to this conversation,

02:11:00.810 --> 02:11:05.750
in thinking about
standards and software

02:11:05.750 --> 02:11:08.130
that we've talked
about this morning?

02:11:09.630 --> 02:11:11.810
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: Oh, sorry.

02:11:11.810 --> 02:11:13.580
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:
Sort of a --

02:11:13.580 --> 02:11:16.650
I mean, it's parallel to the
design process, but in preparing

02:11:16.650 --> 02:11:20.270
for the documents
to be sent to Yale,

02:11:20.270 --> 02:11:25.340
something that we think is
very important is writing a

02:11:25.340 --> 02:11:28.520
narrative, which is a little
bit similar to the PowerPoint

02:11:28.520 --> 02:11:31.110
that Mark was describing.

02:11:31.110 --> 02:11:35.270
But that will tell you, oh,
in 2006, there was the --

02:11:35.270 --> 02:11:37.980
yeah, this huge economic
crisis, so yes,

02:11:37.980 --> 02:11:39.280
the budget had to be cut.

02:11:39.280 --> 02:11:40.580
So we had to redesign.

02:11:40.580 --> 02:11:43.750
That's why there are two
design for that same space.

02:11:43.750 --> 02:11:48.940
And this takes a little bit
of time, but it's not --

02:11:48.940 --> 02:11:50.590
it maybe takes a
couple of hours.

02:11:50.590 --> 02:11:55.520
It's not a crazy amount
of time as renaming files,

02:11:55.520 --> 02:11:59.210
or packaging them, but I think
for anyone that would want

02:11:59.210 --> 02:12:02.650
to go very much into the
project and research it,

02:12:02.650 --> 02:12:05.930
it will at least give them
some sort of direction of how

02:12:05.930 --> 02:12:08.890
to navigate this
nebulous of files.

02:12:08.890 --> 02:12:10.530
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside:

02:12:10.530 --> 02:12:15.350
From a collections
viewpoint, I really like that.

02:12:15.350 --> 02:12:17.560
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: You know, I --

02:12:17.560 --> 02:12:20.630
one of the challenges that
sole practitioners face,

02:12:20.630 --> 02:12:25.040
and we all face, is this sort of
movement towards design build,

02:12:25.040 --> 02:12:26.890
which can mean a lot
of different things,

02:12:26.890 --> 02:12:30.500
depending on whether it's, you
know, a house addition, or,

02:12:30.500 --> 02:12:34.450
you know, a major
master plan that has --

02:12:34.450 --> 02:12:36.360
is a fast-track construction
project.

02:12:36.360 --> 02:12:39.940
So -- but in either of those,

02:12:39.940 --> 02:12:44.000
the initial design brief
is really important.

02:12:44.000 --> 02:12:47.450
And, you know, as I looked at
the slide earlier about the --

02:12:47.450 --> 02:12:51.350
with all the energy
management software, you know,

02:12:51.350 --> 02:12:55.190
one can make a statement that
we would like this project

02:12:55.190 --> 02:13:01.350
to be 30% below ASHRAE 90.1,
and whatever year it is,

02:13:01.350 --> 02:13:05.510
or to meet certain lead
standard, and then --

02:13:05.510 --> 02:13:08.400
but how to actually get there?

02:13:08.400 --> 02:13:11.710
There are many, many pathways,
and that software is --

02:13:11.710 --> 02:13:14.120
you know, a lot of it
is really experimental.

02:13:14.120 --> 02:13:17.850
So this design brief, kind
of like the PowerPoint,

02:13:17.850 --> 02:13:21.400
I imagine it being not unlike,
you know, Boeing's design brief.

02:13:21.400 --> 02:13:23.980
There's all this technical
stuff that you need

02:13:23.980 --> 02:13:28.600
to meet that's non-visual, that
the drawing doesn't represent,

02:13:28.600 --> 02:13:31.370
that are performance standards
that you hope to meet,

02:13:31.370 --> 02:13:33.980
or are required by GSA
to meet, for example.

02:13:33.980 --> 02:13:35.970
So, you know, the real --

02:13:35.970 --> 02:13:38.880
you know, one of the
things that's very hard

02:13:38.880 --> 02:13:41.790
to document is the pathway

02:13:41.790 --> 02:13:46.060
by which these non-visual
standards are met,

02:13:46.060 --> 02:13:48.670
and it's usually some
other kind of paper trail.

02:13:48.670 --> 02:13:51.260
And it may be solved
in some form of BIM.

02:13:51.260 --> 02:13:54.020
Certainly, I would
love to be able to,

02:13:54.020 --> 02:13:59.170
and hope to soon be able to,
click on a part of the drawing

02:13:59.170 --> 02:14:03.740
and come up with a Word document
that -- or an Excel spreadsheet,

02:14:03.740 --> 02:14:08.380
or some other type of file, or
chart, or graph that references,

02:14:08.380 --> 02:14:10.520
you know, why something
is a certain way.

02:14:10.520 --> 02:14:11.820
Because otherwise, the --

02:14:11.820 --> 02:14:16.840
you know, explaining to somebody
retroactively why the building

02:14:16.840 --> 02:14:18.440
doesn't meet that
energy standard,

02:14:18.440 --> 02:14:21.450
and what happened along
the way, and that kind

02:14:21.450 --> 02:14:23.970
of finger-pointing
is pretty common.

02:14:23.970 --> 02:14:26.270
It's a pretty common sight.

02:14:28.790 --> 02:14:30.470
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: Yeah, my
only other comment on that --

02:14:30.470 --> 02:14:33.120
when I think of workflow,
one of our primary challenges

02:14:33.120 --> 02:14:34.860
as an owner is, you
know, we have --

02:14:34.860 --> 02:14:38.170
we usually hire somebody
for our larger projects,

02:14:38.170 --> 02:14:39.470
you know, a design firm.

02:14:39.470 --> 02:14:41.470
We usually hire a
separate contractor.

02:14:41.470 --> 02:14:44.300
We usually hire a CMA
or somebody to help kind

02:14:44.300 --> 02:14:46.060
of oversee it, and
then, you know,

02:14:46.060 --> 02:14:48.440
we might have other
contracts, commissioning agents.

02:14:48.440 --> 02:14:51.380
You know, we're involved at
that project management basis.

02:14:51.380 --> 02:14:53.590
We're dealing with customers and
all sorts of other stakeholders.

02:14:53.590 --> 02:14:56.080
So in terms of workflow
from design

02:14:56.080 --> 02:14:58.460
through that whole
process of a project,

02:14:58.460 --> 02:15:01.690
how do you get all those people
collaborating the right way

02:15:01.690 --> 02:15:06.510
in a system, or in a set of
systems, or other methods

02:15:06.510 --> 02:15:09.640
to produce kind of the
results that you want?

02:15:09.640 --> 02:15:14.680
And our experience with that
has honestly not been great.

02:15:14.680 --> 02:15:17.760
Since 2009, you know, we've had
an electronic product management

02:15:17.760 --> 02:15:22.710
system at GSA that was kind of
intended to do all that, and,

02:15:22.710 --> 02:15:25.560
you know, some teams have
gravitated towards it more,

02:15:25.560 --> 02:15:28.540
and use it for project
collaboration and workflow.

02:15:28.540 --> 02:15:29.840
So if somebody submits
the drawing,

02:15:29.840 --> 02:15:31.140
it gets approved in there.

02:15:31.140 --> 02:15:32.440
If somebody submits an RFI,

02:15:32.440 --> 02:15:35.290
the formal response is recorded
there, all that kind of stuff.

02:15:35.290 --> 02:15:37.960
But many of our projects
are still kind of working,

02:15:37.960 --> 02:15:39.930
in terms of workflow
and collaboration,

02:15:39.930 --> 02:15:41.760
outside of that tool
with other technologies

02:15:41.760 --> 02:15:43.330
that have evolved since then.

02:15:43.330 --> 02:15:45.000
So it's trying to find
kind of the median,

02:15:45.000 --> 02:15:48.120
or the middle ground, between,
you know, what do we mandate,

02:15:48.120 --> 02:15:50.530
or what do we have in a
collective system or set

02:15:50.530 --> 02:15:52.050
of systems, versus, you know,

02:15:52.050 --> 02:15:56.230
how does that workflow
happen outside of it?

02:15:56.230 --> 02:15:59.270
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: Another
area that I think you touched

02:15:59.270 --> 02:16:03.430
on was accessing legacy
data, and some of the --

02:16:03.430 --> 02:16:04.730
and you've learned

02:16:04.730 --> 02:16:06.930
from accessing your legacy
data what you should do

02:16:06.930 --> 02:16:08.230
in the future.

02:16:08.230 --> 02:16:11.130
Are there other thoughts
about that that we could learn

02:16:11.130 --> 02:16:13.920
about from each of you, or
what you would do differently

02:16:13.920 --> 02:16:19.410
as you have had experiences,
unable to access legacy data?

02:16:20.780 --> 02:16:24.730
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: Well, there
-- yeah, I'm reminded that --

02:16:24.730 --> 02:16:27.340
and I know this conference
is largely about software,

02:16:27.340 --> 02:16:29.870
and we were talking
about wish lists.

02:16:29.870 --> 02:16:34.500
A lot of times, our legacy data
is actually a set of drawings

02:16:34.500 --> 02:16:39.220
and sketches, but increasingly,
you know, because it's easy

02:16:39.220 --> 02:16:43.480
to store, having
record photographs --

02:16:43.480 --> 02:16:46.740
you know, it's easy
to get a point cloud

02:16:46.740 --> 02:16:48.650
of the existing building.

02:16:48.650 --> 02:16:56.850
And a lot of that kind of data
that -- but I think, you know,

02:16:56.850 --> 02:17:01.000
what -- it would be helpful
for us in our tiny office,

02:17:01.000 --> 02:17:04.640
would be to have a really
great printer and scanner,

02:17:04.640 --> 02:17:06.560
and a lot of other stuff
that we can't really afford,

02:17:06.560 --> 02:17:10.800
that would just simply
allow us to digitize a lot

02:17:10.800 --> 02:17:14.700
of the documents that
are not fully digital.

02:17:14.700 --> 02:17:17.930
And, you know, I almost
feel like there could be,

02:17:17.930 --> 02:17:20.900
and probably is, a way
to partner with some

02:17:20.900 --> 02:17:26.280
of the more sophisticated
printers to have an archiving --

02:17:26.280 --> 02:17:30.330
probably a -- you know, a
simple PDF archiving standard.

02:17:30.330 --> 02:17:31.630
The other kind of
data I was talking

02:17:31.630 --> 02:17:33.880
about with the energy
stuff might be a lot harder

02:17:33.880 --> 02:17:36.720
to figure out.

02:17:36.720 --> 02:17:38.020
&gt;&gt; Ann Whiteside: Nick?

02:17:38.020 --> 02:17:40.620
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: Yeah, our issue
with accessing legacy data --

02:17:40.620 --> 02:17:43.000
so I kind of mentioned it,
I think, earlier, is that,

02:17:43.000 --> 02:17:47.350
you know, we have many
different business lines at GSA,

02:17:47.350 --> 02:17:51.220
and kind of IT investments
over time, because of the size

02:17:51.220 --> 02:17:54.180
of our agency, have largely
been business-line driven.

02:17:54.180 --> 02:17:56.750
And so, currently, we
have an IT environment

02:17:56.750 --> 02:18:00.200
that has building
drawings over here.

02:18:00.200 --> 02:18:03.160
We have kind of a system that
takes care of work requests,

02:18:03.160 --> 02:18:04.900
so if a light bulb
goes out, you know,

02:18:04.900 --> 02:18:07.570
there's a flow process there
that gets taken care of.

02:18:07.570 --> 02:18:08.870
We have a project
management system,

02:18:08.870 --> 02:18:10.170
which I described earlier.

02:18:10.170 --> 02:18:12.860
We have a portfolio
investment system.

02:18:12.860 --> 02:18:17.910
We have another system that
we use for charging rent

02:18:17.910 --> 02:18:20.320
to the other federal agencies
that are inhabiting our space.

02:18:20.320 --> 02:18:24.760
So we have these drawings
that have kind of come online.

02:18:24.760 --> 02:18:26.170
We're storing them
in all these systems,

02:18:26.170 --> 02:18:27.970
at least for the
last five years.

02:18:27.970 --> 02:18:30.950
And so, how are we -- if
I'm starting a new project,

02:18:30.950 --> 02:18:32.540
you know, am I going to
five different systems

02:18:32.540 --> 02:18:34.240
to get the inputs to
start that project?

02:18:34.240 --> 02:18:37.160
Am I now trying to tie all
these things together, so I can,

02:18:37.160 --> 02:18:39.230
you know, have a
better cohesive model?

02:18:39.230 --> 02:18:40.960
So I think as we're looking

02:18:40.960 --> 02:18:43.060
at our IT expenditures
going forward, we're trying

02:18:43.060 --> 02:18:46.320
to be more strategic
in how we bring those

02:18:46.320 --> 02:18:48.600
that have been historically
separate business units

02:18:48.600 --> 02:18:51.290
and systems, you know,
together to flesh

02:18:51.290 --> 02:18:54.210
out a more cohesive
story about a building,

02:18:54.210 --> 02:18:57.640
or a project, or
set of projects.

02:18:57.640 --> 02:18:59.640
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: I
had one other thought,

02:18:59.640 --> 02:19:02.090
if I could just chime in, and
that just has to do with the --

02:19:02.090 --> 02:19:06.170
you know, the trend in
our time towards just more

02:19:06.170 --> 02:19:09.910
and more sophisticated
images of buildings.

02:19:09.910 --> 02:19:11.460
Architecture is not an image.

02:19:11.460 --> 02:19:13.510
It's a three-dimensional
construct,

02:19:13.510 --> 02:19:16.320
and I was just thinking
about some of the projects

02:19:16.320 --> 02:19:18.210
that I would love
to be able to --

02:19:18.210 --> 02:19:20.400
I'd love to be able to
look at the Form-Z models

02:19:20.400 --> 02:19:22.440
of some old projects
from my former office,

02:19:22.440 --> 02:19:27.290
and actually rotate the design
development Form-Z model,

02:19:27.290 --> 02:19:28.800
because there was
a lot going on.

02:19:28.800 --> 02:19:31.490
And when I look back -- look
at what's in my portfolio,

02:19:31.490 --> 02:19:34.520
it's the rendering
that we sent out.

02:19:34.520 --> 02:19:36.330
And somebody did a great
rendering of the front

02:19:36.330 --> 02:19:39.590
of the building, but there's
all this really great work

02:19:39.590 --> 02:19:41.180
that often -- that
often, what the Library

02:19:41.180 --> 02:19:49.650
of Congress should have is the
high-resolution model before a

02:19:49.650 --> 02:19:53.630
lot of the compromises happen in
the later phases of the building

02:19:53.630 --> 02:19:55.200
and during construction.

02:19:55.200 --> 02:19:58.000
So that you -- you know, that's
the one you would want to show.

02:19:58.000 --> 02:20:00.280
You don't want to show
the one where, you know,

02:20:00.280 --> 02:20:03.530
you've had to value
engineer out the wall panels,

02:20:03.530 --> 02:20:05.990
and the awnings go away,
and the sun shades go away,

02:20:05.990 --> 02:20:07.910
and suddenly, everything
gets very flat.

02:20:07.910 --> 02:20:10.670
And everything that -- you
know, all of the compromises

02:20:10.670 --> 02:20:11.970
that are made along the way.

02:20:11.970 --> 02:20:15.410
But usually, somewhere around
design development, there is --

02:20:15.410 --> 02:20:18.860
the design intent sort of
reaches its highest level,

02:20:18.860 --> 02:20:20.820
and then it starts to drop off.

02:20:20.820 --> 02:20:25.180
And that, historically,
has been a point

02:20:25.180 --> 02:20:30.810
where the best modeling software
available at that time is used,

02:20:30.810 --> 02:20:33.880
and now I have no idea
how you go back --

02:20:33.880 --> 02:20:38.340
how you go back and
retrieve that.

02:20:38.340 --> 02:20:39.880
I hope you figure it out.

02:20:39.880 --> 02:20:41.550
Everybody's pointing at Tim.

02:20:41.550 --> 02:20:47.040
It's all up to Tim.

02:20:47.040 --> 02:20:48.340
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:
And just wanted

02:20:48.340 --> 02:20:50.340
to share an experience
during the archiving process.

02:20:50.340 --> 02:20:55.090
At one point, early on, we
decided that we would create PDF

02:20:55.090 --> 02:21:01.010
of the AutoCAD file at
specific important moment

02:21:01.010 --> 02:21:04.860
in the design process that were
not recorded by the deliverable.

02:21:04.860 --> 02:21:06.590
They were more like
internal meetings

02:21:06.590 --> 02:21:10.120
that sanctioned direction
into the design.

02:21:10.120 --> 02:21:15.900
And we did it for a whole
project, and we looked back

02:21:15.900 --> 02:21:18.800
at those files, and
the line weight,

02:21:18.800 --> 02:21:21.490
or the way they were translated

02:21:21.490 --> 02:21:25.240
in PDF did not reflect
the design.

02:21:25.240 --> 02:21:28.830
I mean, every element was
there, but you couldn't read it.

02:21:28.830 --> 02:21:36.470
And after that experience, we
stopped transforming files.

02:21:36.470 --> 02:21:38.520
So whatever format they are in,

02:21:38.520 --> 02:21:42.890
that's the format we
send them to Yale.

