02:22:07.630 --> 02:22:10.450
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander:
Okay, well, thank you.

02:22:10.450 --> 02:22:12.880
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
Oh, you need a mic.

02:22:19.040 --> 02:22:21.080
&gt;&gt; Aliza Leventhal: Hi, I'm
Aliza Leventhal from Sasaki,

02:22:21.080 --> 02:22:24.350
and my question is really to
all of you, in terms of --

02:22:24.350 --> 02:22:25.650
we've talked a little --

02:22:25.650 --> 02:22:28.770
you guys talked in the second
panel about, like, your hopes

02:22:28.770 --> 02:22:30.850
and dreams of what
would be great to have.

02:22:30.850 --> 02:22:35.720
But I think what I'm -- would
be interested in talking

02:22:35.720 --> 02:22:39.280
about is more, what is a
reasonable standard for --

02:22:39.280 --> 02:22:43.230
like, what is something -- like,
Noemie, you mentioned that --

02:22:43.230 --> 02:22:45.680
Noemie, you mentioned that
you guys have standards,

02:22:45.680 --> 02:22:47.290
and they don't [inaudible] help.

02:22:47.290 --> 02:22:50.250
I can relate to that.

02:22:50.250 --> 02:22:53.160
But the -- what is
reasonable, then?

02:22:53.160 --> 02:22:55.910
How can -- is it something that
needs to be a button in Revit

02:22:55.910 --> 02:22:57.210
in order for that to be --

02:22:57.210 --> 02:22:59.310
or, you know, all these various
software -- can't just be Revit,

02:22:59.310 --> 02:23:01.520
but, like, does every
software need to have, like,

02:23:01.520 --> 02:23:04.130
perfect archive function,
and that's the answer?

02:23:04.130 --> 02:23:07.170
Because that's not reasonable,
but what would be something

02:23:07.170 --> 02:23:09.760
that you'd be -- like, you
can imagine being built

02:23:09.760 --> 02:23:14.770
into your workflow,
in terms of, like,

02:23:14.770 --> 02:23:17.070
making sure things
are accessible?

02:23:20.690 --> 02:23:24.200
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: You
know, I suppose one thing

02:23:24.200 --> 02:23:26.340
that would be -- it's
interesting that sometimes,

02:23:26.340 --> 02:23:31.370
when we send a digital file
out, we like to send a PDF

02:23:31.370 --> 02:23:35.510
so that we know exactly how
it should look when it plots.

02:23:35.510 --> 02:23:37.410
So I'm not sure if
your question is sort

02:23:37.410 --> 02:23:40.520
of asking what would
the standard --

02:23:40.520 --> 02:23:43.800
what would an office standard
be, or a digital standard.

02:23:43.800 --> 02:23:47.900
But I think to the extent that
it's sometimes unclear whether

02:23:47.900 --> 02:23:51.960
or not someone on the receiving
end is going to be able to view

02:23:51.960 --> 02:23:57.060
or plot a drawing the way
it's intended, that some type

02:23:57.060 --> 02:24:01.540
of metadata that says that,
you know, all the lines

02:24:01.540 --> 02:24:06.700
that are magenta should plot at
.35 millimeters, for example --

02:24:06.700 --> 02:24:10.470
that there's actually, like,
some type of graphic interface.

02:24:10.470 --> 02:24:12.060
Because we have it
in the office.

02:24:12.060 --> 02:24:15.600
In the office, we have
a little card that shows

02:24:15.600 --> 02:24:18.850
which colors plot at
which line weight.

02:24:18.850 --> 02:24:21.260
So it's always kind of
funny, in the sophistication

02:24:21.260 --> 02:24:24.920
of a digital environment,
you still have cheat sheets

02:24:24.920 --> 02:24:28.500
on scraps of paper that tell you
which colors plot at which size,

02:24:28.500 --> 02:24:31.770
depending on what your plot
file is that you've used.

02:24:31.770 --> 02:24:36.740
So somehow, that connection
between the design intent

02:24:36.740 --> 02:24:41.000
of the lines and how they
should appear graphically seems

02:24:41.000 --> 02:24:46.890
to be part of the file system
that's needed, at basic.

02:24:46.890 --> 02:24:48.190
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:

02:24:48.190 --> 02:24:49.790
One thing that's
completely unrealistic,

02:24:49.790 --> 02:24:53.900
but I'm not really
sure about discussion

02:24:53.900 --> 02:24:57.570
with industry partners --

02:24:57.570 --> 02:25:02.130
but a read-only file would
be quite interesting,

02:25:02.130 --> 02:25:04.900
when you no longer own
the copy of the software,

02:25:04.900 --> 02:25:09.130
but you could still
just look at that file,

02:25:09.130 --> 02:25:10.690
not modify anything in it.

02:25:10.690 --> 02:25:16.550
Just turn the model around,
look at different elevation.

02:25:16.550 --> 02:25:17.870
Maybe that's not too far off.

02:25:17.870 --> 02:25:20.470
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: Greg, do
you have some thoughts on that?

02:25:20.470 --> 02:25:22.340
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner:
I don't know.

02:25:22.340 --> 02:25:25.930
The answer to the question is
a tough one, because simply,

02:25:25.930 --> 02:25:30.770
if there's not a business
purpose for doing it,

02:25:30.770 --> 02:25:32.990
it's always a tough sell, right?

02:25:32.990 --> 02:25:38.250
So I'm, you know,
sort of a market --

02:25:38.250 --> 02:25:40.180
my thing is, this is a
market-based solution.

02:25:40.180 --> 02:25:42.020
So you have to figure
out what's valuable,

02:25:42.020 --> 02:25:43.680
and that's what will
become useful.

02:25:43.680 --> 02:25:47.380
So, you know, there's these
-- you know, certainly,

02:25:47.380 --> 02:25:50.390
we have contract deliverables
and so forth, but at the end

02:25:50.390 --> 02:25:52.250
of the day, a lot
of the standards are

02:25:52.250 --> 02:25:54.170
for moving between two parties.

02:25:54.170 --> 02:25:55.480
But if you don't have a standard

02:25:55.480 --> 02:25:58.080
that you ever use while you do
your work, it's not valuable

02:25:58.080 --> 02:26:01.550
to you to do the thing that you
have to hand to the next person.

02:26:01.550 --> 02:26:04.790
So that -- somewhere
in that is my thinking.

02:26:04.790 --> 02:26:06.350
I don't know exactly
what that looks like,

02:26:06.350 --> 02:26:09.600
because that basically implies
that you'd have to get vendors

02:26:09.600 --> 02:26:11.490
to work on open formats,

02:26:11.490 --> 02:26:14.080
which is not the way
they currently want

02:26:14.080 --> 02:26:16.730
to view the world.

02:26:16.730 --> 02:26:18.830
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: It
would seem to me that the --

02:26:18.830 --> 02:26:21.330
one of the big ideas
we're going to get

02:26:21.330 --> 02:26:24.410
to after lunch is
access use cases.

02:26:24.410 --> 02:26:27.090
In other words, what is it
you're trying to archive?

02:26:27.090 --> 02:26:31.720
Is it, you know, the
essence of the design at its,

02:26:31.720 --> 02:26:34.010
you know, most refined point?

02:26:34.010 --> 02:26:37.680
Is it what we told the
contractor to build?

02:26:37.680 --> 02:26:39.670
You know, what is it
you're trying to archive?

02:26:39.670 --> 02:26:43.220
And then you have kind of
different requirements,

02:26:43.220 --> 02:26:45.390
and then different methods,
it would seem to me.

02:26:45.390 --> 02:26:47.250
I don't know.

02:26:47.250 --> 02:26:50.450
Phil?

02:26:50.450 --> 02:26:52.140
&gt;&gt; Phil Rocher: Well,
I'm not going

02:26:52.140 --> 02:26:54.850
to answer what you
said, or address that.

02:26:54.850 --> 02:26:58.050
But I will kind of answer what
I think your question was,

02:26:58.050 --> 02:27:00.030
and actually, it's something

02:27:00.030 --> 02:27:01.360
that I'm talking
about after lunch.

02:27:01.360 --> 02:27:06.830
It's my presentation
this time, but anyway --

02:27:06.830 --> 02:27:12.250
we have an implementer forum for
software producers that write

02:27:12.250 --> 02:27:15.400
to the standard format.

02:27:15.400 --> 02:27:19.680
And, you know, we started doing
this, like, back in the '90s,

02:27:19.680 --> 02:27:23.160
and some of the software
developers started

02:27:23.160 --> 02:27:24.690
to write STEP interfaces.

02:27:24.690 --> 02:27:28.040
But they didn't necessarily
communicate or interoperate

02:27:28.040 --> 02:27:31.130
with the other software
developers' STEP interfaces,

02:27:31.130 --> 02:27:35.970
and so, you know, multi-trillion
dollar problem here.

02:27:35.970 --> 02:27:39.140
So industry had asked us to --

02:27:39.140 --> 02:27:42.290
well, how do you test
for interoperability?

02:27:42.290 --> 02:27:47.270
And so, you know, we thought
about it, and some colleagues

02:27:47.270 --> 02:27:50.000
of mine from Ford, and
Boeing, and General Motors,

02:27:50.000 --> 02:27:51.550
and other companies
got together.

02:27:51.550 --> 02:27:55.790
And we came up with, you know,
kind of a testing scenario,

02:27:55.790 --> 02:27:57.900
and we've refined
it over the years.

02:27:57.900 --> 02:28:01.610
But, you know, I think
there's a lot of instances

02:28:01.610 --> 02:28:04.550
where there's a standard
thrown out there --

02:28:04.550 --> 02:28:09.930
like, okay, go implement it,
but it's really not that easy

02:28:09.930 --> 02:28:11.350
to implement, you know.

02:28:11.350 --> 02:28:14.970
And, you know, one vendor
might, you know, go in path A,

02:28:14.970 --> 02:28:17.670
and another vendor go in
path B, and, you know,

02:28:17.670 --> 02:28:19.490
there goes your interoperability
right there.

02:28:19.490 --> 02:28:24.000
So I think my answer to your
question is, is that there has

02:28:24.000 --> 02:28:28.670
to be some forum for software
companies to test their products

02:28:28.670 --> 02:28:30.250
in -- you know,

02:28:30.250 --> 02:28:33.260
a non-adversarial
forum, if you will.

02:28:33.260 --> 02:28:35.450
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
So we could go

02:28:35.450 --> 02:28:36.960
on a long time on this question.

02:28:36.960 --> 02:28:38.570
Are there any others?

02:28:38.570 --> 02:28:40.950
Is there one over there?

02:28:40.950 --> 02:28:43.060
Yep. You're hiding
behind the column.

02:28:43.060 --> 02:28:44.360
I see you.

02:28:44.360 --> 02:28:45.660
Okay.

02:28:45.660 --> 02:28:46.960
&gt;&gt; Okay. I -- Noemie, I
have a question for you.

02:28:46.960 --> 02:28:48.670
I'm sorry?

02:28:48.670 --> 02:28:50.200
Oh, I'm sorry, I'm
Kurt Helfric, again,

02:28:50.200 --> 02:28:51.860
from National Gallery of Art.

02:28:51.860 --> 02:28:54.440
So, Noemie, I just
wanted you -- a comment --

02:28:54.440 --> 02:28:57.560
something you told us struck me,
which was basically this idea

02:28:57.560 --> 02:29:00.540
that at a certain point, you
had thought about creating PDFs

02:29:00.540 --> 02:29:02.060
of some of the drawings.

02:29:02.060 --> 02:29:05.000
And could you just elaborate
a little bit more on that?

02:29:05.000 --> 02:29:10.190
In other words, were they --
they were actually PDFs of CAD,

02:29:10.190 --> 02:29:12.940
or sort of born-digital
materials.

02:29:12.940 --> 02:29:16.400
One of the things that Alex
Ball [assumed spelling] has done

02:29:16.400 --> 02:29:18.480
in his white paper
on CAD is to say,

02:29:18.480 --> 02:29:20.930
"You have to understand why
you're collecting things."

02:29:20.930 --> 02:29:23.840
So if you're collecting things
for image value, for instance,

02:29:23.840 --> 02:29:26.530
PDFs or TIFs are fine,
but if you're doing it

02:29:26.530 --> 02:29:28.100
for other things, then
you really need to think

02:29:28.100 --> 02:29:29.620
about the native formats.

02:29:29.620 --> 02:29:30.980
But I'm actually
really struck --

02:29:30.980 --> 02:29:35.150
I'd like to hear more about
what you found that was missing

02:29:35.150 --> 02:29:40.300
in those PDFs that
you're aware of.

02:29:40.300 --> 02:29:41.600
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:
If we go --

02:29:41.600 --> 02:29:45.890
if I try to explain it from
the -- doing it analog,

02:29:45.890 --> 02:29:48.390
we would have done
-- to go to a meeting

02:29:48.390 --> 02:29:50.270
and discuss different
alternatives,

02:29:50.270 --> 02:29:53.490
we would have sketched out
different things on trace paper.

02:29:53.490 --> 02:29:55.020
And we would have
different layers,

02:29:55.020 --> 02:29:58.370
and maybe we would have put
them on top of one another.

02:29:58.370 --> 02:30:01.770
And we would have, you know,
been able to remove one layer,

02:30:01.770 --> 02:30:04.260
change color, highlight
something, and whatnot.

02:30:04.260 --> 02:30:07.190
And then, if we were to send
that analog piece to Yale,

02:30:07.190 --> 02:30:10.200
we could just send
all of those layers,

02:30:10.200 --> 02:30:13.370
and that would have been
documenting that moment

02:30:13.370 --> 02:30:16.580
in the design process where
we were making decision

02:30:16.580 --> 02:30:19.350
about the size of the
berms, or height --

02:30:19.350 --> 02:30:21.260
I don't know, something.

02:30:21.260 --> 02:30:24.360
If we put this in digital,

02:30:24.360 --> 02:30:28.380
we would have done maybe the
same sort of exercise, you know,

02:30:28.380 --> 02:30:30.440
drawing in CAD those
different curves,

02:30:30.440 --> 02:30:32.750
and they would have been
on different layers.

02:30:32.750 --> 02:30:34.800
And when presenting them,
we would have shown --

02:30:34.800 --> 02:30:37.950
or maybe plotting them, we would
have shown them on different --

02:30:37.950 --> 02:30:39.950
you know, we would
have turned off layers,

02:30:39.950 --> 02:30:45.170
and just show certain image.

02:30:45.170 --> 02:30:48.770
But if we look at that
file 10 years later,

02:30:48.770 --> 02:30:54.090
and we try to plot it as a PDF,
because it was a turning point

02:30:54.090 --> 02:31:00.470
in internal -- at the office,
but in making design decision,

02:31:00.470 --> 02:31:02.140
with the layers history,

02:31:02.140 --> 02:31:05.140
nobody can really tell
us anything about it.

02:31:05.140 --> 02:31:09.750
The plot size -- everything
look like it's the same --

02:31:09.750 --> 02:31:12.960
I don't know, that
it's a planted area,

02:31:12.960 --> 02:31:15.990
or it was a water feature,
or whatever it was,

02:31:15.990 --> 02:31:17.430
everything is at the same level.

02:31:17.430 --> 02:31:21.180
You are losing this layering.

02:31:25.890 --> 02:31:27.190
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
Other questions?

02:31:27.190 --> 02:31:28.490
Oh, here's one.

02:31:28.490 --> 02:31:35.430
Katie has a question.

02:31:38.260 --> 02:31:40.040
&gt;&gt; Katie Pierce Meyer:
Hi, Katie Pierce Meyer.

02:31:40.040 --> 02:31:43.190
Not that this addresses that
question, but I'm wondering

02:31:43.190 --> 02:31:48.670
about how much any of you
might use screenshots as ways

02:31:48.670 --> 02:31:51.000
of capturing some
of those moments.

02:31:51.000 --> 02:31:54.560
And is that something
you would use as a way

02:31:54.560 --> 02:31:56.950
of sharing information on
a particular portion --

02:31:56.950 --> 02:31:59.390
or, you know, points
in a design process?

02:31:59.390 --> 02:32:02.500
And if you do, are those things
that you actually maintain

02:32:02.500 --> 02:32:05.520
as part of the archive
for a project?

02:32:07.040 --> 02:32:08.340
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: I'll take --

02:32:08.340 --> 02:32:10.790
so certainly, we use
screenshots, but they're not --

02:32:10.790 --> 02:32:14.940
I don't think they're typically
used for design discussions.

02:32:14.940 --> 02:32:17.130
They're usually more on the
technical side of things.

02:32:17.130 --> 02:32:20.630
So they're -- like, very
mundane explanatory things,

02:32:20.630 --> 02:32:23.170
like this is the wrong
color, or the wrong size,

02:32:23.170 --> 02:32:24.740
or something like that.

02:32:24.740 --> 02:32:28.350
I think this -- so they
certainly get used,

02:32:28.350 --> 02:32:31.450
and it would have to be part of
a sort of more defined process

02:32:31.450 --> 02:32:34.810
that people would follow
in our environment,

02:32:34.810 --> 02:32:39.650
which is nearly impossible
for me to get people to do.

02:32:39.650 --> 02:32:42.550
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: And there
was another question in the --

02:32:42.550 --> 02:32:45.650
yeah, the people who are
behind the column, I can't tell

02:32:45.650 --> 02:32:51.650
if you have your hands up.

02:32:51.650 --> 02:32:54.360
&gt;&gt; Following up a little
on Katie's question,

02:32:54.360 --> 02:32:59.030
I wonder whether, as you
work through these questions

02:32:59.030 --> 02:33:03.480
about archiving standard, and
the consideration is given

02:33:03.480 --> 02:33:11.250
to adding some narrative
component to the project record.

02:33:11.250 --> 02:33:16.500
In which participants
would be asked to describe

02:33:16.500 --> 02:33:21.610
or recount some of the
experiences of both creativity

02:33:21.610 --> 02:33:27.390
and collaboration that
were part of the process.

02:33:27.390 --> 02:33:29.510
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: So
she had mentioned earlier

02:33:29.510 --> 02:33:31.460
about doing the -- I
think it was you --

02:33:31.460 --> 02:33:32.910
the written narrative.

02:33:32.910 --> 02:33:35.870
So we -- so we've had
discussions internally

02:33:35.870 --> 02:33:38.590
about doing interview-based
processes --

02:33:38.590 --> 02:33:40.590
not actually for
archiving purposes,

02:33:40.590 --> 02:33:41.890
but for knowledge transfer.

02:33:41.890 --> 02:33:45.080
Because we have a
very similar problem

02:33:45.080 --> 02:33:48.630
where if it doesn't describe
well, you're not going to learn

02:33:48.630 --> 02:33:51.160
from it, and you can't move

02:33:51.160 --> 02:33:53.430
between projects,
and move information.

02:33:53.430 --> 02:33:58.760
So I think the tools
probably would be --

02:33:58.760 --> 02:34:01.960
that would be the mechanism
we would look to, and audio

02:34:01.960 --> 02:34:03.820
and video are much
simpler to use

02:34:03.820 --> 02:34:07.200
than having somebody write
something, or an e-mail.

02:34:07.200 --> 02:34:12.740
I think one of the sort of
pieces that we always struggle

02:34:12.740 --> 02:34:15.410
with is, okay, how do you
actually make an association

02:34:15.410 --> 02:34:20.700
of that simple recording to what
it's relevant to in the project?

02:34:20.700 --> 02:34:23.430
And you end up with, you know,
intranets and stuff that --

02:34:23.430 --> 02:34:27.920
oh, it's on there somewhere,
or -- and that's, again,

02:34:27.920 --> 02:34:30.380
another kind of interoperable
standard

02:34:30.380 --> 02:34:32.790
that no one has the same system.

02:34:32.790 --> 02:34:36.000
And so you upgrade systems,
and you lost a connectivity.

02:34:36.000 --> 02:34:38.340
I mean, one of the --
just as a quick aside,

02:34:38.340 --> 02:34:39.640
I once put together a list

02:34:39.640 --> 02:34:42.800
of all the stuff we don't have
standards for that makes sense

02:34:42.800 --> 02:34:45.390
for us, and it's,
like, 65 items long.

02:34:45.390 --> 02:34:48.010
Right? So, like,
just quick examples,

02:34:48.010 --> 02:34:51.420
what a 3D sketch looks like,
you know, photogrammetry.

02:34:51.420 --> 02:34:53.340
There are standards, but, like,

02:34:53.340 --> 02:34:56.370
the odds of a designer
knowing what an open format

02:34:56.370 --> 02:35:00.400
photogrammetry standard is,
I don't really even know.

02:35:00.400 --> 02:35:03.540
Point clouds, all these sort
of things -- so it's a --

02:35:03.540 --> 02:35:04.840
it's sort of a -- I don't know.

02:35:04.840 --> 02:35:06.920
I like to use the term,
"We need an internet,

02:35:06.920 --> 02:35:10.070
not more standards," that
if you think about it, like,

02:35:10.070 --> 02:35:12.170
the internet made
things connect better.

02:35:12.170 --> 02:35:13.470
We don't have that.

02:35:13.470 --> 02:35:15.050
We just have these
little piles of stuff.

02:35:15.050 --> 02:35:17.520
So, I mean, that's
my long-term view,

02:35:17.520 --> 02:35:23.420
how you make this more
simple, but I'll stop there.

