&gt;&gt; Well, my question --

02:35:31.320 --> 02:35:33.070
my question has to do
with this idea that --

02:35:33.070 --> 02:35:36.320
I mean, there's a range of you
up there from small design firms

02:35:36.320 --> 02:35:40.330
to large owners, and
different industries.

02:35:40.330 --> 02:35:44.630
And I'm wondering, you know,
the challenge of trying

02:35:44.630 --> 02:35:47.530
to collect information
and archive it --

02:35:47.530 --> 02:35:50.320
it's somewhat what you want
to do for your own practice,

02:35:50.320 --> 02:35:53.370
and it's also somewhat
driven by what your client

02:35:53.370 --> 02:35:55.580
or the owner wants to require.

02:35:55.580 --> 02:35:59.870
And if the owners are clearer
about what they need and want,

02:35:59.870 --> 02:36:01.300
is that going to sort out some

02:36:01.300 --> 02:36:03.010
of the problems for
the design world?

02:36:03.010 --> 02:36:07.580
And, you know, to some
extent, standards are important

02:36:07.580 --> 02:36:09.370
for things we want to preserve.

02:36:09.370 --> 02:36:11.760
They maybe help you with
the things you just want

02:36:11.760 --> 02:36:14.870
to have access to, but if
the owners were doing more

02:36:14.870 --> 02:36:19.800
to push standardization of the
information they want at the end

02:36:19.800 --> 02:36:22.790
of a project, would
that help sort this out?

02:36:22.790 --> 02:36:25.880
And maybe, is there any
experience from the PLM world

02:36:25.880 --> 02:36:28.040
that might shed some
light on that,

02:36:28.040 --> 02:36:30.930
for us in the architecture
and design world?

02:36:30.930 --> 02:36:32.420
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: Do
you want to take it, Nick?

02:36:32.420 --> 02:36:33.720
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: Sure.

02:36:33.720 --> 02:36:35.020
Yeah, I think on the
federal side, I mean,

02:36:35.020 --> 02:36:38.240
especially for our larger
projects, we have very,

02:36:38.240 --> 02:36:42.550
very detailed contracts
and then specifications

02:36:42.550 --> 02:36:44.230
that dictate deliverables.

02:36:44.230 --> 02:36:46.580
And I think, at the end of
the day, I mean, what we want

02:36:46.580 --> 02:36:49.730
to be able to do with our
projects is that, you know,

02:36:49.730 --> 02:36:51.120
the final deliverables
that are produced,

02:36:51.120 --> 02:36:54.070
either by the architects
of record

02:36:54.070 --> 02:36:56.510
or through an as-built
modification process

02:36:56.510 --> 02:36:58.870
by our contractor, is to
turn over a set of drawings,

02:36:58.870 --> 02:37:02.470
and specs, and O&amp;M manuals, et
cetera, that allow the building

02:37:02.470 --> 02:37:05.460
to continue to be run,
you know, going forward.

02:37:05.460 --> 02:37:08.340
I think where that does break
down a little bit is, you know,

02:37:08.340 --> 02:37:10.710
we have a pretty
good grasp on that

02:37:10.710 --> 02:37:13.670
for our larger projects
above $3 million.

02:37:13.670 --> 02:37:16.340
Projects under that, you
know, there's many more,

02:37:16.340 --> 02:37:19.000
in terms of volume, and those
are the projects where --

02:37:19.000 --> 02:37:20.890
you know, I mean,
it's $25,000 to build

02:37:20.890 --> 02:37:22.450
out a small space somewhere,

02:37:22.450 --> 02:37:24.330
and so how do you get
the smaller contractors

02:37:24.330 --> 02:37:26.960
that might be working on that
stuff to comply with some

02:37:26.960 --> 02:37:29.900
of the more complex requirements
of our bigger projects?

02:37:29.900 --> 02:37:33.790
And so working that out is,
you know, a struggle for us.

02:37:33.790 --> 02:37:35.090
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
So has anyone

02:37:35.090 --> 02:37:39.150
on the panel done a project
for the GSA, and what do you --

02:37:39.150 --> 02:37:43.270
is it just deliverables for
the GSA, Greg, or is it --

02:37:43.270 --> 02:37:46.500
you know, does it really help
you in the future go back?

02:37:46.500 --> 02:37:49.690
Of course, you can't use it,
because it's confidential,

02:37:49.690 --> 02:37:52.350
and for your eyes
only, and all of that.

02:37:52.350 --> 02:37:53.650
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: Well,

02:37:53.650 --> 02:37:55.020
so we've certainly
done GSA projects.

02:37:55.020 --> 02:37:59.310
We have examples where
we were a sub to a --

02:37:59.310 --> 02:38:01.750
in a party where none
of that information

02:38:01.750 --> 02:38:04.220
that we even produced got
handed over to the GSA,

02:38:04.220 --> 02:38:05.770
so that's one example.

02:38:05.770 --> 02:38:07.530
Even with re -- or using
models, and so forth.

02:38:07.530 --> 02:38:09.610
But I think, to Roger's
question,

02:38:09.610 --> 02:38:14.050
there's small areas during a --
and this is design-specific --

02:38:14.050 --> 02:38:16.110
small areas within
the design process

02:38:16.110 --> 02:38:20.770
that the standards can be
used from a practical sense.

02:38:20.770 --> 02:38:22.300
But most of the time,
I think they're seen

02:38:22.300 --> 02:38:25.110
as someone else's
problem, and so we can --

02:38:25.110 --> 02:38:28.210
I can meet your problem,
but I'm going to do --

02:38:28.210 --> 02:38:30.250
it's sort of an image
that came to my head.

02:38:30.250 --> 02:38:33.750
There's this TV show that they
ship things across the country,

02:38:33.750 --> 02:38:36.530
and it's a competition who
can get it there first.

02:38:36.530 --> 02:38:38.480
And they don't care
how you get it there.

02:38:38.480 --> 02:38:41.580
It just has to land there in
one piece, and that's sort

02:38:41.580 --> 02:38:42.880
of how our industry works,

02:38:42.880 --> 02:38:44.320
in that we don't really
have the standards

02:38:44.320 --> 02:38:45.620
about how you get there.

02:38:45.620 --> 02:38:47.820
We have the standards
about how it lands, right?

02:38:47.820 --> 02:38:50.450
And this is, I think,
the challenge.

02:38:50.450 --> 02:38:54.020
Like, it's not a -- it's
not that we can't deliver

02:38:54.020 --> 02:38:57.500
to a standard if needed to,
but it's not one that --

02:38:57.500 --> 02:39:00.630
the standards don't really
apply in the process part.

02:39:00.630 --> 02:39:02.760
They apply in the landing part.

02:39:02.760 --> 02:39:04.770
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: So it's
actually an addition step.

02:39:04.770 --> 02:39:06.690
So you say, okay, so
we have our stuff --

02:39:06.690 --> 02:39:08.650
&gt;&gt;Drive your business
question --

02:39:08.650 --> 02:39:11.310
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: Well, so I
think the specific thing is --

02:39:11.310 --> 02:39:14.440
from a technology perspective,
is there aren't tools

02:39:14.440 --> 02:39:19.170
that utilize standards that we
can leverage for our business.

02:39:19.170 --> 02:39:21.670
There are tools that
are historically seen

02:39:21.670 --> 02:39:26.290
as handover tools, and so
it's a very big discussion.

02:39:26.290 --> 02:39:30.130
But I think it's generally the
way I view things, that it's --

02:39:30.130 --> 02:39:33.000
there's motivation
to have a status quo

02:39:33.000 --> 02:39:35.090
of vendors provide tools
for certain workflow,

02:39:35.090 --> 02:39:39.730
and then open formats for
handover, and that's sort

02:39:39.730 --> 02:39:44.690
of at least how I
[inaudible], yeah.

02:39:44.690 --> 02:39:46.470
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander:
So, you know, I --

02:39:46.470 --> 02:39:50.790
your question is a great one,
because it sort of takes me back

02:39:50.790 --> 02:39:55.450
to imagining looking at an
owner-architect AIA agreement,

02:39:55.450 --> 02:39:58.620
and trying to use that
as a basis for explaining

02:39:58.620 --> 02:40:01.270
to a client what
is about to happen.

02:40:01.270 --> 02:40:03.800
And it's -- does not --

02:40:03.800 --> 02:40:07.650
you know, if you read the
description of schematic design

02:40:07.650 --> 02:40:13.910
in the AIA, it just basically
has a line about planning,

02:40:13.910 --> 02:40:17.030
and organization, and
maybe there's a narrative.

02:40:17.030 --> 02:40:18.330
What are you going to get?

02:40:18.330 --> 02:40:19.630
Meanwhile, books
have been written,

02:40:19.630 --> 02:40:22.220
or there have been
attempts made at explaining

02:40:22.220 --> 02:40:26.350
to a client what the
design process is like.

02:40:26.350 --> 02:40:28.480
But those descriptions
only work --

02:40:28.480 --> 02:40:31.020
are only about some
preconception.

02:40:31.020 --> 02:40:33.750
The AIA has a little film
about you and your architect,

02:40:33.750 --> 02:40:35.050
and what it could
be, but it's a --

02:40:35.050 --> 02:40:38.320
you know, about a really
pretty big building.

02:40:38.320 --> 02:40:40.070
And I would never
think about using

02:40:40.070 --> 02:40:42.380
that for a house renovation.

02:40:42.380 --> 02:40:48.020
So, you know, a great tool would
be probably for some group of us

02:40:48.020 --> 02:40:49.320
to figure out how

02:40:49.320 --> 02:40:51.580
to put together a
little introductory film

02:40:51.580 --> 02:40:54.340
about how the process
works, and that starts

02:40:54.340 --> 02:40:58.620
to adjust the behavior
of all the stakeholders,

02:40:58.620 --> 02:41:01.540
and particularly
explains who is in charge

02:41:01.540 --> 02:41:03.370
at each step, and
who to turn to.

02:41:03.370 --> 02:41:05.670
So --

02:41:11.530 --> 02:41:13.290
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
Please introduce yourself.

02:41:13.290 --> 02:41:16.120
&gt;&gt; Hi. So one of the things --

02:41:16.120 --> 02:41:17.420
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: You are?

02:41:17.420 --> 02:41:18.720
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: You are?

02:41:18.720 --> 02:41:20.020
&gt;&gt; What? Is it on?

02:41:20.020 --> 02:41:21.320
I --

02:41:21.320 --> 02:41:22.620
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: No, you.

02:41:22.620 --> 02:41:23.920
&gt;&gt; Phil Rocher: No, who are you?

02:41:23.920 --> 02:41:25.220
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: Who are you?

02:41:25.220 --> 02:41:26.520
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: What's
your name?

02:41:26.520 --> 02:41:27.820
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander:
What's your name?

02:41:27.820 --> 02:41:29.120
&gt;&gt; Oh, ha.

02:41:29.120 --> 02:41:30.420
I'm Karen Moran, and I'm
actually one of the people

02:41:30.420 --> 02:41:32.070
in partnership with Mark
Rylander, several occasions.

02:41:32.070 --> 02:41:36.990
One of the things that I've been
thinking about is how we are

02:41:36.990 --> 02:41:42.140
so far removed as architects
from the Thomas U. Walter era,

02:41:42.140 --> 02:41:46.400
where his office would've been
the repository of all the data,

02:41:46.400 --> 02:41:48.700
and that you could go
back to the office,

02:41:48.700 --> 02:41:50.000
and it would be there.

02:41:50.000 --> 02:41:53.930
Because once you start
talking about deliverables,

02:41:53.930 --> 02:41:57.620
and the deliverables are
required to be manipulated,

02:41:57.620 --> 02:42:02.280
how do we, as architects,
put our fingerprint on those?

02:42:02.280 --> 02:42:05.410
Because Ms. Leventhal brought
up that even within the office,

02:42:05.410 --> 02:42:07.590
it's hard to understand
the process

02:42:07.590 --> 02:42:10.340
by which these things
get developed.

02:42:10.340 --> 02:42:16.130
So once you release your
deliverable to the owner, and --

02:42:16.130 --> 02:42:18.820
I mean, if any architects
in the room remember,

02:42:18.820 --> 02:42:20.460
it was only a few years ago

02:42:20.460 --> 02:42:23.160
that we would never
release an original

02:42:23.160 --> 02:42:25.010
of any kind to an owner.

02:42:25.010 --> 02:42:29.220
We would release a print, and
that would be a reference.

02:42:29.220 --> 02:42:30.790
And now, we're being pressured

02:42:30.790 --> 02:42:34.820
to release manipulatable
[sic] drawings

02:42:34.820 --> 02:42:37.380
to owners for future use.

02:42:37.380 --> 02:42:41.150
Had we put a fingerprint on
it so that it can go back

02:42:41.150 --> 02:42:43.850
to the originator --
because when it comes

02:42:43.850 --> 02:42:46.770
to digital archiving, you know,

02:42:46.770 --> 02:42:50.950
Thomas U. Walter had a
cornerstone with his name on it.

02:42:50.950 --> 02:42:52.560
Do we now?

02:42:52.560 --> 02:42:54.660
Probably not, for the most part.

02:42:54.660 --> 02:42:57.240
People won't even remember
who the architect was.

02:42:57.240 --> 02:43:00.400
I doubt very many people
go to Boeing and say,

02:43:00.400 --> 02:43:03.760
"Could I have a manipulatable
[sic] drawing of my B52?

02:43:03.760 --> 02:43:07.880
Because I want to screw
around with it in the future."

02:43:07.880 --> 02:43:09.180
I don't think so.

02:43:09.180 --> 02:43:10.850
That doesn't happen,
but people want to do

02:43:10.850 --> 02:43:13.010
that with buildings
all the time.

02:43:13.010 --> 02:43:18.910
So how do we actually document
what was meant to be documented

02:43:18.910 --> 02:43:24.430
in the first place, and how do
we keep that for perpetuity?

02:43:25.540 --> 02:43:26.840
&gt;&gt; Mark Rylander: Read-only.

02:43:26.840 --> 02:43:29.140
Read-only.

02:43:29.140 --> 02:43:30.440
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
Probably the person

02:43:30.440 --> 02:43:32.230
who might have some
thoughts on that is Greg,

02:43:32.230 --> 02:43:33.530
I mean, to some extent.

02:43:33.530 --> 02:43:34.830
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: Well,
I mean, I've thought

02:43:34.830 --> 02:43:37.490
about these problems, but, like,
the actual solutions is not,

02:43:37.490 --> 02:43:40.580
like, something I could --
like, Blockchain, right?

02:43:40.580 --> 02:43:42.530
That's how you solve all
problems today, right now,

02:43:42.530 --> 02:43:44.310
is just to say Blockchain.

02:43:44.310 --> 02:43:47.760
But, I mean, this is -- this
is a realistic interpretation

02:43:47.760 --> 02:43:49.060
of this problem, right?

02:43:49.060 --> 02:43:52.390
You have to have a ledger of
all these things that happen,

02:43:52.390 --> 02:43:54.560
and that's the promise
of these technologies.

02:43:54.560 --> 02:43:57.530
I think what we find is
they're not easily implementable

02:43:57.530 --> 02:44:02.870
in our industry, because one of
the -- even to hear Nick talk,

02:44:02.870 --> 02:44:04.170
we actually don't have owners.

02:44:04.170 --> 02:44:06.530
And when I'm saying owners,
I'm saying process owners.

02:44:06.530 --> 02:44:08.100
We're not building owners.

02:44:08.100 --> 02:44:09.520
No one owns a process.

02:44:09.520 --> 02:44:11.420
We all owned a little
piece of it.

02:44:11.420 --> 02:44:15.780
And so, you know, from a,
you know, pie-in-the-sky,

02:44:15.780 --> 02:44:17.820
if you look at what
the internet tells you,

02:44:17.820 --> 02:44:19.290
that's definitely the
way we need to go.

02:44:19.290 --> 02:44:21.520
How we get there, I
have no idea right now.

02:44:21.520 --> 02:44:24.690
So, I mean --

02:44:24.690 --> 02:44:26.820
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: Maybe
Phil could talk a little bit

02:44:26.820 --> 02:44:30.710
about the whole configuration
management,

02:44:30.710 --> 02:44:34.420
product management issue in
aerospace, and how it's sort

02:44:34.420 --> 02:44:37.150
of handled, at a high level.

02:44:38.870 --> 02:44:40.180
&gt;&gt; Phil Rocher: Well,
you had said something

02:44:40.180 --> 02:44:46.210
about that we don't give the
B52 CAD model to the Air Force,

02:44:46.210 --> 02:44:48.350
but -- because there isn't one.

02:44:48.350 --> 02:44:53.220
But anyway, I -- what -- I'm
going to address that first.

02:44:53.220 --> 02:44:57.220
Actually, I do see
the DOD requesting --

02:44:57.220 --> 02:45:02.460
not an entire weapons system
per se, but, you know,

02:45:02.460 --> 02:45:06.540
give me the wings on
the A7, because I want

02:45:06.540 --> 02:45:08.880
to reengineer them, or I want

02:45:08.880 --> 02:45:10.720
to have somebody
else reengineer them.

02:45:10.720 --> 02:45:12.810
So I do see that quite
a bit these days.

02:45:12.810 --> 02:45:19.700
The other part of that question
kind of had to do with --

02:45:19.700 --> 02:45:22.680
I think it had to do with
traceability, if you will,

02:45:22.680 --> 02:45:24.970
or at least that's what
I'm going to call it.

02:45:24.970 --> 02:45:31.200
But in the aerospace industry,
they're very religious about,

02:45:31.200 --> 02:45:35.990
you know, if the lefthand
bracket is your design,

02:45:35.990 --> 02:45:39.540
it is associated with you

02:45:39.540 --> 02:45:41.830
and the organization
for which you work.

02:45:41.830 --> 02:45:46.030
So if there's a question about
that lefthand bracket, you know,

02:45:46.030 --> 02:45:47.440
some number of years
down the road,

02:45:47.440 --> 02:45:50.910
they do indeed know
who designed it.

02:45:50.910 --> 02:45:54.010
But, you know, whether he's with
the company anymore, you know,

02:45:54.010 --> 02:45:56.980
that's a different story, and
that's out of our control.

02:45:56.980 --> 02:45:58.600
So --

02:45:58.600 --> 02:46:01.260
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
But how do you do that?

02:46:01.260 --> 02:46:02.560
&gt;&gt; That you --

02:46:02.560 --> 02:46:03.860
&gt;&gt; Phil Rocher: How
do you do what?

02:46:03.860 --> 02:46:05.160
&gt;&gt; The information --

02:46:05.160 --> 02:46:06.460
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: How do you
keep track of that information?

02:46:06.460 --> 02:46:09.320
&gt;&gt; Phil Rocher: Our data
model supports that.

02:46:09.320 --> 02:46:13.630
It's -- the entities are
called person and organization.

02:46:13.630 --> 02:46:14.930
It's --

02:46:14.930 --> 02:46:17.760
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: The IFC
data model supports ownership --

02:46:17.760 --> 02:46:19.060
yeah, creative -- yeah.

02:46:19.060 --> 02:46:20.980
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: But I think
-- I mean, from in your --

02:46:20.980 --> 02:46:23.270
like, let's say I'm
going to design a plane.

02:46:23.270 --> 02:46:24.700
Like, let's say I do
something smaller.

02:46:24.700 --> 02:46:27.060
I want to do a single-engine
prop plane.

02:46:27.060 --> 02:46:30.650
If I have a supply chain,
I set up a PLM platform

02:46:30.650 --> 02:46:31.950
that everybody connects to,

02:46:31.950 --> 02:46:33.680
and then that's how you
put it together, right?

02:46:33.680 --> 02:46:35.330
I mean, that's -- I
think that's the --

02:46:35.330 --> 02:46:38.130
sort of the root of your
question, that people point

02:46:38.130 --> 02:46:41.390
to that PLM system, or
platforms, and stuff like that

02:46:41.390 --> 02:46:42.720
as a way we could
solve our industry.

02:46:42.720 --> 02:46:45.030
But it -- okay, who hosts it?

02:46:45.030 --> 02:46:47.610
Who maintains it,
like in our industry?

02:46:47.610 --> 02:46:51.000
It's -- so, like, okay, who
pays the rent on the system

02:46:51.000 --> 02:46:52.300
after the project's done?

02:46:52.300 --> 02:46:53.600
&gt;&gt; Phil Rocher: Yeah.

02:46:53.600 --> 02:46:56.690
And in our case, it's Cessna,
and Gulfstream, and Embraer,

02:46:56.690 --> 02:46:59.240
ad infinitum, whoever
the company is.

02:46:59.240 --> 02:47:00.540
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: Yeah.

02:47:00.540 --> 02:47:02.610
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: But it's
interesting, in the IFC model.

02:47:02.610 --> 02:47:05.620
Because we did a bunch of what
are called the experimental BIMs

02:47:05.620 --> 02:47:09.260
for the Corps of Engineers,
and I would go to a trade show

02:47:09.260 --> 02:47:13.510
and see some company 20
steps removed from us,

02:47:13.510 --> 02:47:15.440
and they'd be showing
something they did

02:47:15.440 --> 02:47:16.740
with these experimental models.

02:47:16.740 --> 02:47:19.090
And I'd look at it, and if
you looked at created by,

