&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon: Nick?

02:48:14.310 --> 02:48:16.340
&gt;&gt; Nick Gicale: I mean, I
think in terms of BIM usage,

02:48:16.340 --> 02:48:19.260
GSA has been kind of
pushing that since I've been

02:48:19.260 --> 02:48:22.480
at the agency, since 2003.

02:48:22.480 --> 02:48:27.360
So, you know, today, at least
for our projects that are

02:48:27.360 --> 02:48:29.920
above $3 million, every one of
those projects has some type

02:48:29.920 --> 02:48:31.490
of BIM usage on that project,

02:48:31.490 --> 02:48:33.290
whether it's spatial data
modeling, or whether it's,

02:48:33.290 --> 02:48:35.650
you know, something more
involved, in terms of taking

02:48:35.650 --> 02:48:37.530
that model through design.

02:48:37.530 --> 02:48:41.130
I guess in terms of, though,
the idea of making sure

02:48:41.130 --> 02:48:45.900
that the architect or designer
is always attached to the work

02:48:45.900 --> 02:48:48.260
that they did, I think we
probably could do better

02:48:48.260 --> 02:48:49.560
in that area.

02:48:49.560 --> 02:48:52.510
We definitely do that for
equipment that we install.

02:48:52.510 --> 02:48:55.350
We always know who made
the faulty equipment

02:48:55.350 --> 02:48:57.150
that we now have to take
out of the building.

02:48:57.150 --> 02:49:00.410
But for, you know, the
renovations and stuff like that,

02:49:00.410 --> 02:49:02.950
you know, if you're not doing a
new building, I think over time,

02:49:02.950 --> 02:49:06.650
kind of that tracking of
who did what does get lost.

02:49:07.860 --> 02:49:10.850
&gt;&gt; Got one back there.

02:49:10.850 --> 02:49:12.150
&gt;&gt; Hi, Stacy Baez
[assumed spelling]

02:49:12.150 --> 02:49:13.830
with the Architect
of the Capitol.

02:49:13.830 --> 02:49:15.680
This kind of goes
on with my thought,

02:49:15.680 --> 02:49:18.540
because the defense industry
has in fact driven, like,

02:49:18.540 --> 02:49:19.870
records management requirements,

02:49:19.870 --> 02:49:23.640
and the space industry has
driven what we now know

02:49:23.640 --> 02:49:25.530
as the OAIS standard.

02:49:25.530 --> 02:49:29.110
Do you see the opportunity,
or is that, in fact,

02:49:29.110 --> 02:49:33.170
desirable for the AED
community to be able to drive --

02:49:33.170 --> 02:49:35.920
like, this is our
requirement, and if you want

02:49:35.920 --> 02:49:39.890
to sell us a system that is
compliant, maybe a [inaudible]

02:49:39.890 --> 02:49:46.250
or something, it must be
able to conform the data

02:49:46.250 --> 02:49:48.110
for the purpose of archiving?

02:49:48.110 --> 02:49:50.770
Because right now, what we're
faced with is, like, okay,

02:49:50.770 --> 02:49:53.660
we wrap up a project
in a massive system

02:49:53.660 --> 02:49:56.310
that a contractor has
used, and then it's like,

02:49:56.310 --> 02:49:57.750
okay, here's your zip file.

02:49:57.750 --> 02:50:01.660
You know, here are your CDs with
all the data, and it's very raw,

02:50:01.660 --> 02:50:04.630
and then the challenges of
trying to do the verification

02:50:04.630 --> 02:50:06.350
and all on the archival side.

02:50:06.350 --> 02:50:10.650
But do you see if there's an
opportunity for our industry

02:50:10.650 --> 02:50:13.860
to drive that -- the
softwares [sic] --

02:50:13.860 --> 02:50:17.230
especially the preeminent
software companies are adding

02:50:17.230 --> 02:50:23.150
modules in to their software
packages that create, you know,

02:50:23.150 --> 02:50:25.910
the archival packages that the
archivists are going to need

02:50:25.910 --> 02:50:28.310
to be able to have some
kind of reliability

02:50:28.310 --> 02:50:32.110
that we can preserve the
formats that were created.

02:50:34.060 --> 02:50:35.360
Greg Schleusner: I would say --

02:50:35.360 --> 02:50:38.200
so one of the things
that you find in a lot

02:50:38.200 --> 02:50:39.500
of client requirements is --

02:50:39.500 --> 02:50:44.580
we're good at doing what
we know can be tested --

02:50:44.580 --> 02:50:48.570
be extremely, you know,
sort of blunt about it.

02:50:48.570 --> 02:50:51.300
So if the client has a very
good standard, and they're going

02:50:51.300 --> 02:50:53.860
to test that we're delivering
to it, we can deliver to it.

02:50:53.860 --> 02:50:55.330
But the second it says --

02:50:55.330 --> 02:50:58.330
you know, someone in the meeting
says, "Eh, not a big deal,"

02:50:58.330 --> 02:50:59.790
well, it's not a big
deal to us anymore.

02:50:59.790 --> 02:51:01.250
And so one of the
things that I think --

02:51:01.250 --> 02:51:05.890
that comes with standards
is the ability

02:51:05.890 --> 02:51:07.820
to make sure you're
receiving them, right?

02:51:07.820 --> 02:51:11.560
And part of the -- I think
from a technology standpoint,

02:51:11.560 --> 02:51:13.360
the standards that exist
today could be delivered

02:51:13.360 --> 02:51:15.070
on on every project.

02:51:15.070 --> 02:51:16.560
I don't think that's a question.

02:51:16.560 --> 02:51:19.590
It's actually just a
will to enforce them

02:51:19.590 --> 02:51:24.020
that is a much more difficult
one, because it actually --

02:51:24.020 --> 02:51:25.320
you could look at
it in two ways.

02:51:25.320 --> 02:51:27.260
There are technologies that
make it easy to enforce,

02:51:27.260 --> 02:51:30.640
or there are -- you either
have the staff to enforce them.

02:51:30.640 --> 02:51:34.680
And no one has that money lying
around until somebody sees it

02:51:34.680 --> 02:51:36.520
as a business model to enforce.

02:51:36.520 --> 02:51:41.250
From a technology perspective,
it's at least how I see it,

02:51:41.250 --> 02:51:43.410
that we won't get
better at delivering it.

02:51:43.410 --> 02:51:45.900
I think that's from a
handover standpoint.

02:51:45.900 --> 02:51:47.200
&gt;&gt; Kristine Fallon:
Yeah, I was talking

02:51:47.200 --> 02:51:49.290
to a BIM manager
at a contractor.

02:51:49.290 --> 02:51:53.150
He said, "So, you know, when
the VA comes out with, you know,

02:51:53.150 --> 02:51:55.860
you're going to deliver this
based on our BIM standard,

02:51:55.860 --> 02:51:59.080
before we bid, I got to call
them and kind of feel them out,

02:51:59.080 --> 02:52:01.220
and figure out whether they
know what they're asking for.

02:52:01.220 --> 02:52:03.420
And if they don't, we
figure we won't do it,

02:52:03.420 --> 02:52:04.720
and we don't charge them for it.

02:52:04.720 --> 02:52:07.000
If they do, then we
figure we have to do it,

02:52:07.000 --> 02:52:08.300
and we charge them for it."

02:52:08.300 --> 02:52:11.080
So that's -- I mean,
that's really the rationale

02:52:11.080 --> 02:52:13.300
that people use, and,
you know, when we --

02:52:13.300 --> 02:52:15.710
yeah, I mean, we've built
validators and things,

02:52:15.710 --> 02:52:17.740
so the clients can know they're
getting what they wanted,

02:52:17.740 --> 02:52:20.040
but yeah.

02:52:23.390 --> 02:52:25.360
&gt;&gt; Kimon Onuma, Onuma Inc.

02:52:25.360 --> 02:52:27.770
One thought here, as
far as the ownership,

02:52:27.770 --> 02:52:30.790
and how do we track
ownership of information.

02:52:30.790 --> 02:52:33.300
I think we're still stuck --
if you look at this morning,

02:52:33.300 --> 02:52:36.130
with the talk about --
we used to even be bound

02:52:36.130 --> 02:52:37.710
to the hardware that we used.

02:52:37.710 --> 02:52:40.810
The applications used to be
bound to that and fused to it.

02:52:40.810 --> 02:52:43.300
In many ways, we're
still bound with our data

02:52:43.300 --> 02:52:45.690
to the applications that we use,
and the software that we use.

02:52:45.690 --> 02:52:47.750
But if we look at a
transaction-based thing

02:52:47.750 --> 02:52:49.190
that we can track
the transaction,

02:52:49.190 --> 02:52:50.670
you can actually
track ownership,

02:52:50.670 --> 02:52:53.070
and it's actually staring us
right on the screen right there.

02:52:53.070 --> 02:52:57.130
So when we tweet to the
hashtag there, it actually says

02:52:57.130 --> 02:53:00.330
where we are, and we post that
location, that information

02:53:00.330 --> 02:53:03.920
about what we're seeing in
this room, which can be traced

02:53:03.920 --> 02:53:05.220
in many different
-- you can search it

02:53:05.220 --> 02:53:06.520
on Google, all kinds of stuff.

02:53:06.520 --> 02:53:07.820
So the technology's
already there.

02:53:07.820 --> 02:53:09.210
I would encourage
us to look in terms

02:53:09.210 --> 02:53:11.660
of how do we track information,

02:53:11.660 --> 02:53:15.600
and look in a more
transactional-based way

02:53:15.600 --> 02:53:16.900
to look at it.

02:53:16.900 --> 02:53:18.200
And then you can start
identifying ownership.

02:53:18.200 --> 02:53:19.630
It goes back to Blockchain,
and a lot of other things.

02:53:19.630 --> 02:53:21.310
Obviously, we're not going
to get there overnight,

02:53:21.310 --> 02:53:22.860
but if we think in those terms,

02:53:22.860 --> 02:53:25.420
I think we could
get there faster.

