02:58:44.810 --> 02:58:48.130
with another firm, you're able
to decide on what standards work

02:58:48.130 --> 02:58:49.950
for you, and develop that.

02:58:49.950 --> 02:58:52.130
But even within Sasaki,
we have conversations

02:58:52.130 --> 02:58:54.350
about how can landscape
architects better communicate

02:58:54.350 --> 02:58:56.320
with architects, and
how does that work

02:58:56.320 --> 02:58:58.960
with a planning project on
top of that kind of thing.

02:58:58.960 --> 02:59:02.160
And so I wonder if you can
explore that a little bit,

02:59:02.160 --> 02:59:04.260
because as experts who already
have the learning curve covered,

02:59:04.260 --> 02:59:07.020
it would be great to know
what are the struggle,

02:59:07.020 --> 02:59:08.560
pain points that you
experience looking

02:59:08.560 --> 02:59:10.450
at a different discipline's
files,

02:59:10.450 --> 02:59:12.810
and trying to integrate
them into your own.

02:59:12.810 --> 02:59:15.010
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: I
feel for you more than me,

02:59:15.010 --> 02:59:16.730
because you probably get
the short end of the stick,

02:59:16.730 --> 02:59:19.530
so I'll let you go first.

02:59:19.530 --> 02:59:23.190
&gt;&gt; Noemie Lafaurie-Debany:
We don't do BIM.

02:59:23.190 --> 02:59:26.520
We provide CAD drawing
for the architects

02:59:26.520 --> 02:59:32.730
to then plug into their set.

02:59:32.730 --> 02:59:40.160
We -- in -- this is getting
out of BIM for a little bit,

02:59:40.160 --> 02:59:45.520
but in different --
visualization is very important

02:59:45.520 --> 02:59:50.020
in landscape, and in
speaking with architects

02:59:50.020 --> 02:59:55.790
or other consultant on
the team, and the client,

02:59:55.790 --> 02:59:59.080
a landscape is something
that changes all the time.

02:59:59.080 --> 03:00:00.720
So it's very hard to present.

03:00:00.720 --> 03:00:03.770
It's not an AutoCAD
block or anything

03:00:03.770 --> 03:00:09.170
that would truly represent
what you are designing.

03:00:09.170 --> 03:00:12.460
So we've experienced
with different software.

03:00:12.460 --> 03:00:15.550
At the moment, we are
using Lumion in order

03:00:15.550 --> 03:00:21.560
to very quickly create a
visualization of trees,

03:00:21.560 --> 03:00:26.060
and grasses, and shrubs.

03:00:26.060 --> 03:00:30.020
No architect we're working with
are using Lumion at the moment,

03:00:30.020 --> 03:00:33.980
so that means that we
need to take their model,

03:00:33.980 --> 03:00:37.480
clean it up in Rhino,
then put it in Lumion.

03:00:37.480 --> 03:00:42.750
In Lumion, we design
the landscape in 3D,

03:00:42.750 --> 03:00:47.620
and that's [inaudible] to
create the image of the design.

03:00:47.620 --> 03:00:51.000
We cannot give that Lumion
model to the architect to figure

03:00:51.000 --> 03:00:53.380
out what the planting
plan would be.

03:00:53.380 --> 03:00:55.900
We need to go back to
AutoCAD and then draw --

03:00:55.900 --> 03:01:01.210
so there is a lot of sort of
dead end in a ways that we need

03:01:01.210 --> 03:01:03.050
to go to in order for
the design to process.

03:01:03.050 --> 03:01:07.670
But for communicating
with other consultants,

03:01:07.670 --> 03:01:10.920
we need go back to CAD.

03:01:10.920 --> 03:01:14.630
That's how we -- where we
are stuck at the moment.

03:01:16.270 --> 03:01:18.080
&gt;&gt; Greg Schleusner: Aliza,
this particular problem,

03:01:18.080 --> 03:01:21.910
we've actually -- so the game
world is actually quite open,

03:01:21.910 --> 03:01:23.680
and Lumion is like
a game engine.

03:01:23.680 --> 03:01:25.840
It's -- we've actually
started to do things

03:01:25.840 --> 03:01:29.670
where we move towards the game
engine tools, and tools built

03:01:29.670 --> 03:01:32.330
on top of game engines, so
we can always get access

03:01:32.330 --> 03:01:35.850
to the source code and extract
the tree location, if you will,

03:01:35.850 --> 03:01:37.740
in the future, versus
having these dead ends.

03:01:37.740 --> 03:01:40.970
But these are, you know,
specialists that, you know --

03:01:40.970 --> 03:01:43.280
finding a game developer
that'll work

03:01:43.280 --> 03:01:47.550
for an architecture salary is
very hard, those sort of things.

03:01:47.550 --> 03:01:52.080
But, I mean, those are the
places that -- we're a big firm.

03:01:52.080 --> 03:01:55.000
We can try to explore, but
they're not sustainable,

03:01:55.000 --> 03:01:57.710
and these dead ends
exist everywhere.

03:01:57.710 --> 03:02:01.280
I think on the building side,
working with partners, it's --

03:02:01.280 --> 03:02:02.850
you know, everybody knows
what the problems are

03:02:02.850 --> 03:02:04.460
if you're using certain
BIM platforms.

03:02:04.460 --> 03:02:05.760
Oh, we have to do this.

03:02:05.760 --> 03:02:08.950
Everybody has the same issues,
where we can't track changes,

03:02:08.950 --> 03:02:10.930
and things -- I have
to get an e-mail

03:02:10.930 --> 03:02:13.430
that says what's changed,
those sort of things.

03:02:13.430 --> 03:02:14.950
I don't know.

03:02:14.950 --> 03:02:17.270
It's a systemic problem.

03:02:17.270 --> 03:02:20.450
It's not unique to us, though.

03:02:20.450 --> 03:02:25.510
&gt;&gt; Okay, so thank you.

